t": "\u2192\u200eSingles:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conan_Gray"}
{"title_page": "Kanslergade Agreement", "text_new": "{{Expand Danish|topic=politics|date=July 2019}}\n\n[[File:Ove Rodes Plads 10.JPG|thumb|right|225px|The building on Kanslergade where Stauning's apartment is located (photo 2016).]]\n\nThe '''Kanslergade Agreement''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0\u00e6n\u02c0sl\u0250\u02cck\u025b\u02d0\u00f0\u0259|IPA}}; {{lang-da|Kanslergadeforliget}}) was a 1933 political agreement in Denmark, which laid the foundation for the Danish [[welfare state]]. It was enacted by the government of [[Prime Minister of Denmark|prime minister]] [[Thorvald Stauning]], with [[Ministry of Social Affairs (Denmark)|social minister]] [[Karl Kristian Steincke|K.K. Steincke]] being its chief architect. The Kanslergade Agreement was negotiated in Stauning's apartment on [[:da:Kanslergade|Kanslergade]] in Copenhagen, from which it takes its name.\n\nThe agreement was reached by [[Stauning II Cabinet|Stauning's government]], consisting of his own [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democratic Party]] and their coalition partner the [[Danish Social Liberal Party|Social Liberal Party]], as well as the main opposition party the [[Venstre (Denmark)|Liberal Party]], on 30 January 1933. The two governing parties held a narrow majority of 76 out of 149 seats in [[Folketing]]et (the lower house of [[Rigsdagen]]). However, they only had 34 out of 76 seats in [[Landstinget]] (the upper house of Rigsdagen), and thus needed the support of the Liberals, who held 27 seats in Landstinget.\n\nThe Kanslergade Agreement set in motion the reforms that would establish the [[Nordic model]] for state welfare services in Denmark. It expanded [[labor rights]], [[Devaluation|devalued]] the [[Danish krone|krone]], and extended [[Agricultural subsidy|state subsidies to farmers]]. Charges for social services were also fixed to affordable levels. As part of the agreement, the Liberal Party withdrew its objections to the social welfare model advocated by the government. The agreement was, at the time, the most extensive agreement yet in Danish politics, with the possible exception of the 1894 budget agreement.<ref>Skou, Kaare R. (2005). ''Dansk politik A-\u00c5'' {{in lang|da}}. Aschehoug, pp. 367-68. {{ISBN|87-11-11652-8}}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*The most recent elections before the Kanslergade Agreement:\n**[[1932 Danish Folketing election]]\n**[[1932 Danish Landsting election]]\n*[[History of Denmark#1901\u20131939]]\n*[[Labor rights]]\n*[[Stauning II Cabinet]]\n*[[Stauning or Chaos]]\n*[[Welfare state]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*Rerup, Lorenz (2007-04-30). [http://www.denmark.dk/en/menu/AboutDenmark/History/The+Period19002000/192940EconomicCrisisAndPoliticalStability/PoliticalExtremismAndEmergencyAgreements/ ''Political extremism & emergency agreements'']. Gyldendal Leksikon. Retrieved on 2007-12-03.\n\n[[Category:1933 in politics]]\n[[Category:1933 in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Political history of Denmark]]\n\n{{Denmark-hist-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Danish|topic=politics|date=July 2019}}\n\n[[File:Ove Rodes Plads 10.JPG|thumb|right|225px|The building on Kanslergade where Stauning's apartment is located (photo 2016).]]\n\nThe '''Kanslergade Agreement''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0\u00e6n\u02c0sl\u0250\u02cck\u00e6\u02d0\u00f0\u0259|IPA}}; {{lang-da|Kanslergadeforliget}}) was a 1933 political agreement in Denmark, which laid the foundation for the Danish [[welfare state]]. It was enacted by the government of [[Prime Minister of Denmark|prime minister]] [[Thorvald Stauning]], with [[Ministry of Social Affairs (Denmark)|social minister]] [[Karl Kristian Steincke|K.K. Steincke]] being its chief architect. The Kanslergade Agreement was negotiated in Stauning's apartment on [[:da:Kanslergade|Kanslergade]] in Copenhagen, from which it takes its name.\n\nThe agreement was reached by [[Stauning II Cabinet|Stauning's government]], consisting of his own [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democratic Party]] and their coalition partner the [[Danish Social Liberal Party|Social Liberal Party]], as well as the main opposition party the [[Venstre (Denmark)|Liberal Party]], on 30 January 1933. The two governing parties held a narrow majority of 76 out of 149 seats in [[Folketing]]et (the lower house of [[Rigsdagen]]). However, they only had 34 out of 76 seats in [[Landstinget]] (the upper house of Rigsdagen), and thus needed the support of the Liberals, who held 27 seats in Landstinget.\n\nThe Kanslergade Agreement set in motion the reforms that would establish the [[Nordic model]] for state welfare services in Denmark. It expanded [[labor rights]], [[Devaluation|devalued]] the [[Danish krone|krone]], and extended [[Agricultural subsidy|state subsidies to farmers]]. Charges for social services were also fixed to affordable levels. As part of the agreement, the Liberal Party withdrew its objections to the social welfare model advocated by the government. The agreement was, at the time, the most extensive agreement yet in Danish politics, with the possible exception of the 1894 budget agreement.<ref>Skou, Kaare R. (2005). ''Dansk politik A-\u00c5'' {{in lang|da}}. Aschehoug, pp. 367-68. {{ISBN|87-11-11652-8}}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*The most recent elections before the Kanslergade Agreement:\n**[[1932 Danish Folketing election]]\n**[[1932 Danish Landsting election]]\n*[[History of Denmark#1901\u20131939]]\n*[[Labor rights]]\n*[[Stauning II Cabinet]]\n*[[Stauning or Chaos]]\n*[[Welfare state]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*Rerup, Lorenz (2007-04-30). [http://www.denmark.dk/en/menu/AboutDenmark/History/The+Period19002000/192940EconomicCrisisAndPoliticalStability/PoliticalExtremismAndEmergencyAgreements/ ''Political extremism & emergency agreements'']. Gyldendal Leksikon. Retrieved on 2007-12-03.\n\n[[Category:1933 in politics]]\n[[Category:1933 in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Political history of Denmark]]\n\n{{Denmark-hist-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kanslergade_Agreement"}
{"title_page": "Presidency of Ronald Reagan", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|Period of the United States government}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n{{for timeline}}\n{{Infobox administration\n| image = Official Portrait of President Reagan 1981.jpg\n| name = Presidency of Ronald Reagan\n| term_start = January 20, 1981\n| term_end = January 20, 1989\n| president = Ronald Reagan\n| president_link = President of the United States\n| cabinet = ''[[#Administration|See list]]''\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| election = [[1980 United States presidential election|1980]], [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]]\n| seat = [[White House]]\n| predecessor = [[Presidency of Jimmy Carter|Jimmy Carter]]\n| successor = [[Presidency of George H. W. Bush|George H. W. Bush]]\n| seal = Seal of the President of the United States.svg\n| seal_caption = Seal of the President\n| library_url = https://www.reaganlibrary.gov/\n}}\n{{Ronald Reagan series}}\nThe '''presidency of Ronald Reagan''' began at noon [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] on January 20, 1981, when [[Ronald Reagan]] was [[First inauguration of Ronald Reagan|inaugurated]] as the [[List of Presidents of the United States|40th]] [[President of the United States]], and ended on January 20, 1989. Reagan, a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] from [[California]], took office following a landslide victory over [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[incumbent]] President [[Jimmy Carter]] in the [[1980 United States presidential election|1980 presidential election]]. Reagan was succeeded by his Vice President, [[George H. W. Bush]], who won the [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential election]] with Reagan's support. Reagan's 1980 election resulted from a dramatic [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative shift to the right]] in American politics, including a loss of confidence in [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]], [[New Deal]], and [[Great Society]] programs and priorities that had dominated the national agenda since the 1930s.\n\nDomestically, the Reagan administration enacted a [[Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981|major tax cut]], sought to cut non-military spending, and eliminated federal regulations. The administration's economic policies, known as \"[[Reaganomics]]\", were inspired by [[supply-side economics]]. The combination of tax cuts and an increase in defense spending led to budget deficits, and the [[National debt of the United States|federal debt]] increased significantly during Reagan's tenure. Reagan signed the [[Tax Reform Act of 1986]] (which simplified the tax code by reducing rates and removing several tax breaks) and the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986]] (which enacted sweeping changes to U.S. immigration law and granted amnesty to three million [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants]]). Reagan also appointed more [[Federal judiciary of the United States|federal judges]] than any other president, including four [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justices.\n\nReagan's [[Foreign policy of the Ronald Reagan administration|foreign policy]] stance was resolutely [[anti-communism|anti-communist]]; its plan of action, known as the [[Reagan Doctrine]], sought to [[rollback|roll back]] the global influence of the [[Soviet Union]] in an attempt to end the Cold War. Under this doctrine, the Reagan administration initiated a massive buildup of the United States military; promoted new technologies such as missile defense systems; and, in 1983, undertook an [[invasion of Grenada]], the first major overseas action by U.S. troops since the end of the [[Vietnam War]]. The administration also created controversy by granting [[United States and state-sponsored terrorism|aid to paramilitary forces]] seeking to overthrow leftist governments, particularly in war-torn [[Central America]] and [[Afghanistan]]. Specifically, the Reagan administration engaged in covert arms sales to [[Iran]] to fund [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in Nicaragua that were fighting to overthrow their nation's socialist government; the resulting [[Iran\u2013Contra affair|scandal]] led to the conviction or resignation of several administration officials. During Reagan's second term, he sought closer relations with Soviet leader [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], and the two leaders signed a major [[arms control]] agreement known as the [[Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty|INF Treaty]].\n\nLeaving office in 1989, Reagan held an approval rating of 68%. This rating matches the approval ratings of [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[Bill Clinton]] as the highest rating for a departing president in the modern era.<ref>{{cite web|title = A Look Back At The Polls|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/news/a-look-back-at-the-polls/|publisher = CBS News|access-date = May 15, 2015}}</ref> Historians and political scientists generally [[Historical rankings of presidents of the United States|rank]] Reagan as an above-average president. Due to Reagan's impact on public discourse and advocacy of [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatism]], some historians have described the period during and after his presidency as the [[Reagan Era]].\n\n==Conservative shift in politics==\n{{Further|Conservatism in the United States|Reagan Era}}\n\nEven prior to becoming president, Reagan was the leader of a dramatic conservative shift that undercut many of the domestic and foreign policies that had dominated the national agenda for decades.<ref>Bruce J. Schulman and Julian E. Zelizer, eds. ''Rightward Bound: Making America Conservative in the 1970s'' (Harvard UP, 2008) pp 1-10.</ref><ref>Andrew Busch, ''Reagan's victory: the presidential election of 1980 and the rise of the right'' (UP of Kansas, 2005).</ref> A major factor in the rise of conservatism was the growing distrust of government in the aftermath of the [[Watergate scandal]]. While distrust of high officials had been an American characteristic for two centuries, Watergate engendered heightened levels of suspicion and encouraged the media to engage in a vigorous search for scandals.<ref>J. Lull, and S. Hinerman, \"The search for scandal' in J. Lull & S. Hinerman, eds. ''Media scandals: Morality and desire in the popular culture marketplace'' (1997) pp. 1-33.</ref> An unexpected new factor was the emergence of the [[Christian right|religious right]] as a cohesive political force that gave strong support to conservatism.<ref>Paul Boyer, \"The Evangelical Resurgence in 1970s American Protestantism\" in Schulman and Zelizer, eds. ''Rightward bound'' pp 29-51.:</ref><ref>Stephen D. Johnson and Joseph B. Tamney, \"The Christian Right and the 1980 presidential election.\" ''Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion'' (1982) 21#2: 123-131. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1385498 online]</ref>\n\nOther factors in the rise of the conservative movement the emergence of a \"[[culture war]]\" as a triangular battle among conservatives, traditional liberals, and the [[New Left]], involving such issues as individual freedom, divorce, sexual freedom, abortion, and homosexuality.<ref>James Davison Hunter, ''Culture wars:  The struggle to control the family, art, education, law, and politics in America'' (1992).</ref> A mass movement of population from the cities to the suburbs led to the creation of a new group of voters less attached to [[New Deal]] economic policies and [[political machine|machine politics]].<ref>Wilentz, pp. 23\u201324</ref> Meanwhile, it became socially acceptable for conservative Southern whites, especially well educated suburbanites, to vote Republican. Though the civil rights legislation of the 1960s had been a triumphal issue for liberalism and had created a new, pro-Democratic black electorate, it had also destroyed the argument that whites had to vote Democratic in order to protect segregation in the South.<ref>Earl Black and Merle Black, ''Politics and Society in the South'' (1989) p 249.</ref> Responding to these various trends, Reagan and other conservatives successfully presented conservative ideas as an alternative to a public that had grown disillusioned with New Deal liberalism and the Democratic Party.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 4\u20137</ref> Reagan's charisma and speaking skills helped him frame conservatism as an optimistic, forward-looking vision for the country.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 137\u2013138</ref>\n\n==1980 presidential election==\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1980.svg|right|thumb|1980 electoral vote results]]\n{{Main|Ronald Reagan 1980 presidential campaign|1980 United States presidential election}}\n\nReagan, who had served as [[Governor of California]] from 1967 to 1975, narrowly lost the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1976|1976 Republican presidential primaries]] to incumbent President [[Gerald Ford]]. With the defeat of Ford by Democrat [[Jimmy Carter]] in the [[1976 United States presidential election|1976 election]], Reagan immediately became the front-runner for the 1980 Republican presidential nomination.<ref>Weisberg,\npp. 56-57</ref> A darling of the conservative movement, Reagan faced more moderate Republicans such as [[George H. W. Bush]], [[Howard Baker]], and [[Bob Dole]] in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1980|1980 Republican presidential primaries]]. After Bush won the Iowa caucuses, he became Reagan's primary challenger, but Reagan won the New Hampshire primary and most of the following primaries, gaining an insurmountable delegate lead by the end of March 1980. Ford was Reagan's first choice for his running mate, but Reagan backed away from the idea out of the fear of a \"copresidency\" in which Ford would exercise an unusual degree of power. Reagan instead chose Bush, and the Reagan-Bush ticket was nominated at the [[1980 Republican National Convention]]. Meanwhile, Carter won the Democratic nomination, defeating a primary challenge by Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]. Polls taken after the party conventions showed a tied race between Reagan and Carter, while independent candidate [[John B. Anderson]] had the support of many moderates.<ref>Weisberg, pp. 61-63</ref>\n\nThe 1980 general campaign between Reagan and Carter was conducted amid a multitude of domestic concerns and the ongoing [[Iran hostage crisis]]. After winning the Republican nomination, Reagan pivoted to the center. Though he continued to champion a major tax cut, Reagan backed off of his support for free trade and the privatization of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], and promised to consider [[arms control]] treaties with the [[Soviet Union]]. He instead sought to focus the race on Carter's handling of the economy. Mired with an approval rating in the low 30s, Carter also waged a negative campaign, focusing on the supposed risk of war if Reagan took office.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 23\u201327</ref>\n\nReagan and Carter met in one presidential debate, held just one week before election day. Reagan delivered an effective performance, asking voters, \"Are you better off than you were four years ago?...Is America as respected throughout the world as it was?\" Though the race had been widely regarded as a close contest, Reagan won over the large majority of undecided voters.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 27\u201328</ref> Reagan took 50.7% of the popular vote and 489 of the 538 electoral votes. Carter won 41% of the popular vote and 49 electoral votes, while Anderson won 6.6% of the popular vote. In the concurrent [[United States elections, 1980|congressional elections]], Republicans took control of the Senate for the first time since the 1950s, while Democrats retained control of the House of Representatives.<ref>Patterson, pp. 149\u2013151</ref>\n\n==Administration==\n\n{{Infobox U.S. Cabinet\n|align=right\n|Name=Reagan\n|President=Ronald Reagan\n|President start=1981\n|President end=1989\n|Vice President=[[George H. W. Bush]]\n|Vice President start=1981\n|Vice President end=1989\n|State=[[Alexander Haig]]\n|State start=1981\n|State end=1982\n|State 2=[[George Shultz]]\n|State start 2=1982\n|State end 2=1989\n|Treasury=[[Donald Regan]]\n|Treasury start=1981\n|Treasury end=1985\n|Treasury 2=[[James Baker]]\n|Treasury start 2=1985\n|Treasury end 2=1988\n|Treasury 3=[[Nicholas F. Brady]]\n|Treasury start 3=1988\n|Treasury end 3=1989\n|Defense=[[Caspar Weinberger]]\n|Defense start=1981\n|Defense end=1987\n|Defense 2=[[Frank Carlucci]]\n|Defense start 2=1987\n|Defense end 2=1989\n|Justice=[[William French Smith]]\n|Justice start=1981\n|Justice end=1985\n|Justice 2=[[Edwin Meese]]\n|Justice start 2=1985\n|Justice end 2=1988\n|Justice 3=[[Dick Thornburgh]]\n|Justice start 3= 1988\n|Justice end 3=1989\n|Interior=[[James G. Watt]]\n|Interior start=1981\n|Interior end=1983\n|Interior 2=[[William P. Clark Jr.]]\n|Interior start 2=1983\n|Interior end 2=1985\n|Interior 3=[[Donald P. Hodel]]\n|Interior start 3=1985\n|Interior end 3=1989\n|Agriculture=[[John Rusling Block]]\n|Agriculture start=1981\n|Agriculture end=1986\n|Agriculture 2=[[Richard Edmund Lyng]]\n|Agriculture start 2=1986\n|Agriculture end 2=1989\n|Commerce=[[Malcolm Baldrige Jr.]]\n|Commerce start=1981\n|Commerce end=1987\n|Commerce 2=[[William Verity Jr.]]\n|Commerce start 2=1987\n|Commerce end 2=1989\n|Labor=[[Raymond J. Donovan]]\n|Labor start=1981\n|Labor end=1985\n|Labor 2=[[Bill Brock]]\n|Labor start 2=1985\n|Labor end 2=1987\n|Labor 3=[[Ann McLaughlin Korologos|Ann Dore McLaughlin]]\n|Labor start 3=1987\n|Labor end 3=1989\n|Health and Human Services=[[Richard Schweiker]]\n|Health and Human Services start=1981\n|Health and Human Services end=1983\n|Health and Human Services 2=[[Margaret Heckler]]\n|Health and Human Services start 2=1983\n|Health and Human Services end 2=1985\n|Health and Human Services 3=[[Otis Bowen]]\n|Health and Human Services start 3=1985\n|Health and Human Services end 3=1989\n|Education=[[Terrel Bell]]\n|Education start=1981\n|Education end=1984\n|Education 2=[[William Bennett]]\n|Education start 2=1985\n|Education end 2=1988\n|Education 3=[[Lauro Cavazos]]\n|Education start 3=1988\n|Education end 3=1989\n|Housing and Urban Development=[[Samuel Pierce]]\n|Housing and Urban Development start=1981\n|Housing and Urban Development end=1989\n|Transportation=[[Andrew L. Lewis Jr.]]\n|Transportation start=1981\n|Transportation end=1983\n|Transportation 2=[[Elizabeth Dole]]\n|Transportation start 2=1983\n|Transportation end 2=1987\n|Transportation 3=[[James H. Burnley IV]]\n|Transportation start 3=1987\n|Transportation end 3=1989\n|Energy=[[James B. Edwards]]\n|Energy start=1981\n|Energy end=1982\n|Energy 2=[[Donald P. Hodel]]\n|Energy start 2=1982\n|Energy end 2=1985\n|Energy 3=[[John S. Herrington]]\n|Energy start 3=1985\n|Energy end 3=1989\n|Counselor to the President=[[Edwin Meese]]\n|Counselor to the President start=1981\n|Counselor to the President end=1985\n|Counselor to the President 2=none\n|Counselor to the President start 2=1985\n|Counselor to the President end 2=1989\n|Management and Budget=[[David Stockman]]\n|Management and Budget start=1981\n|Management and Budget end=1985\n|Management and Budget 2=[[James C. Miller III]]\n|Management and Budget start 2=1985\n|Management and Budget end 2=1988\n|Management and Budget 3=[[Joseph Robert Wright Jr.]]\n|Management and Budget start 3=1988\n|Management and Budget end 3=1989\n|Ambassador to the United Nations=[[Jeane Kirkpatrick]]\n|Ambassador to the United Nations start=1981\n|Ambassador to the United Nations end=1985\n|Ambassador to the United Nations 2=[[Vernon A. Walters]]\n|Ambassador to the United Nations start 2=1985\n|Ambassador to the United Nations end 2=1989\n|Trade=[[Bill Brock]]\n|Trade start=1981\n|Trade end=1985\n|Trade 2=[[Clayton Yeutter]]\n|Trade start 2=1985\n|Trade end 2=1989\n|CIA=[[William J. Casey]]\n|CIA start=1981\n|CIA end=1987\n|CIA 2=[[William H. Webster]]\n|CIA start 2=1987\n|CIA end 2=1989\n}}\n\nReagan tapped [[James Baker]], who had run Bush's 1980 campaign, as his first [[White House Chief of Staff|chief of staff]]. Baker, [[White House Deputy Chief of Staff|Deputy Chief of Staff]] [[Michael Deaver]], and [[Counselor to the President|Counselor]] [[Edwin Meese]] formed the \"troika,\" the key White House staffers early in Reagan's presidency.<ref>Brands, pp. 241-246</ref> Baker quickly established himself as the most powerful member of the troika and the overseer of day-to-day operations, while Meese had nominal leadership of policy development and Deaver orchestrated Reagan's public appearances.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 51\u201352</ref> Aside from the troika, other important White House staffers included [[Richard Darman]] and [[David Gergen]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 52,</ref>\n\nReagan chose [[Alexander Haig]], a former general who had served as chief of staff to [[Richard Nixon]], as his first secretary of state. Other major Cabinet appointees included Secretary of Defense [[Caspar Weinberger]], a former Nixon cabinet official who would preside over an increase in defense spending, and Secretary of the Treasury [[Donald Regan]], a bank executive. Reagan selected [[David Stockman]], a young congressman from [[Michigan]], as the Director of the [[Office of Management and Budget]].<ref>Brands, pp. 246-248</ref> [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|CIA director]] [[William J. Casey]] emerged as an important figure in the administration, as the CIA would figure prominently into Reagan's Cold War initiatives. Reagan downgraded the importance of the [[National Security Advisor (United States)|national security advisor]], and six different individuals held that position during Reagan's presidency.<ref>Herring, pp. 864\u2013866</ref>\n\nHaig left the cabinet in 1982 after clashing with other members of the Reagan administration, and was replaced by another former Nixon administration official, [[George P. Shultz]].<ref>Brands, pp. 376-381</ref> By 1982, National Security Advisor [[William P. Clark Jr.]], [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Jeane Kirkpatrick]], and CIA Director Casey had established themselves as the major figures in the formulation of the administration's foreign policy.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 81\u201382</ref> Shultz eventually emerged as the administration's most influential foreign policy figure, moving the administration towards a less confrontational policy with the Soviet Union.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nBaker and Treasury Secretary Regan switched positions at the beginning of Reagan's second term.<ref>Brands, pp. 472-474</ref> Regan centralized power within his office, and he took on the responsibilities that had been held by Baker, Deaver, and Meese, the latter of whom succeeded [[William French Smith]] as attorney general in 1985.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 178\u2013180</ref> Regan frequently clashed with First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]], and he left the administration in the wake of the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair]] and Republican losses in the [[United States elections, 1986|1986 mid-term elections]]. Regan was replaced by former Senate Majority Leader [[Howard Baker]].<ref>Brands, pp. 645-649</ref>\n\n[[File:1981 US Cabinet.jpg|thumb|300px|left|The Cabinet of President Reagan in 1981]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Judicial appointments==\n{{Further|Ronald Reagan Supreme Court candidates|List of federal judges appointed by Ronald Reagan|Ronald Reagan judicial appointment controversies}}\n[[File:William Rehnquist.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Reagan appointed [[William Rehnquist]] to the office of [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] in 1986; he served until his death in 2005]]\n\nReagan made four successful appointments to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] during his eight years in office. In 1981, he successfully nominated [[Sandra Day O'Connor]] to succeed [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Associate Justice]] [[Potter Stewart]], fulfilling a campaign promise to name the first woman to the Supreme Court. Democrats, who had planned to vigorously oppose Reagan's nominations to the Supreme Court, approved of the nomination of O'Connor. However, the [[Christian right]] was astonished and dismayed with O\u2019Connor, whom they feared would not overturn the Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'', which had established the constitutional right to have an [[abortion in the United States|abortion]] without undue government interference.<ref>Prudence Flowers, \"\u2018A Prolife Disaster\u2019: The Reagan Administration and the Nomination of Sandra Day O\u2019Connor.\" ''Journal of Contemporary History''  53.2 (2018): 391-414</ref><ref>Wilentz, pp. 189\u2013190</ref> O'Connor served on the Supreme Court until 2006, and was generally considered to be a centrist conservative.<ref name=\"bisk\">{{cite news| last1=Biskupic| first1=Joan| title=Rehnquist left Supreme Court with conservative legacy| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/judicial/supremecourtjustices/2005-09-04-rehnquist-legacy_x.htm| accessdate=February 27, 2016| work=USA Today| date=September 4, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Reagan elevated Associate Justice [[William Rehnquist]] to the position of [[Chief Justice of the United States]] after [[Warren Burger]] chose to retire.<ref name=SCOTUS>{{cite web| title=U.S. Senate: Supreme Court Nominations: 1789-Present| url=https://www.senate.gov/pagelayout/reference/nominations/Nominations.htm| website = www.senate.gov| accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Rehnquist, a member of the conservative wing of the Court,<ref name=\"bisk\"/> was the third sitting associate justice to be elevated to chief justice, after [[Edward Douglass White]] and [[Harlan F. Stone]]. Reagan successfully nominated [[Antonin Scalia]] to fill Rehnquist's position as an associate justice of the Supreme Court.<ref name=SCOTUS/> Scalia became a member of the Court's conservative wing.<ref name=\"bisk\"/>\n\nReagan faced greater difficulties in filling the final Supreme Court vacancy, which arose due to the retirement of [[Lewis F. Powell Jr.]] Reagan nominated [[Robert Bork]] in July 1987, but the nomination was [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination|rejected by the Senate]] in October 1987.<ref name=SCOTUS/> Later that month, Reagan announced the nomination of [[Douglas H. Ginsburg]], but Ginsburg withdrew from consideration in November 1987. Finally, Reagan nominated [[Anthony Kennedy]], who won Senate confirmation in February 1988.<ref name=SCOTUS/> Along with O'Connor, Kennedy served as the key swing vote on the Supreme Court in the decades after Reagan left office.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parlapiano |first1=Alicia |last2=Patel |first2=Jugal K. |title=With Kennedy's Retirement, the Supreme Court Loses Its Center |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/27/us/politics/kennedy-retirement-supreme-court-median.html |accessdate=20 July 2018 |work=New York Times |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nReagan appointed a combined total of 368 judges to the [[United States courts of appeals]] and the [[United States district court]]s, [[List of Presidents of the United States by judicial appointments|more than any other president]]. The vast majority of his judicial appointees were conservative white men,<ref>Patterson, p. 174</ref> and many of the appointees were affiliated with the conservative [[Federalist Society]].<ref>Weisberg, pp. 116-117</ref> Partly because Congress passed a law creating new federal judicial positions in 1984, Reagan had appointed nearly half of the federal judiciary by the time he left office in 1989.<ref name=\"auto2\">Rossinow, p. 178</ref>\n\n==Assassination attempt==\n{{Main|Attempted assassination of Ronald Reagan}}\nOn March 30, 1981, only 69 days into the new administration, Reagan, his press secretary [[James Brady]], Washington police officer [[Thomas Delahanty]], and Secret Service agent [[Tim McCarthy]] were struck by gunfire from would-be assassin [[John Hinckley Jr.]] outside the [[Hilton Washington|Washington Hilton Hotel]]. Although Reagan was initially reported to be \"close to death\",<ref name=\"cnn transcript\">{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0103/30/lkl.00.html|title=Remembering the Assassination Attempt on Ronald Reagan|date=2001-03-30|accessdate=2007-12-19|publisher=CNN}}</ref> he recovered and was released from the hospital on April 11, becoming the first serving president to survive being wounded in an assassination attempt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/comment/dsouza200406080824.asp|work=National Review|accessdate=February 16, 2009|date=June 8, 2004|title=Purpose|author=D'Souza, Dinesh}}</ref> The failed assassination attempt had great influence on Reagan's popularity; polls indicated his approval rating to be around 73%.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Reagan's Ratings: 'Great Communicator's' Appeal Is Greater in Retrospect|accessdate=May 30, 2008|date=June 7, 2004|publisher=ABC|author=Langer, Gary|url=http://abcnews.go.com/sections/us/Polls/reagan_ratings_poll_040607.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Leuchtenberg, pp. 597-598\">Leuchtenberg, pp. 597-598</ref> Many pundits and journalists later described the failed assassination as a critical moment in Reagan's presidency, as his newfound popularity provided critical momentum in passing his domestic agenda.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 598-599</ref>\n\n==Domestic affairs==\n{{Main|Domestic policy of the Ronald Reagan administration}}\n\n===\"Reaganomics\" and taxation===\n{{Main|Reaganomics}}\n[[File:Ronald Reagan televised address from the Oval Office, outlining plan for Tax Reduction Legislation July 1981.jpg|thumb|Outlining his plan for ''Tax Reduction Legislation'' from the [[Oval Office]] in a televised address, July 1981]]\n\n====Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981====\n\nReagan implemented economic policies based on [[supply-side economics]], advocating a ''[[laissez-faire]]'' philosophy and [[free market economy|free-market]] fiscal policy.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Karaagac, John|title=Ronald Reagan and Conservative Reformism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZFhGnjKqjgAC&pg=PA113 |isbn=0-7391-0296-6|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2000|page=113}}</ref> Reagan's taxation policies resembled those instituted by President [[Calvin Coolidge]] and Treasury Secretary [[Andrew Mellon]] in the 1920s, but Reagan was also strongly influenced by contemporary economists such as [[Arthur Laffer]], who rejected the then-dominant views of [[Keynesian economics|Keynesian economists]].<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 595-596</ref> Reagan relied on Laffer and other economists to argue that tax cuts would reduce [[inflation]], which went against the prevailing Keynesian view.<ref>Brands, pp. 271-272</ref> Supply-side advocates also asserted that cutting taxes would ultimately lead to higher government revenue due to economic growth, a proposition that was challenged by many economists.<ref>Patterson, pp. 154-155</ref>\n\nRepublican Congressman [[Jack Kemp]] and Republican Senator [[William Roth]] had nearly won passage of a major tax cut during Carter's presidency, but Carter had prevented passage of the bill due to concerns about the deficit.<ref>Rossinow, p. 20</ref> Reagan made the passage of Kemp-Roth bill his top domestic priority upon taking office. As Democrats controlled the House of Representatives, passage of any bill would require the support of some House Democrats in addition to the support of congressional Republicans.<ref name=\"leuch599601\"/> Reagan's victory in the 1980 presidential campaign had united Republicans around his leadership, while conservative Democrats like [[Phil Gramm]] of Texas (who would later [[Party switching in the United States|switch parties]]) were eager to back some of Reagan's conservative policies.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 48\u201349</ref> Throughout 1981, Reagan frequently met with members of Congress, focusing especially on winning support from conservative Southern Democrats.<ref name=\"leuch599601\"/>\n\nIn July 1981, the Senate voted 89\u201311 in favor of the tax cut bill favored by Reagan, and the House subsequently approved the bill in a 238\u2013195 vote.<ref name=\"auto3\">Rossinow, pp. 61\u201362</ref> The [[Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981]] cut the top marginal tax rate from 70% to 50%, lowered the [[Capital gains tax in the United States|capital gains tax]] from 28% to 20%, more than tripled the amount of inherited money exempt from the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]], and cut the [[Corporate tax in the United States|corporate tax]].<ref name=\"leuch599601\">Leuchtenberg, pp. 599-601</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/> Reagan's success in passing a major tax bill and cutting the federal budget was hailed as the \"Reagan Revolution\" by some reporters; one columnist wrote that the Reagan's legislative success represented the \"most formidable domestic initiative any president has driven through since the [[First 100 days of Franklin D. Roosevelt's presidency|Hundred Days]] of [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Roosevelt]].\"<ref name=\"Patterson, p. 157\">Patterson, p. 157</ref>\n\n====Later tax acts====\n\nFaced with concerns about the mounting federal debt, Reagan agreed to raise taxes, signing the [[Tax Equity and Fiscal Responsibility Act of 1982]] (TEFRA).<ref>Brands, pp. 346-349</ref> Many of Reagan's conservative supporters condemned TEFRA, but Reagan argued that his administration would be unable to win further budget cuts without the tax hike.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 148\u2013149</ref> Among other provisions, TEFRA doubled the federal cigarette tax and rescinded a portion of the corporate tax cuts from the 1981 tax bill.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 62\u201363</ref> By 1983, the amount of federal tax had fallen for all or almost all American taxpayers, but most strongly affected the wealthy; the proportion of income paid in taxes by the richest one percent fell from 29.8 percent to 24.8 percent.<ref>Rossinow, p. 63</ref>  Partly due to the poor economy, Reagan's legislative momentum dissipated after his first year in office, and his party lost several seats in the House in the [[United States elections, 1982|1982 congressional elections]].<ref name=\"Patterson, pp. 162-163\">Patterson, pp. 162-163</ref> Compared to other [[United States midterm election|midterm election]]s, the losses were relatively small for the party holding the presidency, but conservative Democrats were less open to Reagan's initiatives after 1982.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 97\u201398, 164</ref> As deficits continued to be an issue, Reagan signed another bill that raised taxes, the [[Deficit Reduction Act of 1984]].<ref name=\"shapiro1\">{{cite journal|last1=Shapiro|first1=Bernard M.|title=Presidential Politics And Deficit Reduction: The Landscape Of Tax Policy In The 1980S And 1990S|journal=Washington and Lee Law Revie|date=1 March 1993|volume=50|issue=2|url=http://scholarlycommons.law.wlu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1749&context=wlulr}}</ref>\n\nWith Donald Regan taking over as Chief of Staff in 1985, the Reagan administration made simplification of the tax code the central focus of its second term domestic agenda.<ref>Brands, pp. 540-541</ref> Working with [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[Tip O'Neill]], a Democrat who also favored tax reform, Reagan overcame significant opposition from members of Congress in both parties to pass the [[Tax Reform Act of 1986]].<ref>Brands, pp. 542-544</ref> The act simplified the tax code by reducing the number of tax brackets to four and slashing a number of tax breaks. The top rate was dropped to 28%, but capital gains taxes were increased on those with the highest incomes from 20% to 28%. The increase of the lowest tax bracket from 11% to 15% was more than offset by expansion of the personal exemption, [[standard deduction]], and [[earned income tax credit]]. The net result was the removal of six million poor Americans from the income tax roll and a reduction of income tax liability at all income levels.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brownlee|first1=Elliot|last2=Graham|first2=Hugh Davis|title=The Reagan Presidency: Pragmatic Conservatism & Its Legacies|date=2003|publisher=University of Kansas Press|location=Lawrence, Kansas|pages=172\u2013173}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Steuerle|first1=C. Eugene|title=The Tax Decade: How Taxes Came to Dominate the Public Agenda|date=1992|publisher=The Urban Institute Press|location=Washington D.C.|isbn=0-87766-523-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/taxdecadehowtaxe0000steu/page/122 122]|url=https://archive.org/details/taxdecadehowtaxe0000steu/page/122}}</ref> The net effect of Reagan's tax bills was that overall tax burden held steady at roughly 19 percent of [[gross national product]].<ref>Patterson, p. 166</ref>\n\n===Government spending===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; text-align:center;\"\n|+ Federal finances and GDP during Reagan's presidency<ref>All figures, except for debt percentage, are presented in billions of dollars. GDP is calculated for the calendar year. The income, outlay, deficit, and debt figures are calculated for the [[US fiscal year|fiscal year]], which ends on September 30. For example, fiscal year 2017 ended on September 30, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Income\n! Outlays\n! Surplus/<br/>Deficit\n! [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]]\n! Debt as a %<br/>of GDP<ref>Represents the national debt held by the public as a percentage of GDP</ref>\n\n|-\n! 1981\n| 599.3\n| 678.2\n| -79.0\n| 3138.4\n| 25.2\n\n|-\n! 1982\n| 617.8\n| 745.7\n| -128.0\n| 3313.9\n| 27.9\n\n|-\n! 1983\n| 600.6\n| 808.4\n| -207.8\n| 3541.1\n| 32.1\n\n|-\n! 1984\n| 666.4\n| 851.8\n| -185.4\n| 3952.8\n| 33.1\n\n|-\n! 1985\n| 734.0\n| 946.3\n| -212.3\n| 4270.4\n| 35.3\n\n|-\n! 1986\n| 769.2\n| 990.4\n| -221.2\n| 4536.1\n| 38.4\n\n|-\n! 1987\n| 854.3\n| 1004.0\n| -149.7\n| 4781.9\n| 39.5\n\n|-\n! 1988\n| 909.2\n| 1064.4\n| -155.2\n| 5155.1\n| 39.8\n\n|-\n! 1989\n| 991.1\n| 1143.7\n| -152.6\n| 5570.0\n| 39.3\n\n|-\n! Ref.\n| colspan=3 | <ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Tables|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/omb/budget/Historicals|website=Obama White House|publisher=Office of Management and Budget|accessdate=23 May 2018|location=Table 1.1}}</ref>\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Tables|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/omb/budget/Historicals|website=Obama White House|publisher=Office of Management and Budget|accessdate=23 May 2018|location=Table 1.2}}</ref>\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Tables|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/omb/budget/Historicals|website=Obama White House|publisher=Office of Management and Budget|accessdate=23 May 2018|location=Table 7.1}}</ref>\n|}\n\nReagan prioritized tax cuts over spending cuts, arguing that lower revenue would eventually require lower spending.<ref>Brands, pp. 263-264</ref> Nonetheless, Reagan was determined to decrease government spending and roll back or dismantle [[Great Society]] programs such as [[Medicaid]] and the [[Office of Economic Opportunity]].<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 594-595</ref> In August 1981, Reagan signed the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1981, which cut federal funding for social programs like [[Food Stamp Program|food stamps]], [[School meal programs in the United States|school lunch programs]], and Medicaid.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 58\u201360</ref> The [[Comprehensive Employment and Training Act]], which had provided for the employment of 300,000 workers in 1980, was also repealed,<ref name=\"Patterson, p. 157\"/> and the administration tightened eligibility for [[unemployment benefits]].<ref name=\"auto4\">Rossinow, p. 85</ref> Notably absent from the budget cuts was the Department of Defense, which saw its budget bolstered.<ref>Brands, pp. 266-267</ref>\n\nReagan experienced several legislative successes in his first year in office, but his attempts to cut federal domestic spending after 1981 met increasing congressional resistance.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 615-616</ref> Spending on programs like [[Supplemental Security Income]], Medicaid, the [[earned income tax credit]], and [[Aid to Families with Dependent Children]] all increased after 1982. The number of federal civilian employees rose during Reagan's tenure, from 2.9 million to 3.1 million.<ref>Patterson, p. 165</ref> Reagan's policy of [[New Federalism]], which sought to shift the responsibility for most social programs to state governments, found little support in Congress.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 618-619</ref>\n\nIn 1981, OMB Director David Stockman won Reagan's approval to seek cuts to [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] in 1981, but this plan was poorly-received in Congress.<ref>Brands, pp. 300-303</ref> In 1982, Reagan established the bipartisan [[Greenspan Commission|National Commission on Social Security Reform]] to make recommendations to secure the long-term integrity of Social Security. The commission rejected Social Security privatization and other major changes to the program, but recommended expanding the Social Security base (by including exempt federal and nonprofit employees), raising Social Security taxes, and reducing some payments. These recommendations were enacted in the [[History of Social Security in the United States#1983 Amendments|Social Security Amendments of 1983]], which received bipartisan support.<ref>Brands, pp. 425-427</ref> While Reagan avoided cuts to Social Security and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] for most individuals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/pressketch.html|title=The Reagan Presidency|publisher=Reagan Presidential Foundation|accessdate=August 4, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517013218/http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/pressketch.html|archivedate=May 17, 2008}}</ref> his administration attempted to purge many people from the Social Security disability rolls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/19/us/us-to-reconsider-denial-of-benefits-to-many-disabled.html?pagewanted=all|title=U.S. to Reconsider Denial of Benefits to Many Disabled|date=April 19, 1992|author=Pear, Robert|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 23, 2008}}</ref> Reagan's inability to implement major cuts to Social Security solidified its status as the \"[[third rail of politics|third rail]]\" of U.S. politics, and future administrations would be reluctant to propose cuts to the popular program.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 149\u2013150</ref>\n\n===Deficits===\n\nAs Reagan was unwilling to match his tax cuts with cuts to defense spending or Social Security, rising deficits became an issue.<ref>Weisberg, pp. 75-76</ref> These deficits were exacerbated by the [[early 1980s recession]], which cut into federal revenue.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 605-606</ref> Unable to win further domestic spending cuts, and pressured to address the deficit, Reagan was forced to raise taxes after 1981.<ref>Brands, pp. 346-347</ref> Nonetheless, the national debt more than tripled between fiscal year 1980 and fiscal year 1989, going from $914 billion to $2.7 trillion, while national debt as a percentage of GDP rose from 33 percent in 1981 to 53 percent in 1989. Reagan never submitted a balanced budget during his time in office.<ref>Patterson, pp. 158-159</ref>\n\nIn an effort to lower the national debt, Congress passed the [[Gramm\u2013Rudman\u2013Hollings Balanced Budget Act]], which called for [[Budget sequestration|automatic spending cuts]] if Congress was unable to eliminate deficits through the regular budget-making process.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However, Congress found ways around the automatic cuts and deficits continued to rise, ultimately leading to the passage of the [[Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1990]].<ref name=\"scline1\">{{cite news|last1=Cline|first1=Seth|title=What Happened Last Time We Had a Budget Sequester?|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/blogs/press-past/2013/03/01/what-happened-last-time-we-had-a-budget-sequester|accessdate=18 May 2017|publisher=US News and World Report|date=1 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\n\nReagan took office in the midst of poor economic conditions, as the country experienced [[stagflation]], a phenomenon in which both inflation and unemployment were high.<ref>Brands, pp. 221-222</ref> The economy experienced a brief period of growth early in Reagan's first year in office, but plunged into a recession in July 1981.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 90\u201391</ref> As the recession continued in the first two years of Reagan's presidency, many within Reagan's administration blamed the policies of [[Paul Volcker]], the [[Chair]] of the [[Federal Reserve System|Federal Reserve]]. But Reagan himself never criticized Volcker.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/commandingheights/shared/minitext/int_paulvolcker.html#6 |title=Commanding Heights, Paul Volcker Interview |date=26 September 2000 |website=PBS |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Volcker sought to fight inflation by pursuing a policy of \"tight money\" in which interest rates were set a high level.<ref name=\"brands317319\"/> High interest rates would restrict lending and investment, which would in turn lower inflation, raise unemployment and, at least in the short term, reduce economic growth.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 88\u201390</ref> Unemployment reached a high of nearly 11% in 1982,<ref name=\"brands317319\">Brands, pp. 317-319</ref> [[Poverty in the United States|poverty]] rate rose from 11.7 percent to 15 percent.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The country emerged from recession in 1983,<ref name=\"Brands, pp. 452-453\">Brands, pp. 452-453</ref> but not all shared equally in the economic recovery, and [[economic inequality]] and the number of [[Homelessness in the United States|homeless]] individuals both increased during the 1980s.<ref>Patterson, pp. 166\u2013167</ref><ref>Rossinow, p. 145</ref> Fearful of damaging confidence in the economic recovery, Reagan nominated Volcker to a second term in 1983, and Volcker remained in office until 1987.<ref name=\"brands668671\"/> Inflation dropped to approximately 3.5% in 1985, while the unemployment rate fell to about 5% in 1988.<ref name=\"Patterson, pp. 162-163\"/> In 1987, Reagan appointed conservative economist [[Alan Greenspan]] to succeed Volcker, and Greenspan would lead the Federal Reserve until 2006. Greenspan raised interest rates in another attempt to curb inflation, setting off a [[stock market crash]] in October 1987 known as \"[[Black Monday (1987)|Black Monday]],\" but the markets stabilized and recovered in the following weeks.<ref name=\"brands668671\">Brands, pp. 668-671</ref>\n\n===Labor===\n\nIn August 1981, the [[Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization (1968)|Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization]] (PATCO), which consisted of federal employees, voted to go on a [[Strike action|labor strike]] in hopes of receiving better pay and benefits. After the vote, Reagan announced that the strikers would be fired if they did not return to work within forty-eight hours. After the deadline passed, Reagan fired over 10,000 air traffic controllers, while approximately 40 percent of the union members returned to work. Reagan's handling of the strike was strongly criticized by union leaders, but it won the approval of his conservative base of voters and others in the public.<ref name=\"patterson157158\"/><ref>Rossinow, pp. 86\u201387</ref> The breaking of the PATCO strike demoralized organized labor, and the number of strikes fell dramatically in the 1980s.<ref name=\"patterson157158\">Patterson, pp. 157-158</ref> Many of the strikes that did occur, including the [[Arizona copper mine strike of 1983]], the 1983 [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]] bus driver strike, and the 1985 [[Hormel]] meatpacking worker strike, ended with dismissal of the strikers. With the assent of Reagan's sympathetic [[National Labor Relations Board]] appointees, many companies also won wage and benefit cutbacks from unions, especially in the manufacturing sector.<ref name=\"rossinow8788\">Rossinow, p. 87\u201388</ref> During Reagan's time in office, the share of employees who were part of a labor union dropped from approximately one-fourth of the total workforce to approximately one-sixth of the total workforce.<ref>Patterson, p. 170</ref>\n\n===Deregulation===\n\nReagan sought to loosen federal regulation of economic activities, and he appointed key officials who shared this agenda. According to historian [[William Leuchtenburg]], by 1986, the Reagan administration eliminated almost half of the federal regulations that had existed in 1981.<ref name=\"leuch601\"/> The [[Federal Communications Commission]] aggressively deregulated the [[broadcasting]] industry, eliminating the [[Fairness Doctrine]] and other restrictions.<ref name=\"donnelly1\">{{cite news|last1=Donnelly|first1=H.|title=Broadcasting Deregulation|url=http://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre1987120400|accessdate=29 November 2017|publisher=CQ Press|date=1987}}</ref> The 1982 [[Garn\u2013St. Germain Depository Institutions Act]] deregulated [[savings and loan association]]s and allowed banks to provide [[adjustable-rate mortgage]]s. Reagan also eliminated numerous government positions and dismissed numerous federal employees, including the entire staff of the [[Employment and Training Administration]]. Secretary of the Interior [[James Watt]] implemented policies designed to open up federal territories to oil drilling and [[surface mining]]. Under [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] Director [[Anne Gorsuch]], the EPA's budget was dramatically reduced and the EPA loosely enforced environmental regulations.<ref name=\"leuch601\">Leuchtenberg, pp. 601-604</ref>\n\n====Savings and loan crisis====\n\nAfter the passage of the Garn\u2013St. Germain Depository Institutions Act, savings and loans associations engaged in riskier activities, and the leaders of some institutions embezzled funds.<ref>Patterson, p. 175</ref> In what became known as the [[Savings and loan crisis]], a total of 747 financial institutions failed and needed to be rescued with $160 billion in taxpayer dollars.<ref>Timothy Curry and Lynn Shibut, The Cost of the Savings and Loan Crisis: Truth and Consequences FDIC, December 2000.</ref> As an indication of this scandal's size, [[Martin Mayer]] wrote at the time, \"The theft from the taxpayer by the community that fattened on the growth of the savings and loan (S&L) industry in the 1980s is the worst public scandal in American history...Measuring by money, [or] by the misallocation of national resources...the S&L outrage makes [[Teapot Dome Scandal|Teapot Dome]] and [[Cr\u00e9dit Mobilier of America scandal|Credit Mobilier]] seem minor episodes.\"<ref>''The Greatest-Ever Bank Robbery: The Collapse of the Savings and Loan Industry'' by Martin Mayer (Scribner's)</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n{{see also|Immigration to the United States}}\n\nThe 1980s saw the highest rate of immigration to the United States since the 1910s, and the proportion of the foreign-born population reached its highest level since the 1940s.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 158\u2013159</ref> Reagan did not make immigration a focus of his administration, but he came to support a package of reforms sponsored by Republican Senator [[Alan Simpson (American politician)|Alan Simpson]] and Democratic Congressman [[Romano Mazzoli]], which he signed into law as the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986|Immigration Reform and Control Act]] in November 1986.<ref>Brands, pp. 544-545</ref> The act made it illegal to knowingly hire or recruit [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants]], required employers to attest to their employees' immigration status, and granted amnesty to approximately three million illegal immigrants who had entered the United States before January 1, 1982, and had lived in the country continuously. The bill was also contained provisions designed to enhance security measures at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]].<ref name=\"bplumer1\"/> Upon signing the act at a ceremony held beside the newly refurbished [[Statue of Liberty]], Reagan said, \"The legalization provisions in this act will go far to improve the lives of a class of individuals who now must hide in the shadows, without access to many of the benefits of a free and open society. Very soon many of these men and women will be able to step into the sunlight and, ultimately, if they choose, they may become Americans.\"<ref name=\"immigration\">Reagan, Ronald. (November 6, 1986) [http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/speeches/1986/110686b.htm Statement on Signing the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986.] Collected Speeches, Ronald Reagan Presidential Library. Retrieved August 15, 2007.</ref> The bill was largely unsuccessful at halting illegal immigration, and the population of illegal immigrants rose from 5 million in 1986 to 11.1 million in 2013.<ref name=\"bplumer1\">{{cite news|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|title=Congress tried to fix immigration back in 1986. Why did it fail?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/01/30/in-1986-congress-tried-to-solve-immigration-why-didnt-it-work/|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=Washington Post|date=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal and anti-drug policy===\n\n[[File:NRJUSTSAYNORALLY.jpg|thumb|right|First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]] at a [[Just Say No]] rally at the White House]]\n\nNot long after being sworn into office, Reagan declared more militant policies in the \"[[War on Drugs]]\".<ref name=\"War on Drugs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/extra/features/jan-june01/drug_war.html |title=The War on Drugs |publisher=pbs. org |date=May 10, 2001 |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Youth Trends\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nida.nih.gov/Infofacts/HSYouthtrends.html |title=NIDA InfoFacts: High School and Youth Trends |publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse, NIH |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref> He promised a \"planned, concerted campaign\" against all drugs,<ref name=\"The Drug War\">{{cite web |url=http://academic.udayton.edu/race/03justice/crime09.htm |title=The Drug War as Race War |accessdate=April 11, 2007 |author=Randall, Vernellia R |date=April 18, 2006 |publisher=The University of Dayton School of Law}}</ref> in hopes of decreasing drug use, particularly among adolescents.<ref name=\"Interview: Dr. Herbert Kleber\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/interviews/kleber.html |title=Interview: Dr. Herbert Kleber |accessdate=June 12, 2007 |publisher=PBS |quote=The politics of the Reagan years and the Bush years probably made it somewhat harder to get treatment expanded, but at the same time, it probably had a good effect in terms of decreasing initiation and use. For example, marijuana went from thirty-three percent of high-school seniors in 1980 to twelve percent in 1991.}}</ref><ref name=\"Decline of Substance Use\">{{cite web |author=Bachman, Gerald G. |url=http://www.monitoringthefuture.org/pubs/jbbook/jbbook02.html |title=The Decline of Substance Use in Young Adulthood |publisher=The Regents of the University of Michigan |accessdate=April 4, 2007|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The \"[[crack epidemic]],\" which saw a large number of individuals become addicted to [[crack cocaine]] and may have played a role in numerous murders, emerged as a major area of public concern.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 122\u2013124</ref> [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] Nancy Reagan made the War on Drugs her main cause as First Lady, founding the \"[[Just Say No]]\" drug awareness campaign.<ref name=\"PBS Frontline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/cron/ |title=Thirty Years of America's Drug War |publisher=PBS |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref>\n\nConcerns about drug use prompted Congress to pass legislation such as the [[Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984]]<ref>Rossinow, p. 124</ref> and the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986]], the latter of which granted $1.7 billion to fight drugs and established a mandatory minimum penalties for drug offenses.<ref name=\"PBS Frontline\"/> Reagan also signed the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988]], which further increased criminal penalties for drug use and established the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]].<ref name=\"jjohnson1\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Julie|title=REAGAN SIGNS BILL TO CURB DRUG USE|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/19/us/reagan-signs-bill-to-curb-drug-use.html|accessdate=7 December 2017|work=New York Times|date=19 November 1988}}</ref> Critics charged that Reagan's policies promoted significant racial disparities in the prison population,<ref name=\"PBS Frontline\"/> were ineffective in reducing the availability of drugs or crime on the street, and came at a great financial and human cost for American society.<ref name=\"Stop the Drug War\">{{cite web |url=http://stopthedrugwar.org/chronicle-old/341/reagan.shtml |publisher=stopthedrugwar.org |title=The Reagan-Era Drug War Legacy |date=June 11, 2004 |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref> Supporters argued that the numbers for adolescent drug users declined during Reagan's years in office.<ref name=\"Decline of Substance Use\"/>\n\n===Social policies and civil rights===\n\nReagan was largely unable to enact his ambitious social policy agenda, which included a federal ban on [[abortions in the United States|abortions]] and an end to [[desegregation busing]].<ref name=\"svroberts1\"/> With Reagan's support, conservative Republican Senator [[Jesse Helms]] led an effort to prevent the Supreme Court from reviewing state and local laws mandating [[school prayer]], but Republican senators like [[Lowell Weicker]] and [[Barry Goldwater]] blocked passage of Helms' bill.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 95\u201396</ref> Despite the lack of major social policy legislation, Reagan was able to influence social policy through regulations and the appointment of conservative Supreme Court Justices.<ref name=\"svroberts1\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Steven V.|title=THE NATION; Reagan's Social Issues: Gone but Not Forgotten|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/09/11/weekinreview/the-nation-reagan-s-social-issues-gone-but-not-forgotten.html|accessdate=7 December 2017|work=New York Times|date=11 September 1988}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, Reagan signed a bill extending the [[Voting Rights Act]] for 25 years after a grass-roots lobbying and legislative campaign forced him to abandon his plan to ease that law's restrictions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Raines|first=Howell|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/30/us/voting-rights-act-signed-by-reagan.html|title=Voting Rights Act Signed by Reagan|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 30, 1982|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> He also reluctantly accepted the continuation of [[Affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]] programs<ref>Patterson, p. 171</ref> and the establishment of [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day]] as a [[Federal holidays in the United States|federal holiday]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 163\u2013164</ref> The [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]] and the Justice Department both prosecuted far fewer civil rights cases per year than they had under Carter.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 42\u201343</ref> In 1988, Reagan vetoed the [[Civil Rights Restoration Act]], but his veto was overridden by Congress. Reagan had argued that the legislation infringed on [[states' rights]] and the rights of churches and business owners.<ref>{{cite book|title=American Civil Rights Policy from Truman to Clinton: The Role of Presidential Leadership |first=Steven A. |last=Shull |year=1999 |publisher=M.E. Sharpe |page=94 |isbn=9780765603944 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CdFdPBCj8NMC&pg=PA95}}</ref>\n\nNo civil rights legislation for [[homosexuality|gay]] individuals passed during Reagan's tenure. Many in the Reagan administration, including [[White House Communications Director|Communications Director]] [[Pat Buchanan]], were hostile to the gay community, as were many religious leaders who were important allies to the administration.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 185\u2013186</ref> Gay rights and the growing [[HIV/AIDS]] emerged as an important matter of public concern in 1985 after it was disclosed that actor [[Rock Hudson]], a personal friend of President Reagan, was receiving treatment for AIDS. As public anxiety over AIDS rose, the Supreme Court upheld a state law that criminalized homosexuality in the case of ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]''.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 132\u2013134</ref> Though Surgeon General [[C. Everett Koop]] advocated for a public health campaign designed to reduce the spread of AIDS by raising awareness and promoting the use of condoms, Reagan favored rejected Koop's proposals in favor of [[abstinence-only sex education]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 212\u2013214</ref> By 1989, approximately 60,000 American had died of AIDS, and liberals strongly criticized Reagan's response to the HIV/AIDS crisis.<ref>Patterson, pp. 179\u2013182</ref> On the 1980 campaign trail, Reagan spoke of the gay rights movement:\n{{quote|My criticism is that [the gay movement] isn\u2019t just asking for civil rights; it\u2019s asking for recognition and acceptance of an alternative lifestyle which I do not believe society can condone, nor can I.<ref>{{cite book |last=Scheer |first=Robert |title=Playing President: My Close Ecounters with Nixon, Carter, Bush I, Reagan, and Clinton--and How They Did Not Prepare Me for George W. Bush |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xhTTyMDzP5EC&pg=PA154 |year=2006 |publisher=Akashic Books |isbn=978-1-933354-01-9 |page=154}}</ref>}}\n\n===Environmental Policy===\nReagan's strong preferences for limited federal involvement and deregulation extended to the environment. His main goal was to lessen the burden of regulation on businesses to promote more economic activity in the United States. Because of this policy, Reagan refused to renew the Clean Air Act during his administration.<ref>Daynes, B. W., & Sussman, G. (2010). ''White House Politics and the Environment: Franklin D. Roosevelt to George W. Bush''. College Station: Texas A & M Univ. Press.</ref> Reagan lessened existing regulations on pollution, cut funding to government environmental agencies, and appointed known anti-environmentalist individuals to key positions presiding over these organizations.<ref>Kline, Benjamin. (2011). ''First Along the River\u202f: a Brief History of the U.S. Environmental Movement''. 4th ed. Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers.</ref> \n\nWhen Reagan took office in 1981, he \"attempted to reduce\" money that was directed towards studying the burgeoning field of global warming and human-driven climate change.<ref>Daynes, B. W. ''White House Politics and the Environment'', p.176.</ref> In the early 1980s, the study of the intersection between human activity and climate change was still in its infancy and scientists were far from a consensus on the topic.<ref>Miller, Norman. (2009). ''Environmental Politics\u202f: Stakeholders, Interests, and Policymaking''. 2nd ed. New York: Routledge.</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the Reagan administration signed the [[Montreal Protocol]] in an effort to reduce emissions that damage the [[ozone layer]].<ref>Daynes, B. W. ''White House Politics and the Environment'', p.185.</ref>\n\n===Mass surveillance===\nCiting [[national security]] concerns, the president's national security team pressed for more [[surveillance]] power early during Reagan's first term. Their recommendations were based upon the [[premise]] that the federal government's [[Intelligence assessment|intelligence]] and [[counterintelligence]] capabilities had been weakened by presidents Carter and Ford.<ref>{{cite web| title=The executive order that led to mass spying, as told by NSA alumni: Feds call it \"twelve triple three\"; whistleblower says it's the heart of the problem| last=Farivar| first=Cyrus| date=August 27, 2014| url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2014/08/a-twisted-history-how-a-reagan-era-executive-order-led-to-mass-spying/2/| publisher=Ars Technica| accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> On December 4, 1981, Reagan signed [[Executive Order 12333]]. This [[presidential directive]] broadened the power of the [[United States Intelligence Community|government's intelligence community]]; mandated rules for spying on United States citizens, permanent residents, and on anyone within the United States; and also directed the Attorney General and others to create further policies and procedures for what information intelligence agencies can collect, retain, and share.<ref>{{cite web| title=A Primer on Executive Order 12333: The Mass Surveillance Starlet| last=Jaycox| first=Mark| date=June 2, 2014| url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/06/primer-executive-order-12333-mass-surveillance-starlet| publisher=Electronic Frontier Foundation| location=San Francisco, California| accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===1986 mid-term elections===\n\nIn the [[United States elections, 1986|1986 mid-term elections]], Democrats retained a majority of the House and won control of the Senate for the first time since the 1980 elections. Reagan campaigned hard for congressional Republicans, and an October 1986 New York Times/CBS News Poll had found that Reagan had a 67 percent approval rating. However, Senate Republicans faced a difficult map that year, as they had to defend 22 of the 34 seats up for election. Republican losses in the Senate were concentrated in the South and in the farm states.<ref name=\"1986midterms\">{{cite news|last1=Dionne, Jr.|first1=E.J.|title=ELECTIONS; DEMOCRATS GAIN CONTROL OF SENATE, DRAWING VOTES OF REAGAN'S BACKERS; CUOMO AND D'AMATO ARE EASY VICTORS; WHAT AWAITS CONGRESS; BROAD G.O.P. LOSSES|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/05/us/elections-democrats-gain-control-senate-drawing-votes-reagan-s-backers-cuomo-d.html|accessdate=13 May 2018|work=New York Times|date=1986}}</ref> The Republican loss of the Senate precluded the possibility of further major conservative legislation during the Reagan administration.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Busch|first1=Andrew|title=Horses in Midstream|date=1999|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|pages=126\u2013135}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign affairs==\n{{Main|Foreign policy of the Ronald Reagan administration}}\n\n===Escalation of the Cold War===\n\n{{See also|Cold War (1979\u201385)}}\n[[File:President Reagan addressing British Parliament, London, June 8, 1982.jpg|thumb|As the first U.S. president invited to speak before the [[British Parliament]] (June 8, 1982), Reagan predicted Marxism would end up on the \"[[ash heap of history]]\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Reagan, Ronald.|date=June 8, 1982|url=http://www.historyplace.com/speeches/reagan-parliament.htm|title=Ronald Reagan Address to British Parliament|publisher=The History Place|accessdate=April 19, 2006}}</ref>]]\n\nReagan escalated the Cold War, accelerating a reversal from the policy of d\u00e9tente which had begun in 1979 after the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|Soviet invasion]] of [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/index.cfm?topic_id=1409&fuseaction=topics.event_summary&event_id=12594|title=Towards an International History of the War in Afghanistan, 1979\u201389|accessdate=May 16, 2007|year=2002|publisher=The Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011144144/http://wilsoncenter.org/index.cfm?topic_id=1409&fuseaction=topics.event_summary&event_id=12594|archivedate=October 11, 2007 }}</ref> Reagan feared that the Soviet Union had gained a military advantage over the United States, and the Reagan administration hoped to that heightened military spending would grant the U.S. military superiority and weaken the Soviet economy.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 66\u201367</ref> Reagan ordered a massive buildup of the [[United States Armed Forces]], directing funding to the [[B-1 Lancer]] bomber, the [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 Spirit bomber]], [[cruise missile]]s, the [[LGM-118 Peacekeeper|MX missile]], and the [[600-ship Navy]].<ref>Patterson, p. 200</ref> In response to Soviet deployment of the [[SS-20]], Reagan oversaw [[NATO]]'s deployment of the [[Pershing missile]] in West Germany.<ref>Patterson, pp. 205</ref> The president also strongly denounced the Soviet Union and Communism in moral terms,<ref>Rossinow, p. 67</ref> describing the Soviet Union an \"[[Evil Empire speech|evil empire]].\"<ref name=\"Cannon-315\">Cannon (1991), pp.&nbsp;314\u2013317.</ref> Despite this heavy rhetoric,<ref>G. Thomas Goodnight,  \"Ronald Reagan's re\u2010formulation of the rhetoric of war: Analysis of the 'zero option,' 'evil empire,' and 'star wars' addresses.\" ''Quarterly Journal of Speech'' 72.4 (1986): 390-414.</ref> the Reagan administration continued arms control talks with the Soviet Union in the form of \"[[START I|START]].\" Unlike the \"[[Strategic Arms Limitation Talks|SALT]]\" treaties of the 1970s, which set upper limits on the size of nuclear arsenals, the proposed START treaty would require both sides to reduce their existing nuclear arsenals.<ref>Herring, pp. 868\u2013869</ref>\n\n[[File:Reagan sitting with people from the Afghanistan-Pakistan region in February 1983.jpg|thumb|right|Meeting with leaders of the Afghan [[Mujahideen]] in the Oval Office, 1983]]\n\nIn March 1983, Reagan introduced the [[Strategic Defense Initiative]] (SDI), a defense project that would have used ground- and space-based systems to protect the United States from attack by strategic nuclear ballistic missiles. Reagan believed that this defense shield could make nuclear war impossible.<ref>Beschloss, p. 293</ref> Many scientists and national security experts criticized the project as costly and technologically infeasible, and critics dubbed SDI as \"Star Wars\" in reference to a [[Star Wars|popular film series of the same name]].<ref>Herring, pp. 870\u2013871</ref> Ultimately, the SDI would be canceled in 1993 due to concerns about its cost and effectiveness as well as a changing international situation.<ref>Brands, pp. 725-726</ref> However, the Soviets became concerned about the possible effects SDI would have and viewed its development as a violation of the [[Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty]].<ref>Brands, pp. 581-585</ref> In protest of SDI, the Soviet Union broke off arms control talks, and U.S.-Soviet relations descended to their lowest point since the early 1960s.<ref>Herring, pp. 869\u2013870</ref> The Cold War tensions influenced works of popular culture such as ''[[The Day After]]'', ''[[WarGames]]'', and ''[[99 Luftballons]]'', each of which exhibited the rising public anxiety for the possibility of a nuclear war.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 116\u2013117</ref>\n\n===Reagan Doctrine===\nUnder a policy that came to be known as the [[Reagan Doctrine]], the Reagan administration provided overt and covert aid to anti-communist [[Guerrilla warfare|resistance movements]] in an effort to \"[[rollback]]\" Soviet-backed communist governments in Africa, Asia, and Latin America.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.org/19860301faessay7785/stephen-s-rosenfeld/the-reagan-doctrine-the-guns-of-july.html|title=The Reagan Doctrine: The Guns of July|author =Stephen S. Rosenfeld|journal =[[Foreign Affairs]]|date =Spring 1986|volume=64|issue=4 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165407/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/19860301faessay7785/stephen-s-rosenfeld/the-reagan-doctrine-the-guns-of-july.html|archivedate=September 30, 2007}}</ref> In Eastern Europe, the CIA provided support to the [[Poland|Polish]] opposition group, [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]], ensuring that it stayed afloat during a [[Martial law in Poland|period of martial law]].<ref name=\"auto\">Herring, pp. 883\u2013884</ref> Reagan deployed the CIA's [[Special Activities Division]] to Afghanistan and Pakistan, and the CIA was instrumental in training, equipping, and leading [[Islamic Unity of Afghanistan Mujahideen|Mujahideen]] forces against the Soviet Army in the Soviet\u2013Afghan War.<ref name=\"Crile 2003\">{{Cite book|first=George|last=Crile|title=Charlie Wilson's War: The Extraordinary Story of the Largest Covert Operation in History|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|year=2003|isbn=0-87113-854-9|url=https://archive.org/details/charliewilsonswa00cril}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Pach, Chester|title=The Reagan Doctrine: Principle, Pragmatism, and Policy|journal=Presidential Studies Quarterly|year=2006|volume=36 |issue=1|pages=75\u201388|doi=10.1111/j.1741-5705.2006.00288.x|jstor=27552748}}</ref> By 1987, the United States was sending over $600 million a year, as well as weapons, intelligence, and combat expertise to Afghanistan. The Soviet Union announced it would withdraw from Afghanistan in 1987, but the U.S. was subjected to [[blowback (intelligence)|blowback]] in the form of the [[Taliban]] and [[al-Qaeda]], two groups that arose out of the Mujahideen and that would oppose the United States in future conflicts.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n===Central America and the Caribbean===\n{{see also|Latin America\u2013United States relations}}\n\n[[File:REAGANEugeniaCharles.jpg|thumb|right|Reagan meets with Prime Minister [[Eugenia Charles]] of [[Dominica]] in the [[Oval Office]] about ongoing events in [[Grenada]]]]\n\nThe Reagan administration placed a high priority on the [[Central America]] and the [[Caribbean Sea]], which it saw as a key front in the Cold War. Reagan and his foreign policy team were particularly concerned about the potential influence of [[Cuba]] on countries such as [[Grenada]], [[Nicaragua]], and [[El Salvador]]. To counter the influence of Cuba and the Soviet Union, Reagan launched the [[Caribbean Basin Initiative]], an economic program designed to aid countries opposed to Communism. He also authorized covert measures, such as the arming of Nicaragua's [[Contras]], in order to minimize Cuban and Soviet influence in the region.<ref>Brands, pp. 350-357</ref> The administration provided support to right-wing governments throughout Latin America, disregarding humans rights abuses in countries like [[Argentina]] and El Salvador.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 73, 77\u201379</ref>\n\nIn 1983, pro-Communist forces led a coup in the [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]] island of [[Grenada]]. After learning that Cuban construction workers were building an airfield on Grenada, Reagan dispatched approximately 5,000 U.S. soldiers to [[United States invasion of Grenada|invade Grenada]]. After two days of fighting that resulted in the deaths of nineteen Americans, forty-five Grenadans, and fifty-nine Cubans, the left-wing government of Grenada was overthrown.<ref>Patterson, pp. 205\u2013206</ref> While the invasion enjoyed public support in the United States and Grenada<ref name=Magnuson>{{Cite news| last =Magnuson |first =Ed |title =Getting Back to Normal |newspaper=Time |date =21 November 1983 |url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926318-1,00.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Age of Reagan: The Conservative Counterrevolution: 1980\u20131989|publisher=Crown Forum|isbn=978-1-4000-5357-5|author=Steven F. Hayward|year=2009|author-link=Steven F. Hayward}}</ref> it was criticized by the United Kingdom, Canada and the [[United Nations General Assembly]] as \"a flagrant violation of [[international law]]\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/depts/dhl/resguide/r38.htm |title=United Nations General Assembly resolution 38/7, page 19 |publisher=United Nations |date=2 November 1983}}</ref>\n\n===Iran\u2013Contra affair===\n{{Main|Iran\u2013Contra affair}}\n{{See also|Reagan administration scandals}}\n\nIn 1979, a group of left-wing rebels in Nicaragua known as the [[Sandinistas]] overthrew the president of Nicaragua and installed [[Daniel Ortega]] as the country's leader.<ref>Patterson, pp. 207\u2013208</ref> Fearing that Communists would take over Nicaragua if it remained under the leadership of the Sandinistas, the Reagan administration authorized CIA Director William J. Casey to arm the right-wing [[Contras]]. Congress, which favored negotiations between the Contras and Sandinista, passed the 1982 [[Boland Amendment]], prohibiting the CIA and Defense Department from using their budgets to provide aid to the Contras. Still intent on supporting the Contras, the Reagan administration raised funds for the Contras from private donors and foreign governments.<ref>Weisberg, pp. 128-129</ref> When Congress learned that the CIA had secretly placed [[naval mine]]s in Nicaraguan harbors, Congress passed a second Boland Amendment that barred granting any assistance to the Contras.<ref>Patterson, pp. 208\u2013209</ref>\n\nDuring his second term, Reagan sought to find a way procure the release of seven American hostages held by [[Hezbollah]], a [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] paramilitary group supported by Iran. The Reagan administration decided to sell American arms to Iran, then engaged in the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]], in hopes that Iran would pressure Hezbollah to release the hostages.<ref name=\"weisberg129134\"/> Secretary of Defense Weinberger and Secretary of State Shultz both opposed the arrangement, so it was handled by National Security Advisor [[Robert McFarlane]] and McFarlane's successor, [[John Poindexter]].<ref>Patterson, pp. 209\u2013210</ref> The Reagan administration sold over 2000 missiles to Iran without informing Congress; Hezbollah released four hostages but captured an additional six Americans. On the initiative of [[Oliver North]], an aide on the National Security Council, the Reagan administration redirected the proceeds from the missile sales to the Contras.<ref name=\"weisberg129134\">Weisberg, pp. 129-134</ref> The transactions became public knowledge by early November 1986. Reagan initially denied any wrongdoing, but on November 25 he announced that Poindexter and North had left the administration and that he would form the [[Tower Commission]] to investigate the transactions. A few weeks later, Reagan asked a panel of federal judges to appoint a [[United States Office of the Independent Counsel|special prosecutor]] who would conduct a separate investigation, and the panel chose [[Lawrence Walsh]].<ref>Patterson, pp. 210\u2013211</ref>\n\nThe Tower Commission, chaired by former Republican Senator [[John Tower]], released a report in February 1987 that confirmed that the administration had traded arms for hostages and sent the proceeds of the weapons sales to the Contras. The report laid most of the blame for the operation on North, Poindexter, and McFarlane, but it was also critical of Regan and other White House staffers.<ref>Brands, pp. 646-649</ref> In response to the Tower Commission report, Reagan stated, \"Its findings are honest, convincing and highly critical...As angry as I may be about activities undertaken without my knowledge, I am still accountable for those activities.\"<ref>Brands, pp. 650-653</ref> The [[Iran\u2013Contra scandal]], as it became known, did serious damage to the Reagan presidency, raising questions about Reagan's competency and the wisdom of conservative policies.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 202\u2013204</ref> A poll taken in March 1987 showed that 85 percent of respondents believed that the Reagan administration had engaged in an organized cover-up, and half of the respondents believed that Reagan had been personally involved. The administration's credibility was also badly damaged on the international stage, as it had violated its own arms embargo on Iran.<ref name=\"brands653674\">Brands, pp. 653, 674</ref> Congressional Democrats considered [[Impeachment in the United States|impeaching]], but decided that it would be an unwise use of political capital against a weakened president; Democrats were also somewhat mollified by Reagan's decision to replace Chief of Staff Regan with Howard Baker.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 216\u2013217</ref>\n\nThe investigations into the Iran\u2013Contra scandal continued after Reagan left office, but were effectively halted when President George H. W. Bush pardoned Secretary of Defense Caspar Weinberger before his trial began.<ref>Brinkley, A. (2009). ''American History: A Survey Vol. II'', p. 887, New York: McGraw-Hill</ref> Investigators did not find conclusive proof that Reagan had known about the aid provided to the Contras, but Walsh's report noted that Reagan had \"created the conditions which made possible the crimes committed by others\" and had \"knowingly participated or acquiesced in covering up the scandal.\"<ref>Patterson, pp. 211\u2013212</ref>\n\n===End of the Cold War===\n{{See also|Cold War (1985\u20131991)}}\n[[File:Reagan and Gorbachev signing.jpg|thumb|right|Gorbachev and Reagan sign the [[INF Treaty]] at the White House, 1987]]\n\nThree different [[List of leaders of the Soviet Union|Soviet leaders]] died between 1982 and 1985, leaving the Soviets with an unstable leadership until [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] came to power in 1985.<ref name=\"auto1\">Herring, p. 894</ref> Although the Soviet Union had not accelerated military spending during Reagan's military buildup,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/past/politics/foreign/reagrus.htm|title=Reagan and the Russians|date=February 1994|work=The Atlantic|last1=Lebow |first1=Richard Ned |last2=Stein |first2=Janice Gross |lastauthoramp=yes |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> their large military expenses, in combination with [[Collectivization in the Soviet Union|collectivized agriculture]] and inefficient [[planned economy|planned manufacturing]], were a heavy burden for the [[Economy of the Soviet Union|Soviet economy]].<ref name=\"Gaidar\">{{Cite book|last=Gaidar|first=Yegor|title=Collapse of an Empire: Lessons for Modern Russia|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|year=2007|isbn=978-5-8243-0759-7|language=Russian|pages=190\u2013205}}</ref> Gorbachev was less ideologically rigid than his predecessors, and he believed that the Soviet Union urgently needed economic and political reforms.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In 1986, he introduced his twin reforms of [[perestroika]] and [[glasnost]], which would change the political and economic conditions of the Soviet Union.<ref>Brands, pp. 675\u2013676</ref> Seeking to reduce military expenditures and minimize the possibility of nuclear war, he also sought to re-open negotiations with the United States over arms control.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAs his influence on domestic affairs waned during his second term, Reagan increasingly focused on relations with the Soviet Union.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 225\u2013226</ref> Reagan recognized the change in the direction of the Soviet leadership under Gorbachev, and shifted to diplomacy, with a view to encourage the Soviet leader to pursue substantial arms agreements. Reagan's personal mission was to achieve a world free of nuclear weapons, which according to [[Jack F. Matlock Jr.]], Reagan's ambassador to Moscow, he regarded as \"totally irrational, totally inhumane, good for nothing but killing, possibly destructive of life on earth and civilization.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul Vorbeck Lettow|title=Ronald Reagan And His Quest to Abolish Nuclear Weapons|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=36pYekyje-kC&pg=PA133|year=2006|page=133|isbn=9780812973266}}</ref> Gorbachev and Reagan agreed to meet at the 1985 [[Geneva Summit (1985)|Geneva Summit]], where they issued a joint statement indicating that neither the U.S. nor the Soviet Union would \"seek to achieve military superiority.\"<ref>Rossinow, pp. 225\u2013227</ref> The two leaders began a private correspondence after the summit, and each became increasingly optimistic about arms control negotiations.<ref>Herring, pp. 895\u2013896</ref> Reagan's willingness to negotiate with the Soviets was opposed by many conservatives, including Weinberger; conservative columnist [[George Will]] wrote that Reagan was \"elevating wishful thinking to the status of a political philosophy.\"<ref>Patterson, pp. 214\u2013215</ref>\n\nVarious issues, including intelligence operations performed by both countries and tensions in Germany and Afghanistan, threatened to forestall the possibility of an agreement between the United States and the Soviet Union. Nonetheless, both Gorbachev and Reagan agreed to continue arms control negotiations at the October 1986 [[Reykjav\u00edk Summit]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 228\u2013230</ref> At the summit, Gorbachev and Reagan closed in on an agreement to greatly reduce or eliminate the nuclear stockpiles of both the U.S. and the Soviet Union over a ten-year period, but the deal collapsed due to disagreements regarding SDI development.<ref>Brands, pp. 596\u2013604</ref> Reagan attacked Gorbachev in a [[Tear down this wall!|1987 speech]] delivered in [[West Berlin]], but negotiations continued.<ref name=\"patterson215\">Patterson, p. 215</ref> Gorbachev and Reagan broke the impasse by agreeing to negotiate separate treaties on intermediate nuclear forces (such as [[intermediate-range ballistic missile]]s) and strategic arms (such as [[intercontinental ballistic missile]]s).<ref>Brands, pp. 676-677</ref>\n\nWith the framework for an agreement in place, Reagan and Gorbachev met at the 1987 [[Washington Summit (1987)|Washington Summit]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 234\u2013235</ref> They signed the [[Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty]] (INF Treaty), which committed both signatories to the total abolition of their respective short-range and medium-range missile stockpiles.<ref name=\"patterson215\"/> The agreement marked the first time that the United States and the Soviet Union had committed to the elimination of a type of nuclear weapon, though it provided for the dismantlement of only about one-twentieth of the worldwide nuclear weapon arsenal. The treaty also established an inspections regime designed to ensure that both parties honored the agreement.<ref>Rossinow, p. 236</ref> In addition to the INF Treaty, Reagan and Gorbachev discussed a potential strategic arms treaty, known as START, but SDI continued to be a major point of contention.<ref>Brands, pp. 682-685</ref> In May 1988, the Senate voted 93-to-5 in favor of ratifying the INF Treaty.<ref>Patterson, p. 216</ref>\n\n[[File:President Reagan's Trip to USSR, Walking in Red Square with Mikhail Gorbachev, Moscow, May 31, 1988.webm|thumb|right|President Reagan's Trip to USSR, Walking in Red Square with Mikhail Gorbachev, Moscow, May 31, 1988]]\nThough it was attacked by conservatives like Jesse Helms, the INF Treaty provided a major boost to Reagan's popularity in the aftermath of the Iran\u2013Contra Affair. A new era of trade and openness between the two powers commenced, and the U.S. and the Soviet Union cooperated on international issues such as the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]].<ref>Herring, pp. 897\u2013898</ref> When Reagan visited Moscow for a [[Moscow Summit (1988)|fourth summit]] with Gorbachev in 1988, he was viewed as a celebrity by the Soviets. A journalist asked the president if he still considered the Soviet Union the evil empire. \"No,\" he replied, \"I was talking about another time, another era.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Talbott|first=Strobe|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 5, 1991|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,973554-5,00.html|title=The Summit Goodfellas|accessdate=January 26, 2008}}</ref> At Gorbachev's request, Reagan gave a speech on free markets at the [[Moscow State University]].<ref>Reagan (1990), p. 713</ref> In December 1988, Gorbachev effectively renounced the [[Brezhnev Doctrine]], paving the way for democratization in Eastern Europe.<ref>Herring, pp. 898\u2013899</ref> In November 1989, ten months after Reagan left office, the [[Berlin Wall]] [[Fall of the Berlin Wall|fell]]. The Cold War was unofficially declared over at the [[Malta Summit]] the following month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/3/newsid_4119000/4119950.stm|title=1989: Malta summit ends Cold War|publisher=BBC News|date=December 3, 1984|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East===\n\n====Lebanon====\n\nA [[Lebanese Civil War|civil war]] had broken out in [[Lebanon]] in 1975, and both [[Israel]] and [[Syria]] undertook military action within Lebanon in 1982.<ref>Brands, pp. 366-367</ref> After Israel [[1982 Lebanon War|invaded]] [[Southern Lebanon]], Reagan faced domestic and international pressure to oppose the Israeli invasion, but Reagan was reluctant to openly break Israel. Reagan sympathized with Israeli's desire to defeat [[Palestine Liberation Organization|PLO]] forces that had struck Israel from Lebanon, but he pressured Israel to end its invasion as casualties mounted and Israeli forces approached the Lebanese capital of [[Beirut]].<ref>Brands, pp. 382-385</ref> American diplomat [[Philip Habib]] arranged a cease-fire in which Israel, Syria, and the PLO, all agreed to evacuate their forces from Lebanon. As Israel delayed a full withdrawal and violence continued in Lebanon, Reagan arranged for a [[Multinational Force in Lebanon|multinational force]], including [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marines]], to serve as peacekeepers in Lebanon.<ref>Brands, pp. 386-389</ref> In October 1983, [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings|two nearly-simultaneous bombings]] in Beirut killed 241 American soldiers and 58 French soldiers.<ref>Brands, pp. 394-395</ref> The international peacekeeping force was withdrawn from Lebanon in 1984. In reaction to the role Israel and the United States played in the Lebanese Civil War, a [[Shia Islam|Shia]] militant group known as [[Hezbollah]] began to take American hostages, holding eight Americans by the middle of 1985.<ref>Brands, pp. 488-491</ref> The Reagan administration's attempts to release these hostages would be a major component of the Iran-Contra Scandal. In response to the U.S. intervention in Lebanon, the Defense Department developed the \"[[Powell Doctrine]],\" which stated that the U.S. should intervene militarily as a last resort and should set clear and limited goals in such interventions.<ref>Herring, p. 875</ref> Though termed the Powell doctrine, the policy was originally developed by Secretary of Defense Weinberger, who was influenced not only by Lebanon but also by the experience of the Vietnam War.<ref>Patterson, pp. 200\u2013201</ref>\n\n====Libya bombing====\n{{Main|1986 United States bombing of Libya}}\n[[File:President Reagan and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at Camp David 1986.jpg|thumb|British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] (here walking with Reagan at [[Camp David]] in 1986) granted the U.S. use of British airbases to launch the Libya attack]]\n\nRelations between Libya and the United States under President Reagan were continually contentious, beginning with the [[Gulf of Sidra incident (1981)|Gulf of Sidra incident]] in 1981; by 1982, Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] was considered by the CIA to be, along with USSR leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]] and Cuban leader [[Fidel Castro]], part of a group known as the \"unholy trinity\" and was also labeled as \"our international public enemy number one\" by a CIA official.<ref name=iokp;>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,925697,00.htm | title= Libya: Fury in the Isolation Ward|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 23, 1982|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref> These tensions were later revived in early April 1986, when [[1986 Berlin discotheque bombing|a bomb exploded in a West Berlin discoth\u00e8que]], resulting in the injury of 63 American military personnel and death of one serviceman. Stating that there was \"irrefutable proof\" that Libya had directed the \"terrorist bombing,\" Reagan authorized the use of force against the country. In the late evening of April 15, 1986, the United States launched a series of [[airstrike]]s on ground targets in Libya.<ref name=\"gs-libya\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/el_dorado_canyon.htm|title=Operation El Dorado Canyon|publisher=GlobalSecurity.org|date=April 25, 2005|accessdate=April 19, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"4-15\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/15/newsid_3975000/3975455.stm|title=1986:US Launches air-strike on Libya|accessdate=April 19, 2008|date=April 15, 2008|publisher=BBC News }}</ref>\n\nBritain's prime minister, Margaret Thatcher, allowed the U.S. Air Force to use Britain's air bases to launch the attack, on the justification that the UK was supporting America's right to self-defense under Article 51 of the [[United Nations Charter]].<ref name=\"4-15\" /> The attack was designed to halt Gaddafi's \"ability to export terrorism,\" offering him \"incentives and reasons to alter his criminal behavior.\"<ref name=\"gs-libya\" /> The president addressed the nation from the [[Oval Office]] after the attacks had commenced, stating, \"When our citizens are attacked or abused anywhere in the world on the direct orders of hostile regimes, we will respond so long as I'm in this office.\"<ref name=\"4-15\" /> The attack was condemned by many countries. By a vote of 79 in favor to 28 against with 33 abstentions, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] adopted resolution 41/38 which \"condemns the military attack perpetrated against the Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya on April 15, 1986, which constitutes a violation of the Charter of the United Nations and of international law.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/documents/ga/res/41/a41r038.htm |title=A/RES/41/38 November 20, 1986 |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===South Africa===\n\n{{main|South Africa under apartheid}}\n[[File:Reagan with Desmond TutuC26199-10.jpg|thumb|President Reagan meeting with South African anti-apartheid activist [[Desmond Tutu]] in 1984]]\nDuring Ronald Reagan's presidency [[South Africa]] continued to use a non-democratic system of government based on racial discrimination, known as [[apartheid]], in which the minority of white South Africans exerted nearly complete legal control over the lives of the non-white majority of the citizens. In the early 1980s the issue had moved to the center of international attention as a result of events in the townships and outcry at the death of [[Stephen Biko]]. Reagan administration policy called for \"[[constructive engagement]]\" with the apartheid government of South Africa. In opposition to the condemnations issued by the U.S. Congress and public demands for diplomatic or economic sanctions, Reagan made relatively minor criticisms of the regime, which was otherwise internationally isolated, and the U.S. granted recognition to the government. South Africa's military was then engaged in an occupation of [[Namibia]] and [[proxy war]]s in several neighboring countries, in alliance with Savimbi's UNITA. Reagan administration officials saw the apartheid government as a key anti-communist ally.<ref>[http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/embargo/rknight840403.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701053013/http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/embargo/rknight840403.htm |date=July 1, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nFinding the Reagan Administration unresponsive to its calls for more stringent economic sanctions, anti-apartheid activists undertook a [[Disinvestment from South Africa|divestment campaign]], aimed at moving individuals and institutions to sell their holdings in companies doing business in South Africa. By late 1985, facing escalating public and congressional opposition to his administration's tolerant attitude toward the South African government's policy of apartheid, Reagan made an \"abrupt reversal\" on the issue and proposed sanctions on the South African government, including an [[arms embargo]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=William E. |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,959843,00.html |title=South Africa Reagan's Abrupt Reversal |publisher=TIME |date=September 16, 1985 |accessdate=April 14, 2014 }}</ref>  However, these sanctions were seen as weak by anti-apartheid activists,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZZopAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AYQDAAAAIBAJ&dq=anti-apartheid+act+reagan&pg=4676,4983327|title=The Deseret News - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref> and as insufficient by the president's opponents in Congress, including 81 House Republicans. In August 1986, Congress approved the [[Comprehensive Anti-Apartheid Act]], which included tougher sanctions. Reagan vetoed the act, but this was overridden by a bipartisan effort in Congress.<ref>{{cite web| last=Glass| first=Andrew| title=House overrides Reagan apartheid veto, Sept. 29, 1986| date=September 27, 2017| url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/29/house-overrides-reagan-apartheid-veto-sept-29-1986-243169| publisher=Politico| accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> By 1990, under Reagan's successor George H. W. Bush, the new South African government of [[F. W. de Klerk]] was introducing widespread reforms, though the Bush administration argued that this was not a result of the tougher sanctions.<ref>George Gedda, {{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iOJLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uIsDAAAAIBAJ&dq=bush+sanctions+south+africa+1989&pg=4903,1578476|title=Analysts differ on sanctions tie to apartheid|website=news.google.com}}, ''The Free Lance-Star'' (Jul 11, 1991)</ref>\n\n===Free trade===\nDuring his 1980 presidential campaign, Reagan proposed the creation of a [[Single market|common market]] in North America. Once in office, Reagan signed the [[Trade and Tariff Act of 1984]], which granted the president \"[[fast track (trade)|fast track]]\" authority in negotiating [[United States free-trade agreements|free trade agreements]].<ref name=\"kamadeo1\"/> In 1985, Reagan signed the [[Israel\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement]], the first bilateral free trade agreement in U.S. history.<ref name=\"mtolchin1\">{{cite news|last1=Tolchin|first1=Martin|title=U.S. Signs Trade Pact With Israel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/23/business/us-signs-trade-pact-with-israel.html|accessdate=28 November 2017|work=New York Times|date=23 April 1985}}</ref> In 1988, Reagan and [[Canada|Canadian]] Prime Minister [[Brian Mulroney]] signed the [[Canada\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement]], which greatly reduced trade barriers between the United States and Canada. This trade pact would serve as the foundation for the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] among the United States, Canada, and [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"kamadeo1\">{{cite web|last1=Amadeo|first1=Kimberly|title=History of NAFTA and Its Purpose|url=https://www.thebalance.com/history-of-nafta-3306272|website=The Balance|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===International travel===\n{{Main|List of international presidential trips made by Ronald Reagan}}\n[[File:Ronald Reagan Overseas Visits.svg|thumb|World map highlighting countries visited by Ronald Reagan while president]]\n\nReagan made 25 international trips to 26 different countries on four [[continents]]&mdash;Europe, Asia, North America, and South America&mdash;during his presidency.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/president/reagan-ronald|title= Travels of President Ronald Reagan|publisher= U.S. Department of State Office of the Historian}}</ref> He made seven trips to continental Europe, three to Asia and one to South America. He is perhaps best remembered for his speeches at the 40th anniversary of the [[Normandy landings]], for his impassioned speech at the [[Berlin Wall]], his summit meetings with [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], and riding horses with [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] at Windsor Park.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n==Age and health==\n[[File:Ronald Reagan February 11, 1985.jpg|thumb|Reagan in February 1985]]\nAt the time of his inauguration, Reagan was the oldest person to be inaugurated as President (age 69).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.potus.com/presidential-facts/age-at-inauguration/|title=Age at Inauguration {{!}} Presidents of the United States (POTUS)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> He remains the oldest person to have held the office; he had reached the age of 77 when his second term ended. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reaganlibrary.gov/sreference/the-reagan-presidency|title=The Reagan Presidency {{!}} Ronald Reagan Presidential Library - National Archives and Records Administration|website=www.reaganlibrary.gov|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> Reagan's health became a concern{{To whom?|date=November 2018}} at times during his presidency.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Former White House correspondent [[Lesley Stahl]] later wrote that she and other reporters noticed what might have been early symptoms of Reagan's later [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref name=\"american chronicle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/6883|work=American Chronicle |date=March 15, 2006|title=Happy Anniversary to the first scheduled presidential press conference - 93 years young! |first=Robert |last=Rouse}}</ref> She said that on her last day on the beat, Reagan spoke to her for a few moments and did not seem to know who she was before returning to his normal behavior.<ref name=\"american chronicle\"/>{{dead link|date=November 2018}} However, Reagan's primary physician, Dr. John Hutton, has said that Reagan \"absolutely\" did not \"show any signs of dementia or Alzheimer's\" during his presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F02E1DE133DF936A35753C1A961958260|title=Reagan's Twilight&nbsp;\u2013 A special report; A President Fades into a World Apart |accessdate=2008-06-18|author=Altman, Lawrence K|date=October 5, 1997|work=The New York Times}}</ref> His doctors have noted that he began exhibiting Alzheimer's symptoms only after he left the White House.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DE5D61030F936A25755C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|title=The Doctors World; A Recollection of Early Questions About Reagan's Health|author=Altman, Lawrence K., M.D.|date=June 15, 2004 |accessdate=2008-11-11}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 1985, Reagan underwent surgery to remove [[polyp (medicine)|polyps]] from his [[colon (anatomy)|colon]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/12/18/us/reagan-s-health-problems.html|title=Reagan's Health Problems|date=1986-12-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> causing the first-ever invocation of the [[Acting President of the United States|Acting President]] clause of the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|25th Amendment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/news/reagan-health-25th-amendment|title=Reagan Aides Once Raised the Possibility of Invoking the 25th Amendment|last=Little|first=Becky|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> On January 5, 1987, Reagan underwent surgery for [[prostate cancer]] which caused further worries about his health, but which significantly raised public awareness of this \"silent killer\".{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Presidential elections==\n===1984 election===\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1984.svg|right|thumb|1984 electoral vote results]]\n{{Main|Ronald Reagan 1984 presidential campaign|1984 United States presidential election}}\n\nReagan's approval ratings fell after his first year in office, but they bounced back when the United States began to emerge from recession in 1983.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 620-621</ref> The leading candidates in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1984|1984 Democratic presidential primaries]] were former Vice President [[Walter Mondale]], Senator [[Gary Hart]] of Colorado, and African-American civil rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]]. Though Hart won several primaries, Mondale ultimately won the nomination. Down in the polls, Mondale [[Democratic Party vice presidential candidate selection, 1984|selected]] Congresswoman [[Geraldine Ferraro]] as his running mate in hopes of galvanizing support for his campaign, thus making Ferraro the first female major party vice presidential nominee in U.S. history.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 166\u2013169, 173</ref> In accepting the Democratic nomination, Mondale attacked Reagan's policies regarding the environment, Social Security, nuclear arms, civil rights, and other issues, stating that the Reagan administration was \"of the rich, by the rich, and for the rich.\"<ref>Rossinow, pp. 171\u2013172</ref> He also criticized the federal debt accumulated under Reagan, stating, \"...The budget will be squeezed. Taxes will go up. And anyone who says they won't is not telling the truth to the American people.\"<ref name=\"Brands, pp. 452-453\"/>\n\nReagan, meanwhile, generally declined to offer new legislative proposals for his re-election campaign, instead focusing on events like the U.S.-hosted [[1984 Summer Olympics]] and the 40th anniversary of the [[Normandy landings]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 169\u2013170, 176</ref> Reagan's ability to perform the duties of president for another term was questioned by some observers, especially after a weak performance in the first presidential debate. His apparent confused and forgetful behavior was evident to his supporters; they had previously known him clever and witty. Rumors began to circulate that he had [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/editors200410040912.asp|title=The Debate: Mondale vs. Reagan|work=National Review|date=October 4, 2004|accessdate=May 25, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416191912/http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/editors200410040912.asp <!-- Added by H3llBot -->|archivedate=April 16, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/debatingourdestiny/newshour/84_1stprez-analysis.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010218175006/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/debatingourdestiny/newshour/84_1stprez-analysis.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 18, 2001|title=Reaction to first Mondale/Reagan debate|publisher=PBS|date=October 8, 1984|accessdate=December 31, 2007}}</ref> Reagan rebounded in the second debate, and confronted questions about his age, quipping, \"I will not make age an issue of this campaign. I am not going to exploit, for political purposes, my opponent's youth and inexperience,\" which generated applause and laughter, even from Mondale himself.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cgi.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/debates/history/1984/|title=1984 Presidential Debates|publisher=CNN|accessdate=May 25, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308065739/http://cgi.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/debates/history/1984/|archivedate=March 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPublic opinion polling consistently showed a Reagan lead in the 1984 campaign, and Mondale was unable to shake up the race.<ref>Rossinow, p. 173</ref> In the end, Reagan won re-election, winning 49 of 50 states.<ref name=\"84 results\" /> Mondale carried only his home state of Minnesota and the District of Columbia. Reagan won a record 525 electoral votes,<ref name=\"pres\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/pressketch.html|title=The Reagan Presidency|accessdate=April 19, 2008|publisher=Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation}}</ref> and received 59% of the popular vote to Mondale's 41%.<ref name=\"84 results\">{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1984|title=1984 Presidential Election Results|publisher=David Leip|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref> Compared to 1980, Reagan's strongest gains came among white Southern voters, and he also performed particularly well among Catholic voters, voters between the ages of eighteen and twenty-nine, and voters over the age of sixty.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 173\u2013174</ref> In the concurrent congressional elections, Republicans retained control of the Senate and Democrats retained control of the House.<ref>Patterson, p. 190</ref>\n\n===1988 election===\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1988.svg|right|thumb|1988 electoral vote results]]\n\nReagan remained publicly neutral in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1988|1988 Republican presidential primaries]], but privately supported Vice President Bush over Senator [[Bob Dole]]. The [[1988 Republican National Convention]], which nominated Bush for president, also acted as a celebration of Reagan's presidency.<ref>Brands, pp. 697-698</ref> Democrats nominated [[Michael Dukakis]], the liberal Governor of Massachusetts. Following the [[1988 Democratic National Convention]], Dukakis led the polls by seventeen points, but Bush, aided by the INF Treaty and the strong economy, closed the gap as the election neared. Democrats tried to link Bush to the Iran-Contra Scandal, but Bush claimed that he had not been involved. The GOP effectively cast Dukakis as \"soft\" on crime and foreign policy issues, seizing on Dukakis's pardon of [[Willie Horton]] and his dispassionate response to a question regarding the [[capital punishment|death penalty]]. In the [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential election]], Bush defeated Dukakis, taking 53.4 percent of the popular vote and 426 electoral votes. The election saw the lowest turnout of eligible voters since [[1924 United States presidential election|1924]]. In the concurrent congressional elections, Democrats retained control of the House and the Senate.<ref>Patterson, pp. 220\u2013225</ref> In large part due to his handling of relations with the Soviet Union, Reagan left office with an approval rating of sixty-eight percent.<ref>Patterson, p. 217</ref>\n\n==Evaluation and legacy==\n[[File:Gallup Poll-Approval Rating-Ronald Reagan.png|thumb|upright=1.5|Graph of Reagan's approval ratings in [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] polls]]\n\nSince Reagan left office in 1989, substantial debate has occurred among scholars, historians, and the general public surrounding his legacy.<ref>Andrew L. Johns, ed., ''A Companion to Ronald Reagan'' (Wiley-Blackwell, 2015).</ref> Supporters have pointed to a more efficient and prosperous economy as a result of Reagan's economic policies,<ref>Hayward, pp.&nbsp;635\u2013638</ref> foreign policy triumphs including a peaceful end to the Cold War,<ref>Beschloss, p. 324</ref> and a restoration of American pride and morale.<ref name=\"cannon746\">Cannon (1991, 2000), p. 746</ref> Proponents also argue Reagan restored faith in the American Dream<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/OPINION/02/02/rollins.reagan/|title=Ronald Reagan restored faith in America|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> after a decline in American confidence and self-respect under Jimmy Carter's perceived weak leadership, particularly during the [[Iran hostage crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipset|first1=Seymour Martin|last2=Schneider|first2=William|title=The Decline of Confidence in American Institutions|url=http://www.planethan.com/drupal/sites/default/files/The%20Decline%20of%20Confidence%20in%20American%20Institutions%20%20By%20Lipset%20Seymour%20Martin%20and%20Schneider%20William%20Political%20Science%20Quarterly%20Fall83%20Vol%2098%20Issue%203%20p379.pdf|work=Political Science Quarterly|accessdate=July 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822132334/http://www.planethan.com/drupal/sites/default/files/The%20Decline%20of%20Confidence%20in%20American%20Institutions%20%20By%20Lipset%20Seymour%20Martin%20and%20Schneider%20William%20Political%20Science%20Quarterly%20Fall83%20Vol%2098%20Issue%203%20p379.pdf|archivedate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> Reagan remains an important symbol of American conservatism, much in the same way that Franklin Roosevelt continued to serve as a symbol of liberalism long after his own death.<ref>Rossinow, p. 293</ref>\n\nCritics contend that Reagan's economic policies resulted in rising budget deficits,<ref name=\"Cannon128\">Cannon (2001), p. 128</ref> a wider [[Wealth inequality in the United States|gap in wealth]], and an increase in [[homelessness]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/reagans-real-legacy/ |title=Reagan's Real Legacy |last=Dreier |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Dreier |date=2011-02-04 |website=[[The Nation]] |language=en-US |access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref> Liberals especially disapproved of Reagan's simultaneous tax cuts for the wealthy and benefit cuts for the poor.<ref>Patterson, p. 158</ref> Some critics assert that the Iran\u2013Contra affair lowered American credibility.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilman|first=Larry|url=http://www.espionageinfo.com/Int-Ke/Iran-Contra-Affair.html|title=Iran-Contra Affair|publisher=Advameg|accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref> In his popular book, ''The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers'', historian [[Paul Kennedy]] argued that Reagan's high level of defense would eventually lead to the decline of the United States as a [[great power]].<ref>Patterson, p. 202</ref> Reagan's leadership and understanding of issues has also been questioned, and even some members of the administration criticized Reagan's passive demeanor during meetings with staff and cabinet members.<ref>Patterson, pp. 160-161</ref> [[Richard Pipes]], a member of the National Security Council, criticized Reagan as \"really lost, out of his depth, uncomfortable\" at NSC meetings.<ref>Leffler, p. 349</ref> Another NSC member, [[Colin Powell]], criticized Reagan's \"passive management style [that] placed a tremendous burden on us.\u201d<ref>Pemberton, p. 151</ref>\n\nDespite the continuing debate surrounding his legacy, many conservative and liberal scholars agree that Reagan has been one of the most influential presidents since Franklin Roosevelt, leaving his imprint on American politics, diplomacy, culture, and economics through his effective communication, dedicated patriotism and pragmatic compromising.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://millercenter.org/president/reagan/essays/biography/8|title=American President|accessdate=October 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011080053/http://millercenter.org/president/reagan/essays/biography/8|archivedate=October 11, 2014}}</ref> Since he left office, historians have reached a consensus,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Henry|first1=David|title=Ronald Reagan and the 1980s: Perceptions, Policies, Legacies. Ed. by Cheryl Hudson and Gareth Davies. (New York: Palgrave Macmillan, 2008. xiv, 268 pp. $84.95, ISBN 978-0-230-60302-8.)|journal=[[The Journal of American History]]|date=December 2009|volume=96|issue=3|pages=933\u2013934|doi=10.1093/jahist/96.3.933|jstor=25622627}}</ref> as summarized by British historian M. J. Heale, who finds that scholars now concur that Reagan rehabilitated conservatism, turned the nation to the right, practiced a considerably pragmatic conservatism that balanced ideology and the constraints of politics, revived faith in the presidency and in [[American exceptionalism]], and contributed to victory in the Cold War.<ref>Heale, M.J. in Cheryl Hudson and Gareth Davies, eds. ''Ronald Reagan and the 1980s: Perceptions, Policies, Legacies'' (2008) Palgrave Macmillan {{ISBN|0-230-60302-5}} p. 250</ref> [[Hugh Heclo]] argues that Reagan himself failed to roll back the [[welfare state]], but that he contributed to a shift in attitudes that led to the defeat of efforts to further expand the welfare state.<ref>Heclo, pp. 558\u2013560</ref> Heclo further argues that Reagan's presidency made American voters and political leaders more tolerant of deficits and more opposed to taxation.<ref>Heclo, pp. 562\u2013563</ref> In 2017, a C-SPAN survey of scholars ranked Reagan as the ninth greatest president.<ref>See [https://static.c-span.org/assets/documents/presidentSurvey/2017%20C-SPAN%20Presidential%20Survey%20Scores%20and%20Ranks%20FINAL.PDF \"S-SPAN 2017 Survey of Presidential Leadership\" '' C-SPAN'']</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Andrew L. Johns, ed.|title=A Companion to Ronald Reagan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aaueBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2|year=2015|publisher=Wiley|pages=1\u20132|isbn=9781118607824}}</ref> A 2018 poll of the [[American Political Science Association]]\u2019s Presidents and Executive Politics section also ranked Reagan as the ninth greatest president.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rottinghaus|first1=Brandon|last2=Vaughn|first2=Justin S.|title=How Does Trump Stack Up Against the Best \u2014 and Worst \u2014 Presidents?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/02/19/opinion/how-does-trump-stack-up-against-the-best-and-worst-presidents.html/|accessdate=14 May 2018|work=New York Times|date=19 February 2018}}</ref> A 2006 poll of historians ranked the Iran-Contra affair as the ninth-worst mistake made by a sitting American president.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scholars rate worst presidential errors |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/2006-02-18-presidential-goofs_x.htm |accessdate=31 August 2018 |agency=AP |publisher=USA Today |date=18 February 2006}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1980s|United States|Politics|Conservatism}}\n* [[History of the United States (1980\u201391)]]\n* [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher]]\n* [[Ronald Reagan Presidential Library]], Simi Valley, California\n* [[600-ship Navy]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Brands|first1=H.W.|title=Reagan: The Life|date=2015|publisher=Doubleday|location=New York}}\n* {{cite book|last = Beschloss|first=Michael|title=Presidential Courage: Brave Leaders and How They Changed America 1789\u20131989|url = https://archive.org/details/presidentialcour00besc|url-access = registration|year =2007|publisher=Simon & Schuster}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cannon|first=Lou|authorlink=Lou Cannon|title=President Reagan: The Role of a Lifetime|year=2000|publisher=Public Affairs|location=New York|isbn=1-891620-91-6|url=https://archive.org/details/presidentreagan000cann}}\n* {{cite book | title = Ronald Reagan: The Presidential Portfolio: A History Illustrated from the Collection of the Ronald Reagan Library and Museum | first = Lou | last = Cannon | authorlink = Lou Cannon | author2 = Michael Beschloss | publisher = PublicAffairs | isbn = 1-891620-84-3 | year = 2001 | url = https://archive.org/details/ronaldreaganpres00cann }}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Heclo|first1=Hugh|title=The Mixed Legacies of Ronald Reagan|journal=Presidential Studies Quarterly|date=2008|volume=38|issue=4|pages=555\u2013574|doi=10.1111/j.1741-5705.2008.02664.x|jstor=41219701}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Herring|first1=George C.|title=From Colony to Superpower; U.S. Foreign Relations Since 1776|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-507822-0|url=https://archive.org/details/fromcolonytosupe00herr}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Leffler|first1=Melvyn P.|title=For the Soul of Mankind: the United States, the Soviet Union, and the Cold War|url=https://archive.org/details/forsoulofmankind00leff|url-access=registration|date=2007|publisher=Hill and Wang}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Leuchtenberg|first1=William E.|title=The American President: From Teddy Roosevelt to Bill Clinton|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195176162}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Patterson|first1=James|title=Restless Giant: The United States from Watergate to Bush v. Gore|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195122169|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/restlessgiantuni00patt_0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Pemberton|first1=William E.|title=Exit with Honor: The Life and Presidency of Ronald Reagan|date=1997|publisher=Routledge}}\n* {{cite book|last= Reagan|first= Ronald|title= An American Life|year= 1990|publisher= Simon and Schuster|location= New York|isbn= 0-7434-0025-9|url= https://archive.org/details/americanlife00reag_0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rossinow|first1=Douglas C.|title=The Reagan Era: A History of the 1980s|date=2015|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231538657}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Weisberg|first1=Jacob|title=Ronald Reagan|date=2016|publisher=Times Books|isbn=978-0-8050-9728-3}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wilentz|first1=Sean|title=The Age of Reagan: A History, 1974-2008|date=2008|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-074480-9|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofreaganhisto00wile}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Main|Ronald Reagan bibliography}}\n\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Brownlee, W. Elliot and Hugh Davis Graham, eds. ''The Reagan Presidency: Pragmatic Conservatism and Its Legacies'' (2003)\n* Coleman, Bradley Lynn and Kyle Longley, eds. ''Reagan and the World: Leadership and National Security, 1981\u20131989'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2017), 319 pp.  essays by scholars\n* {{cite book |last= Diggins |first= John Patrick |title= Ronald Reagan: Fate, Freedom, and the Making of History |url= https://archive.org/details/ronaldreaganfate00digg |url-access= registration | year= 2007| publisher= W. W. Norton |location= New York|isbn= }}\n* Ehrman, John. ''The Eighties: America in the Age of Reagan.'' (2005)\n* Graff, Henry F., ed. ''The Presidents: A Reference History'' (3rd ed. 2002)\n* Hayward, Steven F. ''The Age of Reagan: The Conservative Counterrevolution, 1980\u20131989'' (2010), highly favorable\n* Hertsgaard, Mark. (1988) ''On Bended Knee: The Press and the Reagan Presidency''. New York, New York: Farrar Straus and Giroux.\n* Hill,  Dilys M. and Raymond A. Moore, eds. ''The Reagan Presidency'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 1990) essays by scholars; 252pp.\n* {{cite book |last= Matlock |first= Jack |title= Reagan and Gorbachev: How the Cold War Ended |year= 2004 |publisher= Random House |location= New York |isbn= 0-679-46323-2 |url= https://archive.org/details/reagangorbachevh00matl }}\n* {{cite book |last= Reeves |first= Richard |authorlink= Richard Reeves (American writer) |title= President Reagan: The Triumph of Imagination |year= 2005 |publisher= Simon & Schuster |location= New York |isbn= 0-7432-3022-1 |url= https://archive.org/details/presidentreagant00reev }}\n* Service, Robert. ''The End of the Cold War: 1985-1991'' (2015) [https://www.amazon.com/The-End-Cold-War-1985-1991/dp/1610394992/  excerpt]\n* {{cite book |last= Walsh |first= Kenneth |title= Ronald Reagan |year= 1997 |publisher= Random House Value Publishing, Inc. |location= New York |isbn= 0-517-20078-3 |url= https://archive.org/details/ronaldreagan00wals }}\n{{refend}}\n===Historiography===\n* Johns, Andrew L., ed. ''A Companion to Ronald Reagan'' (Wiley-Blackwell, 2015). xiv, 682 pp.; topical essays by scholars emphasizing historiography; [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/book/10.1002/9781118607770 contents free at many libraries]\n* Kengor, Paul. \"Reagan among the professors: His surprising reputation.\" ''Policy Review'' 98 (1999): 15+. Reports that \" many articles in the top journals have been fair, as have a number of influential books...from respected historians, presidential scholars, and political scientists -- people who were not Reagan supporters and are certainly not right-wingers.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.reaganlibrary.com/ Reagan Library]\n* [https://www.whitehouse.gov/1600/presidents/ronaldreagan Ronald Reagan biography on whitehouse.gov]\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/reagan-era/ Reagan Era] study guide, timeline, quotes, trivia, teacher resources\n\n{{Ronald Reagan}}\n{{US Presidential Administrations}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of Ronald Reagan| ]]\n[[Category:Presidencies of the United States|Reagan, Ronald]]\n[[Category:1980s in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1980\u201391)]]\n[[Category:Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1989 disestablishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|Period of the United States government}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n{{for timeline}}\n{{Infobox administration\n| image = Official Portrait of President Reagan 1981.jpg\n| name = Presidency of Ronald Reagan\n| term_start = January 20, 1981\n| term_end = January 20, 1989\n| president = Ronald Reagan\n| president_link = President of the United States\n| cabinet = ''[[#Administration|See list]]''\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| election = [[1980 United States presidential election|1980]], [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]]\n| seat = [[White House]]\n| predecessor = [[Presidency of Jimmy Carter|Jimmy Carter]]\n| successor = [[Presidency of George H. W. Bush|George H. W. Bush]]\n| seal = Seal of the President of the United States.svg\n| seal_caption = Seal of the President\n| library_url = https://www.reaganlibrary.gov/\n}}\n{{Ronald Reagan series}}\nThe '''presidency of Ronald Reagan''' began at noon [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] on January 20, 1981, when [[Ronald Reagan]] was [[First inauguration of Ronald Reagan|inaugurated]] as the [[List of Presidents of the United States|40th]] [[President of the United States]], and ended on January 20, 1989. Reagan, a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] from [[California]], took office following a landslide victory over [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[incumbent]] President [[Jimmy Carter]] in the [[1980 United States presidential election|1980 presidential election]]. Reagan was succeeded by his Vice President, [[George H. W. Bush]], who won the [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential election]] with Reagan's support. Reagan's 1980 election resulted from a dramatic [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative shift to the right]] in American politics, including a loss of confidence in [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]], [[New Deal]], and [[Great Society]] programs and priorities that had dominated the national agenda since the 1930s.\n\nDomestically, the Reagan administration enacted a [[Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981|major tax cut]], sought to cut non-military spending, and eliminated federal regulations. The administration's economic policies, known as \"[[Reaganomics]]\", were inspired by [[supply-side economics]]. The combination of tax cuts and an increase in defense spending led to budget deficits, and the [[National debt of the United States|federal debt]] increased significantly during Reagan's tenure. Reagan signed the [[Tax Reform Act of 1986]] (which simplified the tax code by reducing rates and removing several tax breaks) and the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986]] (which enacted sweeping changes to U.S. immigration law and granted amnesty to three million [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants]]). Reagan also appointed more [[Federal judiciary of the United States|federal judges]] than any other president, including four [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justices.\n\nReagan's [[Foreign policy of the Ronald Reagan administration|foreign policy]] stance was resolutely [[anti-communism|anti-communist]]; its plan of action, known as the [[Reagan Doctrine]], sought to [[rollback|roll back]] the global influence of the [[Soviet Union]] in an attempt to end the Cold War. Under this doctrine, the Reagan administration initiated a massive buildup of the United States military; promoted new technologies such as missile defense systems; and, in 1983, undertook an [[invasion of Grenada]], the first major overseas action by U.S. troops since the end of the [[Vietnam War]]. The administration also created controversy by granting [[United States and state-sponsored terrorism|aid to paramilitary forces]] seeking to overthrow leftist governments, particularly in war-torn [[Central America]] and [[Afghanistan]]. Specifically, the Reagan administration engaged in covert arms sales to [[Iran]] to fund [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in Nicaragua that were fighting to overthrow their nation's socialist government; the resulting [[Iran\u2013Contra affair|scandal]] led to the conviction or resignation of several administration officials. During Reagan's second term, he sought closer relations with Soviet leader [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], and the two leaders signed a major [[arms control]] agreement known as the [[Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty|INF Treaty]].\n\nLeaving office in 1989, Reagan held an approval rating of 68%. This rating matches the approval ratings of [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[Bill Clinton]] as the highest rating for a departing president in the modern era.<ref>{{cite web|title = A Look Back At The Polls|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/news/a-look-back-at-the-polls/|publisher = CBS News|access-date = May 15, 2015}}</ref> Historians and political scientists generally [[Historical rankings of presidents of the United States|rank]] Reagan as an above-average president. Due to Reagan's impact on public discourse and advocacy of [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatism]], some historians have described the period during and after his presidency as the [[Reagan Era]].\n\n==Conservative shift in politics==\n{{Further|Conservatism in the United States|Reagan Era}}\n\nEven prior to becoming president, Reagan was the leader of a dramatic conservative shift that undercut many of the domestic and foreign policies that had dominated the national agenda for decades.<ref>Bruce J. Schulman and Julian E. Zelizer, eds. ''Rightward Bound: Making America Conservative in the 1970s'' (Harvard UP, 2008) pp 1-10.</ref><ref>Andrew Busch, ''Reagan's victory: the presidential election of 1980 and the rise of the right'' (UP of Kansas, 2005).</ref> A major factor in the rise of conservatism was the growing distrust of government in the aftermath of the [[Watergate scandal]]. While distrust of high officials had been an American characteristic for two centuries, Watergate engendered heightened levels of suspicion and encouraged the media to engage in a vigorous search for scandals.<ref>J. Lull, and S. Hinerman, \"The search for scandal' in J. Lull & S. Hinerman, eds. ''Media scandals: Morality and desire in the popular culture marketplace'' (1997) pp. 1-33.</ref> An unexpected new factor was the emergence of the [[Christian right|religious right]] as a cohesive political force that gave strong support to conservatism.<ref>Paul Boyer, \"The Evangelical Resurgence in 1970s American Protestantism\" in Schulman and Zelizer, eds. ''Rightward bound'' pp 29-51.:</ref><ref>Stephen D. Johnson and Joseph B. Tamney, \"The Christian Right and the 1980 presidential election.\" ''Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion'' (1982) 21#2: 123-131. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1385498 online]</ref>\n\nOther factors in the rise of the conservative movement the emergence of a \"[[culture war]]\" as a triangular battle among conservatives, traditional liberals, and the [[New Left]], involving such issues as individual freedom, divorce, sexual freedom, abortion, and homosexuality.<ref>James Davison Hunter, ''Culture wars:  The struggle to control the family, art, education, law, and politics in America'' (1992).</ref> A mass movement of population from the cities to the suburbs led to the creation of a new group of voters less attached to [[New Deal]] economic policies and [[political machine|machine politics]].<ref>Wilentz, pp. 23\u201324</ref> Meanwhile, it became socially acceptable for conservative Southern whites, especially well educated suburbanites, to vote Republican. Though the civil rights legislation of the 1960s had been a triumphal issue for liberalism and had created a new, pro-Democratic black electorate, it had also destroyed the argument that whites had to vote Democratic in order to protect segregation in the South.<ref>Earl Black and Merle Black, ''Politics and Society in the South'' (1989) p 249.</ref> Responding to these various trends, Reagan and other conservatives successfully presented conservative ideas as an alternative to a public that had grown disillusioned with New Deal liberalism and the Democratic Party.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 4\u20137</ref> Reagan's charisma and speaking skills helped him frame conservatism as an optimistic, forward-looking vision for the country.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 137\u2013138</ref>\n\n==1980 presidential election==\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1980.svg|right|thumb|1980 electoral vote results]]\n{{Main|Ronald Reagan 1980 presidential campaign|1980 United States presidential election}}\n\nReagan, who had served as [[Governor of California]] from 1967 to 1975, narrowly lost the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1976|1976 Republican presidential primaries]] to incumbent President [[Gerald Ford]]. With the defeat of Ford by Democrat [[Jimmy Carter]] in the [[1976 United States presidential election|1976 election]], Reagan immediately became the front-runner for the 1980 Republican presidential nomination.<ref>Weisberg,\npp. 56-57</ref> A darling of the conservative movement, Reagan faced more moderate Republicans such as [[George H. W. Bush]], [[Howard Baker]], and [[Bob Dole]] in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1980|1980 Republican presidential primaries]]. After Bush won the Iowa caucuses, he became Reagan's primary challenger, but Reagan won the New Hampshire primary and most of the following primaries, gaining an insurmountable delegate lead by the end of March 1980. Ford was Reagan's first choice for his running mate, but Reagan backed away from the idea out of the fear of a \"copresidency\" in which Ford would exercise an unusual degree of power. Reagan instead chose Bush, and the Reagan-Bush ticket was nominated at the [[1980 Republican National Convention]]. Meanwhile, Carter won the Democratic nomination, defeating a primary challenge by Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]. Polls taken after the party conventions showed a tied race between Reagan and Carter, while independent candidate [[John B. Anderson]] had the support of many moderates.<ref>Weisberg, pp. 61-63</ref>\n\nThe 1980 general campaign between Reagan and Carter was conducted amid a multitude of domestic concerns and the ongoing [[Iran hostage crisis]]. After winning the Republican nomination, Reagan pivoted to the center. Though he continued to champion a major tax cut, Reagan backed off of his support for free trade and the privatization of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], and promised to consider [[arms control]] treaties with the [[Soviet Union]]. He instead sought to focus the race on Carter's handling of the economy. Mired with an approval rating in the low 30s, Carter also waged a negative campaign, focusing on the supposed risk of war if Reagan took office.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 23\u201327</ref>\n\nReagan and Carter met in one presidential debate, held just one week before election day. Reagan delivered an effective performance, asking voters, \"Are you better off than you were four years ago?...Is America as respected throughout the world as it was?\" Though the race had been widely regarded as a close contest, Reagan won over the large majority of undecided voters.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 27\u201328</ref> Reagan took 50.7% of the popular vote and 489 of the 538 electoral votes. Carter won 41% of the popular vote and 49 electoral votes, while Anderson won 6.6% of the popular vote. In the concurrent [[United States elections, 1980|congressional elections]], Republicans took control of the Senate for the first time since the 1950s, while Democrats retained control of the House of Representatives.<ref>Patterson, pp. 149\u2013151</ref>\n\n==Administration==\n\n{{Infobox U.S. Cabinet\n|align=right\n|Name=Reagan\n|President=Ronald Reagan\n|President start=1981\n|President end=1989\n|Vice President=[[George H. W. Bush]]\n|Vice President start=1981\n|Vice President end=1989\n|State=[[Alexander Haig]]\n|State start=1981\n|State end=1982\n|State 2=[[George Shultz]]\n|State start 2=1982\n|State end 2=1989\n|Treasury=[[Donald Regan]]\n|Treasury start=1981\n|Treasury end=1985\n|Treasury 2=[[James Baker]]\n|Treasury start 2=1985\n|Treasury end 2=1988\n|Treasury 3=[[Nicholas F. Brady]]\n|Treasury start 3=1988\n|Treasury end 3=1989\n|Defense=[[Caspar Weinberger]]\n|Defense start=1981\n|Defense end=1987\n|Defense 2=[[Frank Carlucci]]\n|Defense start 2=1987\n|Defense end 2=1989\n|Justice=[[William French Smith]]\n|Justice start=1981\n|Justice end=1985\n|Justice 2=[[Edwin Meese]]\n|Justice start 2=1985\n|Justice end 2=1988\n|Justice 3=[[Dick Thornburgh]]\n|Justice start 3= 1988\n|Justice end 3=1989\n|Interior=[[James G. Watt]]\n|Interior start=1981\n|Interior end=1983\n|Interior 2=[[William P. Clark Jr.]]\n|Interior start 2=1983\n|Interior end 2=1985\n|Interior 3=[[Donald P. Hodel]]\n|Interior start 3=1985\n|Interior end 3=1989\n|Agriculture=[[John Rusling Block]]\n|Agriculture start=1981\n|Agriculture end=1986\n|Agriculture 2=[[Richard Edmund Lyng]]\n|Agriculture start 2=1986\n|Agriculture end 2=1989\n|Commerce=[[Malcolm Baldrige Jr.]]\n|Commerce start=1981\n|Commerce end=1987\n|Commerce 2=[[William Verity Jr.]]\n|Commerce start 2=1987\n|Commerce end 2=1989\n|Labor=[[Raymond J. Donovan]]\n|Labor start=1981\n|Labor end=1985\n|Labor 2=[[Bill Brock]]\n|Labor start 2=1985\n|Labor end 2=1987\n|Labor 3=[[Ann McLaughlin Korologos|Ann Dore McLaughlin]]\n|Labor start 3=1987\n|Labor end 3=1989\n|Health and Human Services=[[Richard Schweiker]]\n|Health and Human Services start=1981\n|Health and Human Services end=1983\n|Health and Human Services 2=[[Margaret Heckler]]\n|Health and Human Services start 2=1983\n|Health and Human Services end 2=1985\n|Health and Human Services 3=[[Otis Bowen]]\n|Health and Human Services start 3=1985\n|Health and Human Services end 3=1989\n|Education=[[Terrel Bell]]\n|Education start=1981\n|Education end=1984\n|Education 2=[[William Bennett]]\n|Education start 2=1985\n|Education end 2=1988\n|Education 3=[[Lauro Cavazos]]\n|Education start 3=1988\n|Education end 3=1989\n|Housing and Urban Development=[[Samuel Pierce]]\n|Housing and Urban Development start=1981\n|Housing and Urban Development end=1989\n|Transportation=[[Andrew L. Lewis Jr.]]\n|Transportation start=1981\n|Transportation end=1983\n|Transportation 2=[[Elizabeth Dole]]\n|Transportation start 2=1983\n|Transportation end 2=1987\n|Transportation 3=[[James H. Burnley IV]]\n|Transportation start 3=1987\n|Transportation end 3=1989\n|Energy=[[James B. Edwards]]\n|Energy start=1981\n|Energy end=1982\n|Energy 2=[[Donald P. Hodel]]\n|Energy start 2=1982\n|Energy end 2=1985\n|Energy 3=[[John S. Herrington]]\n|Energy start 3=1985\n|Energy end 3=1989\n|Counselor to the President=[[Edwin Meese]]\n|Counselor to the President start=1981\n|Counselor to the President end=1985\n|Counselor to the President 2=none\n|Counselor to the President start 2=1985\n|Counselor to the President end 2=1989\n|Management and Budget=[[David Stockman]]\n|Management and Budget start=1981\n|Management and Budget end=1985\n|Management and Budget 2=[[James C. Miller III]]\n|Management and Budget start 2=1985\n|Management and Budget end 2=1988\n|Management and Budget 3=[[Joseph Robert Wright Jr.]]\n|Management and Budget start 3=1988\n|Management and Budget end 3=1989\n|Ambassador to the United Nations=[[Jeane Kirkpatrick]]\n|Ambassador to the United Nations start=1981\n|Ambassador to the United Nations end=1985\n|Ambassador to the United Nations 2=[[Vernon A. Walters]]\n|Ambassador to the United Nations start 2=1985\n|Ambassador to the United Nations end 2=1989\n|Trade=[[Bill Brock]]\n|Trade start=1981\n|Trade end=1985\n|Trade 2=[[Clayton Yeutter]]\n|Trade start 2=1985\n|Trade end 2=1989\n|CIA=[[William J. Casey]]\n|CIA start=1981\n|CIA end=1987\n|CIA 2=[[William H. Webster]]\n|CIA start 2=1987\n|CIA end 2=1989\n}}\n\nReagan tapped [[James Baker]], who had run Bush's 1980 campaign, as his first [[White House Chief of Staff|chief of staff]]. Baker, [[White House Deputy Chief of Staff|Deputy Chief of Staff]] [[Michael Deaver]], and [[Counselor to the President|Counselor]] [[Edwin Meese]] formed the \"troika,\" the key White House staffers early in Reagan's presidency.<ref>Brands, pp. 241-246</ref> Baker quickly established himself as the most powerful member of the troika and the overseer of day-to-day operations, while Meese had nominal leadership of policy development and Deaver orchestrated Reagan's public appearances.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 51\u201352</ref> Aside from the troika, other important White House staffers included [[Richard Darman]] and [[David Gergen]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 52,</ref>\n\nReagan chose [[Alexander Haig]], a former general who had served as chief of staff to [[Richard Nixon]], as his first secretary of state. Other major Cabinet appointees included Secretary of Defense [[Caspar Weinberger]], a former Nixon cabinet official who would preside over an increase in defense spending, and Secretary of the Treasury [[Donald Regan]], a bank executive. Reagan selected [[David Stockman]], a young congressman from [[Michigan]], as the Director of the [[Office of Management and Budget]].<ref>Brands, pp. 246-248</ref> [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|CIA director]] [[William J. Casey]] emerged as an important figure in the administration, as the CIA would figure prominently into Reagan's Cold War initiatives. Reagan downgraded the importance of the [[National Security Advisor (United States)|national security advisor]], and six different individuals held that position during Reagan's presidency.<ref>Herring, pp. 864\u2013866</ref>\n\nHaig left the cabinet in 1982 after clashing with other members of the Reagan administration, and was replaced by another former Nixon administration official, [[George P. Shultz]].<ref>Brands, pp. 376-381</ref> By 1982, National Security Advisor [[William P. Clark Jr.]], [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Jeane Kirkpatrick]], and CIA Director Casey had established themselves as the major figures in the formulation of the administration's foreign policy.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 81\u201382</ref> Shultz eventually emerged as the administration's most influential foreign policy figure, moving the administration towards a less confrontational policy with the Soviet Union.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nBaker and Treasury Secretary Regan switched positions at the beginning of Reagan's second term.<ref>Brands, pp. 472-474</ref> Regan centralized power within his office, and he took on the responsibilities that had been held by Baker, Deaver, and Meese, the latter of whom succeeded [[William French Smith]] as attorney general in 1985.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 178\u2013180</ref> Regan frequently clashed with First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]], and he left the administration in the wake of the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair]] and Republican losses in the [[United States elections, 1986|1986 mid-term elections]]. Regan was replaced by former Senate Majority Leader [[Howard Baker]].<ref>Brands, pp. 645-649</ref>\n\n[[File:1981 US Cabinet.jpg|thumb|300px|left|The Cabinet of President Reagan in 1981]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Judicial appointments==\n{{Further|Ronald Reagan Supreme Court candidates|List of federal judges appointed by Ronald Reagan|Ronald Reagan judicial appointment controversies}}\n[[File:William Rehnquist.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Reagan appointed [[William Rehnquist]] to the office of [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] in 1986; he served until his death in 2005]]\n\nReagan made four successful appointments to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] during his eight years in office. In 1981, he successfully nominated [[Sandra Day O'Connor]] to succeed [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Associate Justice]] [[Potter Stewart]], fulfilling a campaign promise to name the first woman to the Supreme Court. Democrats, who had planned to vigorously oppose Reagan's nominations to the Supreme Court, approved of the nomination of O'Connor. However, the [[Christian right]] was astonished and dismayed with O\u2019Connor, whom they feared would not overturn the Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'', which had established the constitutional right to have an [[abortion in the United States|abortion]] without undue government interference.<ref>Prudence Flowers, \"\u2018A Prolife Disaster\u2019: The Reagan Administration and the Nomination of Sandra Day O\u2019Connor.\" ''Journal of Contemporary History''  53.2 (2018): 391-414</ref><ref>Wilentz, pp. 189\u2013190</ref> O'Connor served on the Supreme Court until 2006, and was generally considered to be a centrist conservative.<ref name=\"bisk\">{{cite news| last1=Biskupic| first1=Joan| title=Rehnquist left Supreme Court with conservative legacy| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/judicial/supremecourtjustices/2005-09-04-rehnquist-legacy_x.htm| accessdate=February 27, 2016| work=USA Today| date=September 4, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Reagan elevated Associate Justice [[William Rehnquist]] to the position of [[Chief Justice of the United States]] after [[Warren Burger]] chose to retire.<ref name=SCOTUS>{{cite web| title=U.S. Senate: Supreme Court Nominations: 1789-Present| url=https://www.senate.gov/pagelayout/reference/nominations/Nominations.htm| website = www.senate.gov| accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Rehnquist, a member of the conservative wing of the Court,<ref name=\"bisk\"/> was the third sitting associate justice to be elevated to chief justice, after [[Edward Douglass White]] and [[Harlan F. Stone]]. Reagan successfully nominated [[Antonin Scalia]] to fill Rehnquist's position as an associate justice of the Supreme Court.<ref name=SCOTUS/> Scalia became a member of the Court's conservative wing.<ref name=\"bisk\"/>\n\nReagan faced greater difficulties in filling the final Supreme Court vacancy, which arose due to the retirement of [[Lewis F. Powell Jr.]] Reagan nominated [[Robert Bork]] in July 1987, but the nomination was [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination|rejected by the Senate]] in October 1987.<ref name=SCOTUS/> Later that month, Reagan announced the nomination of [[Douglas H. Ginsburg]], but Ginsburg withdrew from consideration in November 1987. Finally, Reagan nominated [[Anthony Kennedy]], who won Senate confirmation in February 1988.<ref name=SCOTUS/> Along with O'Connor, Kennedy served as the key swing vote on the Supreme Court in the decades after Reagan left office.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parlapiano |first1=Alicia |last2=Patel |first2=Jugal K. |title=With Kennedy's Retirement, the Supreme Court Loses Its Center |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/27/us/politics/kennedy-retirement-supreme-court-median.html |accessdate=20 July 2018 |work=New York Times |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nReagan appointed a combined total of 368 judges to the [[United States courts of appeals]] and the [[United States district court]]s, [[List of Presidents of the United States by judicial appointments|more than any other president]]. The vast majority of his judicial appointees were conservative white men,<ref>Patterson, p. 174</ref> and many of the appointees were affiliated with the conservative [[Federalist Society]].<ref>Weisberg, pp. 116-117</ref> Partly because Congress passed a law creating new federal judicial positions in 1984, Reagan had appointed nearly half of the federal judiciary by the time he left office in 1989.<ref name=\"auto2\">Rossinow, p. 178</ref>\n\n==Assassination attempt==\n{{Main|Attempted assassination of Ronald Reagan}}\nOn March 30, 1981, only 69 days into the new administration, Reagan, his press secretary [[James Brady]], Washington police officer [[Thomas Delahanty]], and Secret Service agent [[Tim McCarthy]] were struck by gunfire from would-be assassin [[John Hinckley Jr.]] outside the [[Hilton Washington|Washington Hilton Hotel]]. Although Reagan was initially reported to be \"close to death\",<ref name=\"cnn transcript\">{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0103/30/lkl.00.html|title=Remembering the Assassination Attempt on Ronald Reagan|date=2001-03-30|accessdate=2007-12-19|publisher=CNN}}</ref> he recovered and was released from the hospital on April 11, becoming the first serving president to survive being wounded in an assassination attempt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/comment/dsouza200406080824.asp|work=National Review|accessdate=February 16, 2009|date=June 8, 2004|title=Purpose|author=D'Souza, Dinesh}}</ref> The failed assassination attempt had great influence on Reagan's popularity; polls indicated his approval rating to be around 73%.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Reagan's Ratings: 'Great Communicator's' Appeal Is Greater in Retrospect|accessdate=May 30, 2008|date=June 7, 2004|publisher=ABC|author=Langer, Gary|url=http://abcnews.go.com/sections/us/Polls/reagan_ratings_poll_040607.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Leuchtenberg, pp. 597-598\">Leuchtenberg, pp. 597-598</ref> Many pundits and journalists later described the failed assassination as a critical moment in Reagan's presidency, as his newfound popularity provided critical momentum in passing his domestic agenda.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 598-599</ref>\n\n==Domestic affairs==\n{{Main|Domestic policy of the Ronald Reagan administration}}\n\n===\"Reaganomics\" and taxation===\n{{Main|Reaganomics}}\n[[File:Ronald Reagan televised address from the Oval Office, outlining plan for Tax Reduction Legislation July 1981.jpg|thumb|Outlining his plan for ''Tax Reduction Legislation'' from the [[Oval Office]] in a televised address, July 1981]]\n\n====Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981====\n\nReagan implemented economic policies based on [[supply-side economics]], advocating a ''[[laissez-faire]]'' philosophy and [[free market economy|free-market]] fiscal policy.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Karaagac, John|title=Ronald Reagan and Conservative Reformism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZFhGnjKqjgAC&pg=PA113 |isbn=0-7391-0296-6|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2000|page=113}}</ref> Reagan's taxation policies resembled those instituted by President [[Calvin Coolidge]] and Treasury Secretary [[Andrew Mellon]] in the 1920s, but Reagan was also strongly influenced by contemporary economists such as [[Arthur Laffer]], who rejected the then-dominant views of [[Keynesian economics|Keynesian economists]].<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 595-596</ref> Reagan relied on Laffer and other economists to argue that tax cuts would reduce [[inflation]], which went against the prevailing Keynesian view.<ref>Brands, pp. 271-272</ref> Supply-side advocates also asserted that cutting taxes would ultimately lead to higher government revenue due to economic growth, a proposition that was challenged by many economists.<ref>Patterson, pp. 154-155</ref>\n\nRepublican Congressman [[Jack Kemp]] and Republican Senator [[William Roth]] had nearly won passage of a major tax cut during Carter's presidency, but Carter had prevented passage of the bill due to concerns about the deficit.<ref>Rossinow, p. 20</ref> Reagan made the passage of Kemp-Roth bill his top domestic priority upon taking office. As Democrats controlled the House of Representatives, passage of any bill would require the support of some House Democrats in addition to the support of congressional Republicans.<ref name=\"leuch599601\"/> Reagan's victory in the 1980 presidential campaign had united Republicans around his leadership, while conservative Democrats like [[Phil Gramm]] of Texas (who would later [[Party switching in the United States|switch parties]]) were eager to back some of Reagan's conservative policies.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 48\u201349</ref> Throughout 1981, Reagan frequently met with members of Congress, focusing especially on winning support from conservative Southern Democrats.<ref name=\"leuch599601\"/>\n\nIn July 1981, the Senate voted 89-11 in favor of the tax cut bill favored by Reagan, and the House subsequently approved the bill in a 238-195 vote.<ref name=\"auto3\">Rossinow, pp. 61\u201362</ref> The [[Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981]] cut the top marginal tax rate from 70% to 50%, lowered the [[Capital gains tax in the United States|capital gains tax]] from 28% to 20%, more than tripled the amount of inherited money exempt from the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]], and cut the [[Corporate tax in the United States|corporate tax]].<ref name=\"leuch599601\">Leuchtenberg, pp. 599-601</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/> Reagan's success in passing a major tax bill and cutting the federal budget was hailed as the \"Reagan Revolution\" by some reporters; one columnist wrote that the Reagan's legislative success represented the \"most formidable domestic initiative any president has driven through since the [[First 100 days of Franklin D. Roosevelt's presidency|Hundred Days]] of [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Roosevelt]].\"<ref name=\"Patterson, p. 157\">Patterson, p. 157</ref>\n\n====Later tax acts====\n\nFaced with concerns about the mounting federal debt, Reagan agreed to raise taxes, signing the [[Tax Equity and Fiscal Responsibility Act of 1982]] (TEFRA).<ref>Brands, pp. 346-349</ref> Many of Reagan's conservative supporters condemned TEFRA, but Reagan argued that his administration would be unable to win further budget cuts without the tax hike.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 148\u2013149</ref> Among other provisions, TEFRA doubled the federal cigarette tax and rescinded a portion of the corporate tax cuts from the 1981 tax bill.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 62\u201363</ref> By 1983, the amount of federal tax had fallen for all or almost all American taxpayers, but most strongly affected the wealthy; the proportion of income paid in taxes by the richest one percent fell from 29.8 percent to 24.8 percent.<ref>Rossinow, p. 63</ref>  Partly due to the poor economy, Reagan's legislative momentum dissipated after his first year in office, and his party lost several seats in the House in the [[United States elections, 1982|1982 congressional elections]].<ref name=\"Patterson, pp. 162-163\">Patterson, pp. 162-163</ref> Compared to other [[United States midterm election|midterm election]]s, the losses were relatively small for the party holding the presidency, but conservative Democrats were less open to Reagan's initiatives after 1982.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 97\u201398, 164</ref> As deficits continued to be an issue, Reagan signed another bill that raised taxes, the [[Deficit Reduction Act of 1984]].<ref name=\"shapiro1\">{{cite journal|last1=Shapiro|first1=Bernard M.|title=Presidential Politics And Deficit Reduction: The Landscape Of Tax Policy In The 1980S And 1990S|journal=Washington and Lee Law Revie|date=1 March 1993|volume=50|issue=2|url=http://scholarlycommons.law.wlu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1749&context=wlulr}}</ref>\n\nWith Donald Regan taking over as Chief of Staff in 1985, the Reagan administration made simplification of the tax code the central focus of its second term domestic agenda.<ref>Brands, pp. 540-541</ref> Working with [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[Tip O'Neill]], a Democrat who also favored tax reform, Reagan overcame significant opposition from members of Congress in both parties to pass the [[Tax Reform Act of 1986]].<ref>Brands, pp. 542-544</ref> The act simplified the tax code by reducing the number of tax brackets to four and slashing a number of tax breaks. The top rate was dropped to 28%, but capital gains taxes were increased on those with the highest incomes from 20% to 28%. The increase of the lowest tax bracket from 11% to 15% was more than offset by expansion of the personal exemption, [[standard deduction]], and [[earned income tax credit]]. The net result was the removal of six million poor Americans from the income tax roll and a reduction of income tax liability at all income levels.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brownlee|first1=Elliot|last2=Graham|first2=Hugh Davis|title=The Reagan Presidency: Pragmatic Conservatism & Its Legacies|date=2003|publisher=University of Kansas Press|location=Lawrence, Kansas|pages=172\u2013173}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Steuerle|first1=C. Eugene|title=The Tax Decade: How Taxes Came to Dominate the Public Agenda|date=1992|publisher=The Urban Institute Press|location=Washington D.C.|isbn=0-87766-523-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/taxdecadehowtaxe0000steu/page/122 122]|url=https://archive.org/details/taxdecadehowtaxe0000steu/page/122}}</ref> The net effect of Reagan's tax bills was that overall tax burden held steady at roughly 19 percent of [[gross national product]].<ref>Patterson, p. 166</ref>\n\n===Government spending===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; text-align:center;\"\n|+ Federal finances and GDP during Reagan's presidency<ref>All figures, except for debt percentage, are presented in billions of dollars. GDP is calculated for the calendar year. The income, outlay, deficit, and debt figures are calculated for the [[US fiscal year|fiscal year]], which ends on September 30. For example, fiscal year 2017 ended on September 30, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Income\n! Outlays\n! Surplus/<br/>Deficit\n! [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]]\n! Debt as a %<br/>of GDP<ref>Represents the national debt held by the public as a percentage of GDP</ref>\n\n|-\n! 1981\n| 599.3\n| 678.2\n| -79.0\n| 3138.4\n| 25.2\n\n|-\n! 1982\n| 617.8\n| 745.7\n| -128.0\n| 3313.9\n| 27.9\n\n|-\n! 1983\n| 600.6\n| 808.4\n| -207.8\n| 3541.1\n| 32.1\n\n|-\n! 1984\n| 666.4\n| 851.8\n| -185.4\n| 3952.8\n| 33.1\n\n|-\n! 1985\n| 734.0\n| 946.3\n| -212.3\n| 4270.4\n| 35.3\n\n|-\n! 1986\n| 769.2\n| 990.4\n| -221.2\n| 4536.1\n| 38.4\n\n|-\n! 1987\n| 854.3\n| 1004.0\n| -149.7\n| 4781.9\n| 39.5\n\n|-\n! 1988\n| 909.2\n| 1064.4\n| -155.2\n| 5155.1\n| 39.8\n\n|-\n! 1989\n| 991.1\n| 1143.7\n| -152.6\n| 5570.0\n| 39.3\n\n|-\n! Ref.\n| colspan=3 | <ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Tables|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/omb/budget/Historicals|website=Obama White House|publisher=Office of Management and Budget|accessdate=23 May 2018|location=Table 1.1}}</ref>\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Tables|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/omb/budget/Historicals|website=Obama White House|publisher=Office of Management and Budget|accessdate=23 May 2018|location=Table 1.2}}</ref>\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Tables|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/omb/budget/Historicals|website=Obama White House|publisher=Office of Management and Budget|accessdate=23 May 2018|location=Table 7.1}}</ref>\n|}\n\nReagan prioritized tax cuts over spending cuts, arguing that lower revenue would eventually require lower spending.<ref>Brands, pp. 263-264</ref> Nonetheless, Reagan was determined to decrease government spending and roll back or dismantle [[Great Society]] programs such as [[Medicaid]] and the [[Office of Economic Opportunity]].<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 594-595</ref> In August 1981, Reagan signed the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1981, which cut federal funding for social programs like [[Food Stamp Program|food stamps]], [[School meal programs in the United States|school lunch programs]], and Medicaid.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 58\u201360</ref> The [[Comprehensive Employment and Training Act]], which had provided for the employment of 300,000 workers in 1980, was also repealed,<ref name=\"Patterson, p. 157\"/> and the administration tightened eligibility for [[unemployment benefits]].<ref name=\"auto4\">Rossinow, p. 85</ref> Notably absent from the budget cuts was the Department of Defense, which saw its budget bolstered.<ref>Brands, pp. 266-267</ref>\n\nReagan experienced several legislative successes in his first year in office, but his attempts to cut federal domestic spending after 1981 met increasing congressional resistance.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 615-616</ref> Spending on programs like [[Supplemental Security Income]], Medicaid, the [[earned income tax credit]], and [[Aid to Families with Dependent Children]] all increased after 1982. The number of federal civilian employees rose during Reagan's tenure, from 2.9 million to 3.1 million.<ref>Patterson, p. 165</ref> Reagan's policy of [[New Federalism]], which sought to shift the responsibility for most social programs to state governments, found little support in Congress.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 618-619</ref>\n\nIn 1981, OMB Director David Stockman won Reagan's approval to seek cuts to [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] in 1981, but this plan was poorly-received in Congress.<ref>Brands, pp. 300-303</ref> In 1982, Reagan established the bipartisan [[Greenspan Commission|National Commission on Social Security Reform]] to make recommendations to secure the long-term integrity of Social Security. The commission rejected Social Security privatization and other major changes to the program, but recommended expanding the Social Security base (by including exempt federal and nonprofit employees), raising Social Security taxes, and reducing some payments. These recommendations were enacted in the [[History of Social Security in the United States#1983 Amendments|Social Security Amendments of 1983]], which received bipartisan support.<ref>Brands, pp. 425-427</ref> While Reagan avoided cuts to Social Security and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] for most individuals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/pressketch.html|title=The Reagan Presidency|publisher=Reagan Presidential Foundation|accessdate=August 4, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517013218/http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/pressketch.html|archivedate=May 17, 2008}}</ref> his administration attempted to purge many people from the Social Security disability rolls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/19/us/us-to-reconsider-denial-of-benefits-to-many-disabled.html?pagewanted=all|title=U.S. to Reconsider Denial of Benefits to Many Disabled|date=April 19, 1992|author=Pear, Robert|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 23, 2008}}</ref> Reagan's inability to implement major cuts to Social Security solidified its status as the \"[[third rail of politics|third rail]]\" of U.S. politics, and future administrations would be reluctant to propose cuts to the popular program.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 149\u2013150</ref>\n\n===Deficits===\n\nAs Reagan was unwilling to match his tax cuts with cuts to defense spending or Social Security, rising deficits became an issue.<ref>Weisberg, pp. 75-76</ref> These deficits were exacerbated by the [[early 1980s recession]], which cut into federal revenue.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 605-606</ref> Unable to win further domestic spending cuts, and pressured to address the deficit, Reagan was forced to raise taxes after 1981.<ref>Brands, pp. 346-347</ref> Nonetheless, the national debt more than tripled between fiscal year 1980 and fiscal year 1989, going from $914 billion to $2.7 trillion, while national debt as a percentage of GDP rose from 33 percent in 1981 to 53 percent in 1989. Reagan never submitted a balanced budget during his time in office.<ref>Patterson, pp. 158-159</ref>\n\nIn an effort to lower the national debt, Congress passed the [[Gramm\u2013Rudman\u2013Hollings Balanced Budget Act]], which called for [[Budget sequestration|automatic spending cuts]] if Congress was unable to eliminate deficits through the regular budget-making process.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However, Congress found ways around the automatic cuts and deficits continued to rise, ultimately leading to the passage of the [[Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1990]].<ref name=\"scline1\">{{cite news|last1=Cline|first1=Seth|title=What Happened Last Time We Had a Budget Sequester?|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/blogs/press-past/2013/03/01/what-happened-last-time-we-had-a-budget-sequester|accessdate=18 May 2017|publisher=US News and World Report|date=1 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\n\nReagan took office in the midst of poor economic conditions, as the country experienced [[stagflation]], a phenomenon in which both inflation and unemployment were high.<ref>Brands, pp. 221-222</ref> The economy experienced a brief period of growth early in Reagan's first year in office, but plunged into a recession in July 1981.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 90\u201391</ref> As the recession continued in the first two years of Reagan's presidency, many within Reagan's administration blamed the policies of [[Paul Volcker]], the [[Chair]] of the [[Federal Reserve System|Federal Reserve]]. But Reagan himself never criticized Volcker.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/commandingheights/shared/minitext/int_paulvolcker.html#6 |title=Commanding Heights, Paul Volcker Interview |date=26 September 2000 |website=PBS |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Volcker sought to fight inflation by pursuing a policy of \"tight money\" in which interest rates were set a high level.<ref name=\"brands317319\"/> High interest rates would restrict lending and investment, which would in turn lower inflation, raise unemployment and, at least in the short term, reduce economic growth.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 88\u201390</ref> Unemployment reached a high of nearly 11% in 1982,<ref name=\"brands317319\">Brands, pp. 317-319</ref> [[Poverty in the United States|poverty]] rate rose from 11.7 percent to 15 percent.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The country emerged from recession in 1983,<ref name=\"Brands, pp. 452-453\">Brands, pp. 452-453</ref> but not all shared equally in the economic recovery, and [[economic inequality]] and the number of [[Homelessness in the United States|homeless]] individuals both increased during the 1980s.<ref>Patterson, pp. 166\u2013167</ref><ref>Rossinow, p. 145</ref> Fearful of damaging confidence in the economic recovery, Reagan nominated Volcker to a second term in 1983, and Volcker remained in office until 1987.<ref name=\"brands668671\"/> Inflation dropped to approximately 3.5% in 1985, while the unemployment rate fell to about 5% in 1988.<ref name=\"Patterson, pp. 162-163\"/> In 1987, Reagan appointed conservative economist [[Alan Greenspan]] to succeed Volcker, and Greenspan would lead the Federal Reserve until 2006. Greenspan raised interest rates in another attempt to curb inflation, setting off a [[stock market crash]] in October 1987 known as \"[[Black Monday (1987)|Black Monday]],\" but the markets stabilized and recovered in the following weeks.<ref name=\"brands668671\">Brands, pp. 668-671</ref>\n\n===Labor===\n\nIn August 1981, the [[Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization (1968)|Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization]] (PATCO), which consisted of federal employees, voted to go on a [[Strike action|labor strike]] in hopes of receiving better pay and benefits. After the vote, Reagan announced that the strikers would be fired if they did not return to work within forty-eight hours. After the deadline passed, Reagan fired over 10,000 air traffic controllers, while approximately 40 percent of the union members returned to work. Reagan's handling of the strike was strongly criticized by union leaders, but it won the approval of his conservative base of voters and others in the public.<ref name=\"patterson157158\"/><ref>Rossinow, pp. 86\u201387</ref> The breaking of the PATCO strike demoralized organized labor, and the number of strikes fell dramatically in the 1980s.<ref name=\"patterson157158\">Patterson, pp. 157-158</ref> Many of the strikes that did occur, including the [[Arizona copper mine strike of 1983]], the 1983 [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]] bus driver strike, and the 1985 [[Hormel]] meatpacking worker strike, ended with dismissal of the strikers. With the assent of Reagan's sympathetic [[National Labor Relations Board]] appointees, many companies also won wage and benefit cutbacks from unions, especially in the manufacturing sector.<ref name=\"rossinow8788\">Rossinow, p. 87\u201388</ref> During Reagan's time in office, the share of employees who were part of a labor union dropped from approximately one-fourth of the total workforce to approximately one-sixth of the total workforce.<ref>Patterson, p. 170</ref>\n\n===Deregulation===\n\nReagan sought to loosen federal regulation of economic activities, and he appointed key officials who shared this agenda. According to historian [[William Leuchtenburg]], by 1986, the Reagan administration eliminated almost half of the federal regulations that had existed in 1981.<ref name=\"leuch601\"/> The [[Federal Communications Commission]] aggressively deregulated the [[broadcasting]] industry, eliminating the [[Fairness Doctrine]] and other restrictions.<ref name=\"donnelly1\">{{cite news|last1=Donnelly|first1=H.|title=Broadcasting Deregulation|url=http://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre1987120400|accessdate=29 November 2017|publisher=CQ Press|date=1987}}</ref> The 1982 [[Garn\u2013St. Germain Depository Institutions Act]] deregulated [[savings and loan association]]s and allowed banks to provide [[adjustable-rate mortgage]]s. Reagan also eliminated numerous government positions and dismissed numerous federal employees, including the entire staff of the [[Employment and Training Administration]]. Secretary of the Interior [[James Watt]] implemented policies designed to open up federal territories to oil drilling and [[surface mining]]. Under [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] Director [[Anne Gorsuch]], the EPA's budget was dramatically reduced and the EPA loosely enforced environmental regulations.<ref name=\"leuch601\">Leuchtenberg, pp. 601-604</ref>\n\n====Savings and loan crisis====\n\nAfter the passage of the Garn\u2013St. Germain Depository Institutions Act, savings and loans associations engaged in riskier activities, and the leaders of some institutions embezzled funds.<ref>Patterson, p. 175</ref> In what became known as the [[Savings and loan crisis]], a total of 747 financial institutions failed and needed to be rescued with $160 billion in taxpayer dollars.<ref>Timothy Curry and Lynn Shibut, The Cost of the Savings and Loan Crisis: Truth and Consequences FDIC, December 2000.</ref> As an indication of this scandal's size, [[Martin Mayer]] wrote at the time, \"The theft from the taxpayer by the community that fattened on the growth of the savings and loan (S&L) industry in the 1980s is the worst public scandal in American history...Measuring by money, [or] by the misallocation of national resources...the S&L outrage makes [[Teapot Dome Scandal|Teapot Dome]] and [[Cr\u00e9dit Mobilier of America scandal|Credit Mobilier]] seem minor episodes.\"<ref>''The Greatest-Ever Bank Robbery: The Collapse of the Savings and Loan Industry'' by Martin Mayer (Scribner's)</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n{{see also|Immigration to the United States}}\n\nThe 1980s saw the highest rate of immigration to the United States since the 1910s, and the proportion of the foreign-born population reached its highest level since the 1940s.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 158\u2013159</ref> Reagan did not make immigration a focus of his administration, but he came to support a package of reforms sponsored by Republican Senator [[Alan Simpson (American politician)|Alan Simpson]] and Democratic Congressman [[Romano Mazzoli]], which he signed into law as the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986|Immigration Reform and Control Act]] in November 1986.<ref>Brands, pp. 544-545</ref> The act made it illegal to knowingly hire or recruit [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants]], required employers to attest to their employees' immigration status, and granted amnesty to approximately three million illegal immigrants who had entered the United States before January 1, 1982, and had lived in the country continuously. The bill was also contained provisions designed to enhance security measures at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]].<ref name=\"bplumer1\"/> Upon signing the act at a ceremony held beside the newly refurbished [[Statue of Liberty]], Reagan said, \"The legalization provisions in this act will go far to improve the lives of a class of individuals who now must hide in the shadows, without access to many of the benefits of a free and open society. Very soon many of these men and women will be able to step into the sunlight and, ultimately, if they choose, they may become Americans.\"<ref name=\"immigration\">Reagan, Ronald. (November 6, 1986) [http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/speeches/1986/110686b.htm Statement on Signing the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986.] Collected Speeches, Ronald Reagan Presidential Library. Retrieved August 15, 2007.</ref> The bill was largely unsuccessful at halting illegal immigration, and the population of illegal immigrants rose from 5 million in 1986 to 11.1 million in 2013.<ref name=\"bplumer1\">{{cite news|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|title=Congress tried to fix immigration back in 1986. Why did it fail?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/01/30/in-1986-congress-tried-to-solve-immigration-why-didnt-it-work/|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=Washington Post|date=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal and anti-drug policy===\n\n[[File:NRJUSTSAYNORALLY.jpg|thumb|right|First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]] at a [[Just Say No]] rally at the White House]]\n\nNot long after being sworn into office, Reagan declared more militant policies in the \"[[War on Drugs]]\".<ref name=\"War on Drugs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/extra/features/jan-june01/drug_war.html |title=The War on Drugs |publisher=pbs. org |date=May 10, 2001 |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Youth Trends\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nida.nih.gov/Infofacts/HSYouthtrends.html |title=NIDA InfoFacts: High School and Youth Trends |publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse, NIH |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref> He promised a \"planned, concerted campaign\" against all drugs,<ref name=\"The Drug War\">{{cite web |url=http://academic.udayton.edu/race/03justice/crime09.htm |title=The Drug War as Race War |accessdate=April 11, 2007 |author=Randall, Vernellia R |date=April 18, 2006 |publisher=The University of Dayton School of Law}}</ref> in hopes of decreasing drug use, particularly among adolescents.<ref name=\"Interview: Dr. Herbert Kleber\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/interviews/kleber.html |title=Interview: Dr. Herbert Kleber |accessdate=June 12, 2007 |publisher=PBS |quote=The politics of the Reagan years and the Bush years probably made it somewhat harder to get treatment expanded, but at the same time, it probably had a good effect in terms of decreasing initiation and use. For example, marijuana went from thirty-three percent of high-school seniors in 1980 to twelve percent in 1991.}}</ref><ref name=\"Decline of Substance Use\">{{cite web |author=Bachman, Gerald G. |url=http://www.monitoringthefuture.org/pubs/jbbook/jbbook02.html |title=The Decline of Substance Use in Young Adulthood |publisher=The Regents of the University of Michigan |accessdate=April 4, 2007|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The \"[[crack epidemic]],\" which saw a large number of individuals become addicted to [[crack cocaine]] and may have played a role in numerous murders, emerged as a major area of public concern.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 122\u2013124</ref> [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] Nancy Reagan made the War on Drugs her main cause as First Lady, founding the \"[[Just Say No]]\" drug awareness campaign.<ref name=\"PBS Frontline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/cron/ |title=Thirty Years of America's Drug War |publisher=PBS |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref>\n\nConcerns about drug use prompted Congress to pass legislation such as the [[Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984]]<ref>Rossinow, p. 124</ref> and the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986]], the latter of which granted $1.7 billion to fight drugs and established a mandatory minimum penalties for drug offenses.<ref name=\"PBS Frontline\"/> Reagan also signed the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988]], which further increased criminal penalties for drug use and established the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]].<ref name=\"jjohnson1\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Julie|title=REAGAN SIGNS BILL TO CURB DRUG USE|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/19/us/reagan-signs-bill-to-curb-drug-use.html|accessdate=7 December 2017|work=New York Times|date=19 November 1988}}</ref> Critics charged that Reagan's policies promoted significant racial disparities in the prison population,<ref name=\"PBS Frontline\"/> were ineffective in reducing the availability of drugs or crime on the street, and came at a great financial and human cost for American society.<ref name=\"Stop the Drug War\">{{cite web |url=http://stopthedrugwar.org/chronicle-old/341/reagan.shtml |publisher=stopthedrugwar.org |title=The Reagan-Era Drug War Legacy |date=June 11, 2004 |accessdate=April 4, 2007}}</ref> Supporters argued that the numbers for adolescent drug users declined during Reagan's years in office.<ref name=\"Decline of Substance Use\"/>\n\n===Social policies and civil rights===\n\nReagan was largely unable to enact his ambitious social policy agenda, which included a federal ban on [[abortions in the United States|abortions]] and an end to [[desegregation busing]].<ref name=\"svroberts1\"/> With Reagan's support, conservative Republican Senator [[Jesse Helms]] led an effort to prevent the Supreme Court from reviewing state and local laws mandating [[school prayer]], but Republican senators like [[Lowell Weicker]] and [[Barry Goldwater]] blocked passage of Helms' bill.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 95\u201396</ref> Despite the lack of major social policy legislation, Reagan was able to influence social policy through regulations and the appointment of conservative Supreme Court Justices.<ref name=\"svroberts1\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Steven V.|title=THE NATION; Reagan's Social Issues: Gone but Not Forgotten|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/09/11/weekinreview/the-nation-reagan-s-social-issues-gone-but-not-forgotten.html|accessdate=7 December 2017|work=New York Times|date=11 September 1988}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, Reagan signed a bill extending the [[Voting Rights Act]] for 25 years after a grass-roots lobbying and legislative campaign forced him to abandon his plan to ease that law's restrictions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Raines|first=Howell|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/30/us/voting-rights-act-signed-by-reagan.html|title=Voting Rights Act Signed by Reagan|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 30, 1982|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> He also reluctantly accepted the continuation of [[Affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]] programs<ref>Patterson, p. 171</ref> and the establishment of [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day]] as a [[Federal holidays in the United States|federal holiday]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 163\u2013164</ref> The [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]] and the Justice Department both prosecuted far fewer civil rights cases per year than they had under Carter.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 42\u201343</ref> In 1988, Reagan vetoed the [[Civil Rights Restoration Act]], but his veto was overridden by Congress. Reagan had argued that the legislation infringed on [[states' rights]] and the rights of churches and business owners.<ref>{{cite book|title=American Civil Rights Policy from Truman to Clinton: The Role of Presidential Leadership |first=Steven A. |last=Shull |year=1999 |publisher=M.E. Sharpe |page=94 |isbn=9780765603944 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CdFdPBCj8NMC&pg=PA95}}</ref>\n\nNo civil rights legislation for [[homosexuality|gay]] individuals passed during Reagan's tenure. Many in the Reagan administration, including [[White House Communications Director|Communications Director]] [[Pat Buchanan]], were hostile to the gay community, as were many religious leaders who were important allies to the administration.<ref>Wilentz, pp. 185\u2013186</ref> Gay rights and the growing [[HIV/AIDS]] emerged as an important matter of public concern in 1985 after it was disclosed that actor [[Rock Hudson]], a personal friend of President Reagan, was receiving treatment for AIDS. As public anxiety over AIDS rose, the Supreme Court upheld a state law that criminalized homosexuality in the case of ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]''.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 132\u2013134</ref> Though Surgeon General [[C. Everett Koop]] advocated for a public health campaign designed to reduce the spread of AIDS by raising awareness and promoting the use of condoms, Reagan favored rejected Koop's proposals in favor of [[abstinence-only sex education]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 212\u2013214</ref> By 1989, approximately 60,000 American had died of AIDS, and liberals strongly criticized Reagan's response to the HIV/AIDS crisis.<ref>Patterson, pp. 179\u2013182</ref> On the 1980 campaign trail, Reagan spoke of the gay rights movement:\n{{quote|My criticism is that [the gay movement] isn\u2019t just asking for civil rights; it\u2019s asking for recognition and acceptance of an alternative lifestyle which I do not believe society can condone, nor can I.<ref>{{cite book |last=Scheer |first=Robert |title=Playing President: My Close Ecounters with Nixon, Carter, Bush I, Reagan, and Clinton--and How They Did Not Prepare Me for George W. Bush |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xhTTyMDzP5EC&pg=PA154 |year=2006 |publisher=Akashic Books |isbn=978-1-933354-01-9 |page=154}}</ref>}}\n\n===Environmental Policy===\nReagan's strong preferences for limited federal involvement and deregulation extended to the environment. His main goal was to lessen the burden of regulation on businesses to promote more economic activity in the United States. Because of this policy, Reagan refused to renew the Clean Air Act during his administration.<ref>Daynes, B. W., & Sussman, G. (2010). ''White House Politics and the Environment: Franklin D. Roosevelt to George W. Bush''. College Station: Texas A & M Univ. Press.</ref> Reagan lessened existing regulations on pollution, cut funding to government environmental agencies, and appointed known anti-environmentalist individuals to key positions presiding over these organizations.<ref>Kline, Benjamin. (2011). ''First Along the River\u202f: a Brief History of the U.S. Environmental Movement''. 4th ed. Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers.</ref> \n\nWhen Reagan took office in 1981, he \"attempted to reduce\" money that was directed towards studying the burgeoning field of global warming and human-driven climate change.<ref>Daynes, B. W. ''White House Politics and the Environment'', p.176.</ref> In the early 1980's, the study of the intersection between human activity and climate change was still in its infancy and scientists were far from a consensus on the topic.<ref>Miller, Norman. (2009). ''Environmental Politics\u202f: Stakeholders, Interests, and Policymaking''. 2nd ed. New York: Routledge.</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the Reagan administration signed the [[Montreal Protocol]] in an effort to reduce emissions that damage the [[ozone layer]].<ref>Daynes, B. W. ''White House Politics and the Environment'', p.185.</ref>\n\n===Mass surveillance===\nCiting [[national security]] concerns, the president's national security team pressed for more [[surveillance]] power early during Reagan's first term. Their recommendations were based upon the [[premise]] that the federal government's [[Intelligence assessment|intelligence]] and [[counterintelligence]] capabilities had been weakened by presidents Carter and Ford.<ref>{{cite web| title=The executive order that led to mass spying, as told by NSA alumni: Feds call it \"twelve triple three\"; whistleblower says it's the heart of the problem| last=Farivar| first=Cyrus| date=August 27, 2014| url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2014/08/a-twisted-history-how-a-reagan-era-executive-order-led-to-mass-spying/2/| publisher=Ars Technica| accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> On December 4, 1981, Reagan signed [[Executive Order 12333]]. This [[presidential directive]] broadened the power of the [[United States Intelligence Community|government's intelligence community]]; mandated rules for spying on United States citizens, permanent residents, and on anyone within the United States; and also directed the Attorney General and others to create further policies and procedures for what information intelligence agencies can collect, retain, and share.<ref>{{cite web| title=A Primer on Executive Order 12333: The Mass Surveillance Starlet| last=Jaycox| first=Mark| date=June 2, 2014| url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/06/primer-executive-order-12333-mass-surveillance-starlet| publisher=Electronic Frontier Foundation| location=San Francisco, California| accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===1986 mid-term elections===\n\nIn the [[United States elections, 1986|1986 mid-term elections]], Democrats retained a majority of the House and won control of the Senate for the first time since the 1980 elections. Reagan campaigned hard for congressional Republicans, and an October 1986 New York Times/CBS News Poll had found that Reagan had a 67 percent approval rating. However, Senate Republicans faced a difficult map that year, as they had to defend 22 of the 34 seats up for election. Republican losses in the Senate were concentrated in the South and in the farm states.<ref name=\"1986midterms\">{{cite news|last1=Dionne, Jr.|first1=E.J.|title=ELECTIONS; DEMOCRATS GAIN CONTROL OF SENATE, DRAWING VOTES OF REAGAN'S BACKERS; CUOMO AND D'AMATO ARE EASY VICTORS; WHAT AWAITS CONGRESS; BROAD G.O.P. LOSSES|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/05/us/elections-democrats-gain-control-senate-drawing-votes-reagan-s-backers-cuomo-d.html|accessdate=13 May 2018|work=New York Times|date=1986}}</ref> The Republican loss of the Senate precluded the possibility of further major conservative legislation during the Reagan administration.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Busch|first1=Andrew|title=Horses in Midstream|date=1999|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|pages=126\u2013135}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign affairs==\n{{Main|Foreign policy of the Ronald Reagan administration}}\n\n===Escalation of the Cold War===\n\n{{See also|Cold War (1979\u201385)}}\n[[File:President Reagan addressing British Parliament, London, June 8, 1982.jpg|thumb|As the first U.S. president invited to speak before the [[British Parliament]] (June 8, 1982), Reagan predicted Marxism would end up on the \"[[ash heap of history]]\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Reagan, Ronald.|date=June 8, 1982|url=http://www.historyplace.com/speeches/reagan-parliament.htm|title=Ronald Reagan Address to British Parliament|publisher=The History Place|accessdate=April 19, 2006}}</ref>]]\n\nReagan escalated the Cold War, accelerating a reversal from the policy of d\u00e9tente which had begun in 1979 after the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|Soviet invasion]] of [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/index.cfm?topic_id=1409&fuseaction=topics.event_summary&event_id=12594|title=Towards an International History of the War in Afghanistan, 1979\u201389|accessdate=May 16, 2007|year=2002|publisher=The Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011144144/http://wilsoncenter.org/index.cfm?topic_id=1409&fuseaction=topics.event_summary&event_id=12594|archivedate=October 11, 2007 }}</ref> Reagan feared that the Soviet Union had gained a military advantage over the United States, and the Reagan administration hoped to that heightened military spending would grant the U.S. military superiority and weaken the Soviet economy.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 66\u201367</ref> Reagan ordered a massive buildup of the [[United States Armed Forces]], directing funding to the [[B-1 Lancer]] bomber, the [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 Spirit bomber]], [[cruise missile]]s, the [[LGM-118 Peacekeeper|MX missile]], and the [[600-ship Navy]].<ref>Patterson, p. 200</ref> In response to Soviet deployment of the [[SS-20]], Reagan oversaw [[NATO]]'s deployment of the [[Pershing missile]] in West Germany.<ref>Patterson, pp. 205</ref> The president also strongly denounced the Soviet Union and Communism in moral terms,<ref>Rossinow, p. 67</ref> describing the Soviet Union an \"[[Evil Empire speech|evil empire]].\"<ref name=\"Cannon-315\">Cannon (1991), pp.&nbsp;314\u2013317.</ref> Despite this heavy rhetoric,<ref>G. Thomas Goodnight,  \"Ronald Reagan's re\u2010formulation of the rhetoric of war: Analysis of the 'zero option,' 'evil empire,' and 'star wars' addresses.\" ''Quarterly Journal of Speech'' 72.4 (1986): 390-414.</ref> the Reagan administration continued arms control talks with the Soviet Union in the form of \"[[START I|START]].\" Unlike the \"[[Strategic Arms Limitation Talks|SALT]]\" treaties of the 1970s, which set upper limits on the size of nuclear arsenals, the proposed START treaty would require both sides to reduce their existing nuclear arsenals.<ref>Herring, pp. 868\u2013869</ref>\n\n[[File:Reagan sitting with people from the Afghanistan-Pakistan region in February 1983.jpg|thumb|right|Meeting with leaders of the Afghan [[Mujahideen]] in the Oval Office, 1983]]\n\nIn March 1983, Reagan introduced the [[Strategic Defense Initiative]] (SDI), a defense project that would have used ground- and space-based systems to protect the United States from attack by strategic nuclear ballistic missiles. Reagan believed that this defense shield could make nuclear war impossible.<ref>Beschloss, p. 293</ref> Many scientists and national security experts criticized the project as costly and technologically infeasible, and critics dubbed SDI as \"Star Wars\" in reference to a [[Star Wars|popular film series of the same name]].<ref>Herring, pp. 870\u2013871</ref> Ultimately, the SDI would be canceled in 1993 due to concerns about its cost and effectiveness as well as a changing international situation.<ref>Brands, pp. 725-726</ref> However, the Soviets became concerned about the possible effects SDI would have and viewed its development as a violation of the [[Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty]].<ref>Brands, pp. 581-585</ref> In protest of SDI, the Soviet Union broke off arms control talks, and U.S.-Soviet relations descended to their lowest point since the early 1960s.<ref>Herring, pp. 869\u2013870</ref> The Cold War tensions influenced works of popular culture such as ''[[The Day After]]'', ''[[WarGames]]'', and ''[[99 Luftballons]]'', each of which exhibited the rising public anxiety for the possibility of a nuclear war.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 116\u2013117</ref>\n\n===Reagan Doctrine===\nUnder a policy that came to be known as the [[Reagan Doctrine]], the Reagan administration provided overt and covert aid to anti-communist [[Guerrilla warfare|resistance movements]] in an effort to \"[[rollback]]\" Soviet-backed communist governments in Africa, Asia, and Latin America.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.org/19860301faessay7785/stephen-s-rosenfeld/the-reagan-doctrine-the-guns-of-july.html|title=The Reagan Doctrine: The Guns of July|author =Stephen S. Rosenfeld|journal =[[Foreign Affairs]]|date =Spring 1986|volume=64|issue=4 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165407/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/19860301faessay7785/stephen-s-rosenfeld/the-reagan-doctrine-the-guns-of-july.html|archivedate=September 30, 2007}}</ref> In Eastern Europe, the CIA provided support to the [[Poland|Polish]] opposition group, [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]], ensuring that it stayed afloat during a [[Martial law in Poland|period of martial law]].<ref name=\"auto\">Herring, pp. 883\u2013884</ref> Reagan deployed the CIA's [[Special Activities Division]] to Afghanistan and Pakistan, and the CIA was instrumental in training, equipping, and leading [[Islamic Unity of Afghanistan Mujahideen|Mujahideen]] forces against the Soviet Army in the Soviet\u2013Afghan War.<ref name=\"Crile 2003\">{{Cite book|first=George|last=Crile|title=Charlie Wilson's War: The Extraordinary Story of the Largest Covert Operation in History|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|year=2003|isbn=0-87113-854-9|url=https://archive.org/details/charliewilsonswa00cril}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Pach, Chester|title=The Reagan Doctrine: Principle, Pragmatism, and Policy|journal=Presidential Studies Quarterly|year=2006|volume=36 |issue=1|pages=75\u201388|doi=10.1111/j.1741-5705.2006.00288.x|jstor=27552748}}</ref> By 1987, the United States was sending over $600 million a year, as well as weapons, intelligence, and combat expertise to Afghanistan. The Soviet Union announced it would withdraw from Afghanistan in 1987, but the U.S. was subjected to [[blowback (intelligence)|blowback]] in the form of the [[Taliban]] and [[al-Qaeda]], two groups that arose out of the Mujahideen and that would oppose the United States in future conflicts.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n===Central America and the Caribbean===\n{{see also|Latin America\u2013United States relations}}\n\n[[File:REAGANEugeniaCharles.jpg|thumb|right|Reagan meets with Prime Minister [[Eugenia Charles]] of [[Dominica]] in the [[Oval Office]] about ongoing events in [[Grenada]]]]\n\nThe Reagan administration placed a high priority on the [[Central America]] and the [[Caribbean Sea]], which it saw as a key front in the Cold War. Reagan and his foreign policy team were particularly concerned about the potential influence of [[Cuba]] on countries such as [[Grenada]], [[Nicaragua]], and [[El Salvador]]. To counter the influence of Cuba and the Soviet Union, Reagan launched the [[Caribbean Basin Initiative]], an economic program designed to aid countries opposed to Communism. He also authorized covert measures, such as the arming of Nicaragua's [[Contras]], in order to minimize Cuban and Soviet influence in the region.<ref>Brands, pp. 350-357</ref> The administration provided support to right-wing governments throughout Latin America, disregarding humans rights abuses in countries like [[Argentina]] and El Salvador.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 73, 77\u201379</ref>\n\nIn 1983, pro-Communist forces led a coup in the [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]] island of [[Grenada]]. After learning that Cuban construction workers were building an airfield on Grenada, Reagan dispatched approximately 5,000 U.S. soldiers to [[United States invasion of Grenada|invade Grenada]]. After two days of fighting that resulted in the deaths of nineteen Americans, forty-five Grenadans, and fifty-nine Cubans, the left-wing government of Grenada was overthrown.<ref>Patterson, pp. 205\u2013206</ref> While the invasion enjoyed public support in the United States and Grenada<ref name=Magnuson>{{Cite news| last =Magnuson |first =Ed |title =Getting Back to Normal |newspaper=Time |date =21 November 1983 |url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926318-1,00.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Age of Reagan: The Conservative Counterrevolution: 1980\u20131989|publisher=Crown Forum|isbn=978-1-4000-5357-5|author=Steven F. Hayward|year=2009|author-link=Steven F. Hayward}}</ref> it was criticized by the United Kingdom, Canada and the [[United Nations General Assembly]] as \"a flagrant violation of [[international law]]\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/depts/dhl/resguide/r38.htm |title=United Nations General Assembly resolution 38/7, page 19 |publisher=United Nations |date=2 November 1983}}</ref>\n\n===Iran\u2013Contra affair===\n{{Main|Iran\u2013Contra affair}}\n{{See also|Reagan administration scandals}}\n\nIn 1979, a group of left-wing rebels in Nicaragua known as the [[Sandinistas]] overthrew the president of Nicaragua and installed [[Daniel Ortega]] as the country's leader.<ref>Patterson, pp. 207\u2013208</ref> Fearing that Communists would take over Nicaragua if it remained under the leadership of the Sandinistas, the Reagan administration authorized CIA Director William J. Casey to arm the right-wing [[Contras]]. Congress, which favored negotiations between the Contras and Sandinista, passed the 1982 [[Boland Amendment]], prohibiting the CIA and Defense Department from using their budgets to provide aid to the Contras. Still intent on supporting the Contras, the Reagan administration raised funds for the Contras from private donors and foreign governments.<ref>Weisberg, pp. 128-129</ref> When Congress learned that the CIA had secretly placed [[naval mine]]s in Nicaraguan harbors, Congress passed a second Boland Amendment that barred granting any assistance to the Contras.<ref>Patterson, pp. 208\u2013209</ref>\n\nDuring his second term, Reagan sought to find a way procure the release of seven American hostages held by [[Hezbollah]], a [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] paramilitary group supported by Iran. The Reagan administration decided to sell American arms to Iran, then engaged in the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]], in hopes that Iran would pressure Hezbollah to release the hostages.<ref name=\"weisberg129134\"/> Secretary of Defense Weinberger and Secretary of State Shultz both opposed the arrangement, so it was handled by National Security Advisor [[Robert McFarlane]] and McFarlane's successor, [[John Poindexter]].<ref>Patterson, pp. 209\u2013210</ref> The Reagan administration sold over 2000 missiles to Iran without informing Congress; Hezbollah released four hostages but captured an additional six Americans. On the initiative of [[Oliver North]], an aide on the National Security Council, the Reagan administration redirected the proceeds from the missile sales to the Contras.<ref name=\"weisberg129134\">Weisberg, pp. 129-134</ref> The transactions became public knowledge by early November 1986. Reagan initially denied any wrongdoing, but on November 25 he announced that Poindexter and North had left the administration and that he would form the [[Tower Commission]] to investigate the transactions. A few weeks later, Reagan asked a panel of federal judges to appoint a [[United States Office of the Independent Counsel|special prosecutor]] who would conduct a separate investigation, and the panel chose [[Lawrence Walsh]].<ref>Patterson, pp. 210\u2013211</ref>\n\nThe Tower Commission, chaired by former Republican Senator [[John Tower]], released a report in February 1987 that confirmed that the administration had traded arms for hostages and sent the proceeds of the weapons sales to the Contras. The report laid most of the blame for the operation on North, Poindexter, and McFarlane, but it was also critical of Regan and other White House staffers.<ref>Brands, pp. 646-649</ref> In response to the Tower Commission report, Reagan stated, \"Its findings are honest, convincing and highly critical...As angry as I may be about activities undertaken without my knowledge, I am still accountable for those activities.\"<ref>Brands, pp. 650-653</ref> The [[Iran\u2013Contra scandal]], as it became known, did serious damage to the Reagan presidency, raising questions about Reagan's competency and the wisdom of conservative policies.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 202\u2013204</ref> A poll taken in March 1987 showed that 85 percent of respondents believed that the Reagan administration had engaged in an organized cover-up, and half of the respondents believed that Reagan had been personally involved. The administration's credibility was also badly damaged on the international stage, as it had violated its own arms embargo on Iran.<ref name=\"brands653674\">Brands, pp. 653, 674</ref> Congressional Democrats considered [[Impeachment in the United States|impeaching]], but decided that it would be an unwise use of political capital against a weakened president; Democrats were also somewhat mollified by Reagan's decision to replace Chief of Staff Regan with Howard Baker.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 216\u2013217</ref>\n\nThe investigations into the Iran\u2013Contra scandal continued after Reagan left office, but were effectively halted when President George H. W. Bush pardoned Secretary of Defense Caspar Weinberger before his trial began.<ref>Brinkley, A. (2009). ''American History: A Survey Vol. II'', p. 887, New York: McGraw-Hill</ref> Investigators did not find conclusive proof that Reagan had known about the aid provided to the Contras, but Walsh's report noted that Reagan had \"created the conditions which made possible the crimes committed by others\" and had \"knowingly participated or acquiesced in covering up the scandal.\"<ref>Patterson, pp. 211\u2013212</ref>\n\n===End of the Cold War===\n{{See also|Cold War (1985\u20131991)}}\n[[File:Reagan and Gorbachev signing.jpg|thumb|right|Gorbachev and Reagan sign the [[INF Treaty]] at the White House, 1987]]\n\nThree different [[List of leaders of the Soviet Union|Soviet leaders]] died between 1982 and 1985, leaving the Soviets with an unstable leadership until [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] came to power in 1985.<ref name=\"auto1\">Herring, p. 894</ref> Although the Soviet Union had not accelerated military spending during Reagan's military buildup,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/past/politics/foreign/reagrus.htm|title=Reagan and the Russians|date=February 1994|work=The Atlantic|last1=Lebow |first1=Richard Ned |last2=Stein |first2=Janice Gross |lastauthoramp=yes |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> their large military expenses, in combination with [[Collectivization in the Soviet Union|collectivized agriculture]] and inefficient [[planned economy|planned manufacturing]], were a heavy burden for the [[Economy of the Soviet Union|Soviet economy]].<ref name=\"Gaidar\">{{Cite book|last=Gaidar|first=Yegor|title=Collapse of an Empire: Lessons for Modern Russia|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|year=2007|isbn=978-5-8243-0759-7|language=Russian|pages=190\u2013205}}</ref> Gorbachev was less ideologically rigid than his predecessors, and he believed that the Soviet Union urgently needed economic and political reforms.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In 1986, he introduced his twin reforms of [[perestroika]] and [[glasnost]], which would change the political and economic conditions of the Soviet Union.<ref>Brands, pp. 675\u2013676</ref> Seeking to reduce military expenditures and minimize the possibility of nuclear war, he also sought to re-open negotiations with the United States over arms control.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAs his influence on domestic affairs waned during his second term, Reagan increasingly focused on relations with the Soviet Union.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 225\u2013226</ref> Reagan recognized the change in the direction of the Soviet leadership under Gorbachev, and shifted to diplomacy, with a view to encourage the Soviet leader to pursue substantial arms agreements. Reagan's personal mission was to achieve a world free of nuclear weapons, which according to [[Jack F. Matlock Jr.]], Reagan's ambassador to Moscow, he regarded as \"totally irrational, totally inhumane, good for nothing but killing, possibly destructive of life on earth and civilization.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul Vorbeck Lettow|title=Ronald Reagan And His Quest to Abolish Nuclear Weapons|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=36pYekyje-kC&pg=PA133|year=2006|page=133|isbn=9780812973266}}</ref> Gorbachev and Reagan agreed to meet at the 1985 [[Geneva Summit (1985)|Geneva Summit]], where they issued a joint statement indicating that neither the U.S. nor the Soviet Union would \"seek to achieve military superiority.\"<ref>Rossinow, pp. 225\u2013227</ref> The two leaders began a private correspondence after the summit, and each became increasingly optimistic about arms control negotiations.<ref>Herring, pp. 895\u2013896</ref> Reagan's willingness to negotiate with the Soviets was opposed by many conservatives, including Weinberger; conservative columnist [[George Will]] wrote that Reagan was \"elevating wishful thinking to the status of a political philosophy.\"<ref>Patterson, pp. 214\u2013215</ref>\n\nVarious issues, including intelligence operations performed by both countries and tensions in Germany and Afghanistan, threatened to forestall the possibility of an agreement between the United States and the Soviet Union. Nonetheless, both Gorbachev and Reagan agreed to continue arms control negotiations at the October 1986 [[Reykjav\u00edk Summit]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 228\u2013230</ref> At the summit, Gorbachev and Reagan closed in on an agreement to greatly reduce or eliminate the nuclear stockpiles of both the U.S. and the Soviet Union over a ten-year period, but the deal collapsed due to disagreements regarding SDI development.<ref>Brands, pp. 596\u2013604</ref> Reagan attacked Gorbachev in a [[Tear down this wall!|1987 speech]] delivered in [[West Berlin]], but negotiations continued.<ref name=\"patterson215\">Patterson, p. 215</ref> Gorbachev and Reagan broke the impasse by agreeing to negotiate separate treaties on intermediate nuclear forces (such as [[intermediate-range ballistic missile]]s) and strategic arms (such as [[intercontinental ballistic missile]]s).<ref>Brands, pp. 676-677</ref>\n\nWith the framework for an agreement in place, Reagan and Gorbachev met at the 1987 [[Washington Summit (1987)|Washington Summit]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 234\u2013235</ref> They signed the [[Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty]] (INF Treaty), which committed both signatories to the total abolition of their respective short-range and medium-range missile stockpiles.<ref name=\"patterson215\"/> The agreement marked the first time that the United States and the Soviet Union had committed to the elimination of a type of nuclear weapon, though it provided for the dismantlement of only about one-twentieth of the worldwide nuclear weapon arsenal. The treaty also established an inspections regime designed to ensure that both parties honored the agreement.<ref>Rossinow, p. 236</ref> In addition to the INF Treaty, Reagan and Gorbachev discussed a potential strategic arms treaty, known as START, but SDI continued to be a major point of contention.<ref>Brands, pp. 682-685</ref> In May 1988, the Senate voted 93-to-5 in favor of ratifying the INF Treaty.<ref>Patterson, p. 216</ref>\n\n[[File:President Reagan's Trip to USSR, Walking in Red Square with Mikhail Gorbachev, Moscow, May 31, 1988.webm|thumb|right|President Reagan's Trip to USSR, Walking in Red Square with Mikhail Gorbachev, Moscow, May 31, 1988]]\nThough it was attacked by conservatives like Jesse Helms, the INF Treaty provided a major boost to Reagan's popularity in the aftermath of the Iran\u2013Contra Affair. A new era of trade and openness between the two powers commenced, and the U.S. and the Soviet Union cooperated on international issues such as the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]].<ref>Herring, pp. 897\u2013898</ref> When Reagan visited Moscow for a [[Moscow Summit (1988)|fourth summit]] with Gorbachev in 1988, he was viewed as a celebrity by the Soviets. A journalist asked the president if he still considered the Soviet Union the evil empire. \"No,\" he replied, \"I was talking about another time, another era.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Talbott|first=Strobe|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 5, 1991|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,973554-5,00.html|title=The Summit Goodfellas|accessdate=January 26, 2008}}</ref> At Gorbachev's request, Reagan gave a speech on free markets at the [[Moscow State University]].<ref>Reagan (1990), p. 713</ref> In December 1988, Gorbachev effectively renounced the [[Brezhnev Doctrine]], paving the way for democratization in Eastern Europe.<ref>Herring, pp. 898\u2013899</ref> In November 1989, ten months after Reagan left office, the [[Berlin Wall]] [[Fall of the Berlin Wall|fell]]. The Cold War was unofficially declared over at the [[Malta Summit]] the following month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/3/newsid_4119000/4119950.stm|title=1989: Malta summit ends Cold War|publisher=BBC News|date=December 3, 1984|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East===\n\n====Lebanon====\n\nA [[Lebanese Civil War|civil war]] had broken out in [[Lebanon]] in 1975, and both [[Israel]] and [[Syria]] undertook military action within Lebanon in 1982.<ref>Brands, pp. 366-367</ref> After Israel [[1982 Lebanon War|invaded]] [[Southern Lebanon]], Reagan faced domestic and international pressure to oppose the Israeli invasion, but Reagan was reluctant to openly break Israel. Reagan sympathized with Israeli's desire to defeat [[Palestine Liberation Organization|PLO]] forces that had struck Israel from Lebanon, but he pressured Israel to end its invasion as casualties mounted and Israeli forces approached the Lebanese capital of [[Beirut]].<ref>Brands, pp. 382-385</ref> American diplomat [[Philip Habib]] arranged a cease-fire in which Israel, Syria, and the PLO, all agreed to evacuate their forces from Lebanon. As Israel delayed a full withdrawal and violence continued in Lebanon, Reagan arranged for a [[Multinational Force in Lebanon|multinational force]], including [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marines]], to serve as peacekeepers in Lebanon.<ref>Brands, pp. 386-389</ref> In October 1983, [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings|two nearly-simultaneous bombings]] in Beirut killed 241 American soldiers and 58 French soldiers.<ref>Brands, pp. 394-395</ref> The international peacekeeping force was withdrawn from Lebanon in 1984. In reaction to the role Israel and the United States played in the Lebanese Civil War, a [[Shia Islam|Shia]] militant group known as [[Hezbollah]] began to take American hostages, holding eight Americans by the middle of 1985.<ref>Brands, pp. 488-491</ref> The Reagan administration's attempts to release these hostages would be a major component of the Iran-Contra Scandal. In response to the U.S. intervention in Lebanon, the Defense Department developed the \"[[Powell Doctrine]],\" which stated that the U.S. should intervene militarily as a last resort and should set clear and limited goals in such interventions.<ref>Herring, p. 875</ref> Though termed the Powell doctrine, the policy was originally developed by Secretary of Defense Weinberger, who was influenced not only by Lebanon but also by the experience of the Vietnam War.<ref>Patterson, pp. 200\u2013201</ref>\n\n====Libya bombing====\n{{Main|1986 United States bombing of Libya}}\n[[File:President Reagan and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at Camp David 1986.jpg|thumb|British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] (here walking with Reagan at [[Camp David]] in 1986) granted the U.S. use of British airbases to launch the Libya attack]]\n\nRelations between Libya and the United States under President Reagan were continually contentious, beginning with the [[Gulf of Sidra incident (1981)|Gulf of Sidra incident]] in 1981; by 1982, Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] was considered by the CIA to be, along with USSR leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]] and Cuban leader [[Fidel Castro]], part of a group known as the \"unholy trinity\" and was also labeled as \"our international public enemy number one\" by a CIA official.<ref name=iokp;>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,925697,00.htm | title= Libya: Fury in the Isolation Ward|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 23, 1982|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref> These tensions were later revived in early April 1986, when [[1986 Berlin discotheque bombing|a bomb exploded in a West Berlin discoth\u00e8que]], resulting in the injury of 63 American military personnel and death of one serviceman. Stating that there was \"irrefutable proof\" that Libya had directed the \"terrorist bombing,\" Reagan authorized the use of force against the country. In the late evening of April 15, 1986, the United States launched a series of [[airstrike]]s on ground targets in Libya.<ref name=\"gs-libya\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/el_dorado_canyon.htm|title=Operation El Dorado Canyon|publisher=GlobalSecurity.org|date=April 25, 2005|accessdate=April 19, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"4-15\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/15/newsid_3975000/3975455.stm|title=1986:US Launches air-strike on Libya|accessdate=April 19, 2008|date=April 15, 2008|publisher=BBC News }}</ref>\n\nBritain's prime minister, Margaret Thatcher, allowed the U.S. Air Force to use Britain's air bases to launch the attack, on the justification that the UK was supporting America's right to self-defense under Article 51 of the [[United Nations Charter]].<ref name=\"4-15\" /> The attack was designed to halt Gaddafi's \"ability to export terrorism,\" offering him \"incentives and reasons to alter his criminal behavior.\"<ref name=\"gs-libya\" /> The president addressed the nation from the [[Oval Office]] after the attacks had commenced, stating, \"When our citizens are attacked or abused anywhere in the world on the direct orders of hostile regimes, we will respond so long as I'm in this office.\"<ref name=\"4-15\" /> The attack was condemned by many countries. By a vote of 79 in favor to 28 against with 33 abstentions, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] adopted resolution 41/38 which \"condemns the military attack perpetrated against the Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya on April 15, 1986, which constitutes a violation of the Charter of the United Nations and of international law.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/documents/ga/res/41/a41r038.htm |title=A/RES/41/38 November 20, 1986 |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===South Africa===\n\n{{main|South Africa under apartheid}}\n[[File:Reagan with Desmond TutuC26199-10.jpg|thumb|President Reagan meeting with South African anti-apartheid activist [[Desmond Tutu]] in 1984]]\nDuring Ronald Reagan's presidency [[South Africa]] continued to use a non-democratic system of government based on racial discrimination, known as [[apartheid]], in which the minority of white South Africans exerted nearly complete legal control over the lives of the non-white majority of the citizens. In the early 1980s the issue had moved to the center of international attention as a result of events in the townships and outcry at the death of [[Stephen Biko]]. Reagan administration policy called for \"[[constructive engagement]]\" with the apartheid government of South Africa. In opposition to the condemnations issued by the U.S. Congress and public demands for diplomatic or economic sanctions, Reagan made relatively minor criticisms of the regime, which was otherwise internationally isolated, and the U.S. granted recognition to the government. South Africa's military was then engaged in an occupation of [[Namibia]] and [[proxy war]]s in several neighboring countries, in alliance with Savimbi's UNITA. Reagan administration officials saw the apartheid government as a key anti-communist ally.<ref>[http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/embargo/rknight840403.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701053013/http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/embargo/rknight840403.htm |date=July 1, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nFinding the Reagan Administration unresponsive to its calls for more stringent economic sanctions, anti-apartheid activists undertook a [[Disinvestment from South Africa|divestment campaign]], aimed at moving individuals and institutions to sell their holdings in companies doing business in South Africa. By late 1985, facing escalating public and congressional opposition to his administration's tolerant attitude toward the South African government's policy of apartheid, Reagan made an \"abrupt reversal\" on the issue and proposed sanctions on the South African government, including an [[arms embargo]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=William E. |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,959843,00.html |title=South Africa Reagan's Abrupt Reversal |publisher=TIME |date=September 16, 1985 |accessdate=April 14, 2014 }}</ref>  However, these sanctions were seen as weak by anti-apartheid activists,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZZopAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AYQDAAAAIBAJ&dq=anti-apartheid+act+reagan&pg=4676,4983327|title=The Deseret News - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref> and as insufficient by the president's opponents in Congress, including 81 House Republicans. In August 1986, Congress approved the [[Comprehensive Anti-Apartheid Act]], which included tougher sanctions. Reagan vetoed the act, but this was overridden by a bipartisan effort in Congress.<ref>{{cite web| last=Glass| first=Andrew| title=House overrides Reagan apartheid veto, Sept. 29, 1986| date=September 27, 2017| url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/29/house-overrides-reagan-apartheid-veto-sept-29-1986-243169| publisher=Politico| accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> By 1990, under Reagan's successor George H. W. Bush, the new South African government of [[F. W. de Klerk]] was introducing widespread reforms, though the Bush administration argued that this was not a result of the tougher sanctions.<ref>George Gedda, {{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iOJLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uIsDAAAAIBAJ&dq=bush+sanctions+south+africa+1989&pg=4903,1578476|title=Analysts differ on sanctions tie to apartheid|website=news.google.com}}, ''The Free Lance-Star'' (Jul 11, 1991)</ref>\n\n===Free trade===\nDuring his 1980 presidential campaign, Reagan proposed the creation of a [[Single market|common market]] in North America. Once in office, Reagan signed the [[Trade and Tariff Act of 1984]], which granted the president \"[[fast track (trade)|fast track]]\" authority in negotiating [[United States free-trade agreements|free trade agreements]].<ref name=\"kamadeo1\"/> In 1985, Reagan signed the [[Israel\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement]], the first bilateral free trade agreement in U.S. history.<ref name=\"mtolchin1\">{{cite news|last1=Tolchin|first1=Martin|title=U.S. Signs Trade Pact With Israel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/23/business/us-signs-trade-pact-with-israel.html|accessdate=28 November 2017|work=New York Times|date=23 April 1985}}</ref> In 1988, Reagan and [[Canada|Canadian]] Prime Minister [[Brian Mulroney]] signed the [[Canada\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement]], which greatly reduced trade barriers between the United States and Canada. This trade pact would serve as the foundation for the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] among the United States, Canada, and [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"kamadeo1\">{{cite web|last1=Amadeo|first1=Kimberly|title=History of NAFTA and Its Purpose|url=https://www.thebalance.com/history-of-nafta-3306272|website=The Balance|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===International travel===\n{{Main|List of international presidential trips made by Ronald Reagan}}\n[[File:Ronald Reagan Overseas Visits.svg|thumb|World map highlighting countries visited by Ronald Reagan while president]]\n\nReagan made 25 international trips to 26 different countries on four [[continents]]&mdash;Europe, Asia, North America, and South America&mdash;during his presidency.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/president/reagan-ronald|title= Travels of President Ronald Reagan|publisher= U.S. Department of State Office of the Historian}}</ref> He made seven trips to continental Europe, three to Asia and one to South America. He is perhaps best remembered for his speeches at the 40th anniversary of the [[Normandy landings]], for his impassioned speech at the [[Berlin Wall]], his summit meetings with [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], and riding horses with [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] at Windsor Park.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n==Age and health==\n[[File:Ronald Reagan February 11, 1985.jpg|thumb|Reagan in February 1985]]\nAt the time of his inauguration, Reagan was the oldest person to be inaugurated as President (age 69).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.potus.com/presidential-facts/age-at-inauguration/|title=Age at Inauguration {{!}} Presidents of the United States (POTUS)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> He remains the oldest person to have held the office; he had reached the age of 77 when his second term ended. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reaganlibrary.gov/sreference/the-reagan-presidency|title=The Reagan Presidency {{!}} Ronald Reagan Presidential Library - National Archives and Records Administration|website=www.reaganlibrary.gov|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> Reagan's health became a concern{{To whom?|date=November 2018}} at times during his presidency.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Former White House correspondent [[Lesley Stahl]] later wrote that she and other reporters noticed what might have been early symptoms of Reagan's later [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref name=\"american chronicle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/6883|work=American Chronicle |date=March 15, 2006|title=Happy Anniversary to the first scheduled presidential press conference - 93 years young! |first=Robert |last=Rouse}}</ref> She said that on her last day on the beat, Reagan spoke to her for a few moments and did not seem to know who she was before returning to his normal behavior.<ref name=\"american chronicle\"/>{{dead link|date=November 2018}} However, Reagan's primary physician, Dr. John Hutton, has said that Reagan \"absolutely\" did not \"show any signs of dementia or Alzheimer's\" during his presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F02E1DE133DF936A35753C1A961958260|title=Reagan's Twilight&nbsp;\u2013 A special report; A President Fades into a World Apart |accessdate=2008-06-18|author=Altman, Lawrence K|date=October 5, 1997|work=The New York Times}}</ref> His doctors have noted that he began exhibiting Alzheimer's symptoms only after he left the White House.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DE5D61030F936A25755C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|title=The Doctors World; A Recollection of Early Questions About Reagan's Health|author=Altman, Lawrence K., M.D.|date=June 15, 2004 |accessdate=2008-11-11}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 1985, Reagan underwent surgery to remove [[polyp (medicine)|polyps]] from his [[colon (anatomy)|colon]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/12/18/us/reagan-s-health-problems.html|title=Reagan's Health Problems|date=1986-12-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> causing the first-ever invocation of the [[Acting President of the United States|Acting President]] clause of the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|25th Amendment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/news/reagan-health-25th-amendment|title=Reagan Aides Once Raised the Possibility of Invoking the 25th Amendment|last=Little|first=Becky|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> On January 5, 1987, Reagan underwent surgery for [[prostate cancer]] which caused further worries about his health, but which significantly raised public awareness of this \"silent killer\".{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Presidential elections==\n===1984 election===\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1984.svg|right|thumb|1984 electoral vote results]]\n{{Main|Ronald Reagan 1984 presidential campaign|1984 United States presidential election}}\n\nReagan's approval ratings fell after his first year in office, but they bounced back when the United States began to emerge from recession in 1983.<ref>Leuchtenberg, pp. 620-621</ref> The leading candidates in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1984|1984 Democratic presidential primaries]] were former Vice President [[Walter Mondale]], Senator [[Gary Hart]] of Colorado, and African-American civil rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]]. Though Hart won several primaries, Mondale ultimately won the nomination. Down in the polls, Mondale [[Democratic Party vice presidential candidate selection, 1984|selected]] Congresswoman [[Geraldine Ferraro]] as his running mate in hopes of galvanizing support for his campaign, thus making Ferraro the first female major party vice presidential nominee in U.S. history.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 166\u2013169, 173</ref> In accepting the Democratic nomination, Mondale attacked Reagan's policies regarding the environment, Social Security, nuclear arms, civil rights, and other issues, stating that the Reagan administration was \"of the rich, by the rich, and for the rich.\"<ref>Rossinow, pp. 171\u2013172</ref> He also criticized the federal debt accumulated under Reagan, stating, \"...The budget will be squeezed. Taxes will go up. And anyone who says they won't is not telling the truth to the American people.\"<ref name=\"Brands, pp. 452-453\"/>\n\nReagan, meanwhile, generally declined to offer new legislative proposals for his re-election campaign, instead focusing on events like the U.S.-hosted [[1984 Summer Olympics]] and the 40th anniversary of the [[Normandy landings]].<ref>Rossinow, pp. 169\u2013170, 176</ref> Reagan's ability to perform the duties of president for another term was questioned by some observers, especially after a weak performance in the first presidential debate. His apparent confused and forgetful behavior was evident to his supporters; they had previously known him clever and witty. Rumors began to circulate that he had [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/editors200410040912.asp|title=The Debate: Mondale vs. Reagan|work=National Review|date=October 4, 2004|accessdate=May 25, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416191912/http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/editors200410040912.asp <!-- Added by H3llBot -->|archivedate=April 16, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/debatingourdestiny/newshour/84_1stprez-analysis.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010218175006/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/debatingourdestiny/newshour/84_1stprez-analysis.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 18, 2001|title=Reaction to first Mondale/Reagan debate|publisher=PBS|date=October 8, 1984|accessdate=December 31, 2007}}</ref> Reagan rebounded in the second debate, and confronted questions about his age, quipping, \"I will not make age an issue of this campaign. I am not going to exploit, for political purposes, my opponent's youth and inexperience,\" which generated applause and laughter, even from Mondale himself.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cgi.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/debates/history/1984/|title=1984 Presidential Debates|publisher=CNN|accessdate=May 25, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308065739/http://cgi.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/debates/history/1984/|archivedate=March 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPublic opinion polling consistently showed a Reagan lead in the 1984 campaign, and Mondale was unable to shake up the race.<ref>Rossinow, p. 173</ref> In the end, Reagan won re-election, winning 49 of 50 states.<ref name=\"84 results\" /> Mondale carried only his home state of Minnesota and the District of Columbia. Reagan won a record 525 electoral votes,<ref name=\"pres\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/pressketch.html|title=The Reagan Presidency|accessdate=April 19, 2008|publisher=Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation}}</ref> and received 59% of the popular vote to Mondale's 41%.<ref name=\"84 results\">{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1984|title=1984 Presidential Election Results|publisher=David Leip|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref> Compared to 1980, Reagan's strongest gains came among white Southern voters, and he also performed particularly well among Catholic voters, voters between the ages of eighteen and twenty-nine, and voters over the age of sixty.<ref>Rossinow, pp. 173\u2013174</ref> In the concurrent congressional elections, Republicans retained control of the Senate and Democrats retained control of the House.<ref>Patterson, p. 190</ref>\n\n===1988 election===\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1988.svg|right|thumb|1988 electoral vote results]]\n\nReagan remained publicly neutral in the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1988|1988 Republican presidential primaries]], but privately supported Vice President Bush over Senator [[Bob Dole]]. The [[1988 Republican National Convention]], which nominated Bush for president, also acted as a celebration of Reagan's presidency.<ref>Brands, pp. 697-698</ref> Democrats nominated [[Michael Dukakis]], the liberal Governor of Massachusetts. Following the [[1988 Democratic National Convention]], Dukakis led the polls by seventeen points, but Bush, aided by the INF Treaty and the strong economy, closed the gap as the election neared. Democrats tried to link Bush to the Iran-Contra Scandal, but Bush claimed that he had not been involved. The GOP effectively cast Dukakis as \"soft\" on crime and foreign policy issues, seizing on Dukakis's pardon of [[Willie Horton]] and his dispassionate response to a question regarding the [[capital punishment|death penalty]]. In the [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential election]], Bush defeated Dukakis, taking 53.4 percent of the popular vote and 426 electoral votes. The election saw the lowest turnout of eligible voters since [[1924 United States presidential election|1924]]. In the concurrent congressional elections, Democrats retained control of the House and the Senate.<ref>Patterson, pp. 220\u2013225</ref> In large part due to his handling of relations with the Soviet Union, Reagan left office with an approval rating of sixty-eight percent.<ref>Patterson, p. 217</ref>\n\n==Evaluation and legacy==\n[[File:Gallup Poll-Approval Rating-Ronald Reagan.png|thumb|upright=1.5|Graph of Reagan's approval ratings in [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] polls]]\n\nSince Reagan left office in 1989, substantial debate has occurred among scholars, historians, and the general public surrounding his legacy.<ref>Andrew L. Johns, ed., ''A Companion to Ronald Reagan'' (Wiley-Blackwell, 2015).</ref> Supporters have pointed to a more efficient and prosperous economy as a result of Reagan's economic policies,<ref>Hayward, pp.&nbsp;635\u2013638</ref> foreign policy triumphs including a peaceful end to the Cold War,<ref>Beschloss, p. 324</ref> and a restoration of American pride and morale.<ref name=\"cannon746\">Cannon (1991, 2000), p. 746</ref> Proponents also argue Reagan restored faith in the American Dream<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/OPINION/02/02/rollins.reagan/|title=Ronald Reagan restored faith in America|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> after a decline in American confidence and self-respect under Jimmy Carter's perceived weak leadership, particularly during the [[Iran hostage crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipset|first1=Seymour Martin|last2=Schneider|first2=William|title=The Decline of Confidence in American Institutions|url=http://www.planethan.com/drupal/sites/default/files/The%20Decline%20of%20Confidence%20in%20American%20Institutions%20%20By%20Lipset%20Seymour%20Martin%20and%20Schneider%20William%20Political%20Science%20Quarterly%20Fall83%20Vol%2098%20Issue%203%20p379.pdf|work=Political Science Quarterly|accessdate=July 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822132334/http://www.planethan.com/drupal/sites/default/files/The%20Decline%20of%20Confidence%20in%20American%20Institutions%20%20By%20Lipset%20Seymour%20Martin%20and%20Schneider%20William%20Political%20Science%20Quarterly%20Fall83%20Vol%2098%20Issue%203%20p379.pdf|archivedate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> Reagan remains an important symbol of American conservatism, much in the same way that Franklin Roosevelt continued to serve as a symbol of liberalism long after his own death.<ref>Rossinow, p. 293</ref>\n\nCritics contend that Reagan's economic policies resulted in rising budget deficits,<ref name=\"Cannon128\">Cannon (2001), p. 128</ref> a wider [[Wealth inequality in the United States|gap in wealth]], and an increase in [[homelessness]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/reagans-real-legacy/ |title=Reagan's Real Legacy |last=Dreier |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Dreier |date=2011-02-04 |website=[[The Nation]] |language=en-US |access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref> Liberals especially disapproved of Reagan's simultaneous tax cuts for the wealthy and benefit cuts for the poor.<ref>Patterson, p. 158</ref> Some critics assert that the Iran\u2013Contra affair lowered American credibility.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilman|first=Larry|url=http://www.espionageinfo.com/Int-Ke/Iran-Contra-Affair.html|title=Iran-Contra Affair|publisher=Advameg|accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref> In his popular book, ''The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers'', historian [[Paul Kennedy]] argued that Reagan's high level of defense would eventually lead to the decline of the United States as a [[great power]].<ref>Patterson, p. 202</ref> Reagan's leadership and understanding of issues has also been questioned, and even some members of the administration criticized Reagan's passive demeanor during meetings with staff and cabinet members.<ref>Patterson, pp. 160-161</ref> [[Richard Pipes]], a member of the National Security Council, criticized Reagan as \"really lost, out of his depth, uncomfortable\" at NSC meetings.<ref>Leffler, p. 349</ref> Another NSC member, [[Colin Powell]], criticized Reagan's \"passive management style [that] placed a tremendous burden on us.\u201d<ref>Pemberton, p. 151</ref>\n\nDespite the continuing debate surrounding his legacy, many conservative and liberal scholars agree that Reagan has been one of the most influential presidents since Franklin Roosevelt, leaving his imprint on American politics, diplomacy, culture, and economics through his effective communication, dedicated patriotism and pragmatic compromising.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://millercenter.org/president/reagan/essays/biography/8|title=American President|accessdate=October 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011080053/http://millercenter.org/president/reagan/essays/biography/8|archivedate=October 11, 2014}}</ref> Since he left office, historians have reached a consensus,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Henry|first1=David|title=Ronald Reagan and the 1980s: Perceptions, Policies, Legacies. Ed. by Cheryl Hudson and Gareth Davies. (New York: Palgrave Macmillan, 2008. xiv, 268 pp. $84.95, ISBN 978-0-230-60302-8.)|journal=[[The Journal of American History]]|date=December 2009|volume=96|issue=3|pages=933\u2013934|doi=10.1093/jahist/96.3.933|jstor=25622627}}</ref> as summarized by British historian M. J. Heale, who finds that scholars now concur that Reagan rehabilitated conservatism, turned the nation to the right, practiced a considerably pragmatic conservatism that balanced ideology and the constraints of politics, revived faith in the presidency and in [[American exceptionalism]], and contributed to victory in the Cold War.<ref>Heale, M.J. in Cheryl Hudson and Gareth Davies, eds. ''Ronald Reagan and the 1980s: Perceptions, Policies, Legacies'' (2008) Palgrave Macmillan {{ISBN|0-230-60302-5}} p. 250</ref> [[Hugh Heclo]] argues that Reagan himself failed to roll back the [[welfare state]], but that he contributed to a shift in attitudes that led to the defeat of efforts to further expand the welfare state.<ref>Heclo, pp. 558\u2013560</ref> Heclo further argues that Reagan's presidency made American voters and political leaders more tolerant of deficits and more opposed to taxation.<ref>Heclo, pp. 562\u2013563</ref> In 2017, a C-SPAN survey of scholars ranked Reagan as the ninth greatest president.<ref>See [https://static.c-span.org/assets/documents/presidentSurvey/2017%20C-SPAN%20Presidential%20Survey%20Scores%20and%20Ranks%20FINAL.PDF \"S-SPAN 2017 Survey of Presidential Leadership\" '' C-SPAN'']</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Andrew L. Johns, ed.|title=A Companion to Ronald Reagan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aaueBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2|year=2015|publisher=Wiley|pages=1\u20132|isbn=9781118607824}}</ref> A 2018 poll of the [[American Political Science Association]]\u2019s Presidents and Executive Politics section also ranked Reagan as the ninth greatest president.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rottinghaus|first1=Brandon|last2=Vaughn|first2=Justin S.|title=How Does Trump Stack Up Against the Best \u2014 and Worst \u2014 Presidents?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/02/19/opinion/how-does-trump-stack-up-against-the-best-and-worst-presidents.html/|accessdate=14 May 2018|work=New York Times|date=19 February 2018}}</ref> A 2006 poll of historians ranked the Iran-Contra affair as the ninth-worst mistake made by a sitting American president.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scholars rate worst presidential errors |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/2006-02-18-presidential-goofs_x.htm |accessdate=31 August 2018 |agency=AP |publisher=USA Today |date=18 February 2006}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1980s|United States|Politics|Conservatism}}\n* [[History of the United States (1980\u201391)]]\n* [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher]]\n* [[Ronald Reagan Presidential Library]], Simi Valley, California\n* [[600-ship Navy]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Brands|first1=H.W.|title=Reagan: The Life|date=2015|publisher=Doubleday|location=New York}}\n* {{cite book|last = Beschloss|first=Michael|title=Presidential Courage: Brave Leaders and How They Changed America 1789\u20131989|url = https://archive.org/details/presidentialcour00besc|url-access = registration|year =2007|publisher=Simon & Schuster}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cannon|first=Lou|authorlink=Lou Cannon|title=President Reagan: The Role of a Lifetime|year=2000|publisher=Public Affairs|location=New York|isbn=1-891620-91-6|url=https://archive.org/details/presidentreagan000cann}}\n* {{cite book | title = Ronald Reagan: The Presidential Portfolio: A History Illustrated from the Collection of the Ronald Reagan Library and Museum | first = Lou | last = Cannon | authorlink = Lou Cannon | author2 = Michael Beschloss | publisher = PublicAffairs | isbn = 1-891620-84-3 | year = 2001 | url = https://archive.org/details/ronaldreaganpres00cann }}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Heclo|first1=Hugh|title=The Mixed Legacies of Ronald Reagan|journal=Presidential Studies Quarterly|date=2008|volume=38|issue=4|pages=555\u2013574|doi=10.1111/j.1741-5705.2008.02664.x|jstor=41219701}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Herring|first1=George C.|title=From Colony to Superpower; U.S. Foreign Relations Since 1776|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-507822-0|url=https://archive.org/details/fromcolonytosupe00herr}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Leffler|first1=Melvyn P.|title=For the Soul of Mankind: the United States, the Soviet Union, and the Cold War|url=https://archive.org/details/forsoulofmankind00leff|url-access=registration|date=2007|publisher=Hill and Wang}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Leuchtenberg|first1=William E.|title=The American President: From Teddy Roosevelt to Bill Clinton|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195176162}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Patterson|first1=James|title=Restless Giant: The United States from Watergate to Bush v. Gore|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195122169|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/restlessgiantuni00patt_0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Pemberton|first1=William E.|title=Exit with Honor: The Life and Presidency of Ronald Reagan|date=1997|publisher=Routledge}}\n* {{cite book|last= Reagan|first= Ronald|title= An American Life|year= 1990|publisher= Simon and Schuster|location= New York|isbn= 0-7434-0025-9|url= https://archive.org/details/americanlife00reag_0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rossinow|first1=Douglas C.|title=The Reagan Era: A History of the 1980s|date=2015|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231538657}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Weisberg|first1=Jacob|title=Ronald Reagan|date=2016|publisher=Times Books|isbn=978-0-8050-9728-3}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wilentz|first1=Sean|title=The Age of Reagan: A History, 1974-2008|date=2008|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-074480-9|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofreaganhisto00wile}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Main|Ronald Reagan bibliography}}\n\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Brownlee, W. Elliot and Hugh Davis Graham, eds. ''The Reagan Presidency: Pragmatic Conservatism and Its Legacies'' (2003)\n* Coleman, Bradley Lynn and Kyle Longley, eds. ''Reagan and the World: Leadership and National Security, 1981\u20131989'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2017), 319 pp.  essays by scholars\n* {{cite book |last= Diggins |first= John Patrick |title= Ronald Reagan: Fate, Freedom, and the Making of History |url= https://archive.org/details/ronaldreaganfate00digg |url-access= registration | year= 2007| publisher= W. W. Norton |location= New York|isbn= }}\n* Ehrman, John. ''The Eighties: America in the Age of Reagan.'' (2005)\n* Graff, Henry F., ed. ''The Presidents: A Reference History'' (3rd ed. 2002)\n* Hayward, Steven F. ''The Age of Reagan: The Conservative Counterrevolution, 1980\u20131989'' (2010), highly favorable\n* Hertsgaard, Mark. (1988) ''On Bended Knee: The Press and the Reagan Presidency''. New York, New York: Farrar Straus and Giroux.\n* Hill,  Dilys M. and Raymond A. Moore, eds. ''The Reagan Presidency'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 1990) essays by scholars; 252pp.\n* {{cite book |last= Matlock |first= Jack |title= Reagan and Gorbachev: How the Cold War Ended |year= 2004 |publisher= Random House |location= New York |isbn= 0-679-46323-2 |url= https://archive.org/details/reagangorbachevh00matl }}\n* {{cite book |last= Reeves |first= Richard |authorlink= Richard Reeves (American writer) |title= President Reagan: The Triumph of Imagination |year= 2005 |publisher= Simon & Schuster |location= New York |isbn= 0-7432-3022-1 |url= https://archive.org/details/presidentreagant00reev }}\n* Service, Robert. ''The End of the Cold War: 1985-1991'' (2015) [https://www.amazon.com/The-End-Cold-War-1985-1991/dp/1610394992/  excerpt]\n* {{cite book |last= Walsh |first= Kenneth |title= Ronald Reagan |year= 1997 |publisher= Random House Value Publishing, Inc. |location= New York |isbn= 0-517-20078-3 |url= https://archive.org/details/ronaldreagan00wals }}\n{{refend}}\n===Historiography===\n* Johns, Andrew L., ed. ''A Companion to Ronald Reagan'' (Wiley-Blackwell, 2015). xiv, 682 pp.; topical essays by scholars emphasizing historiography; [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/book/10.1002/9781118607770 contents free at many libraries]\n* Kengor, Paul. \"Reagan among the professors: His surprising reputation.\" ''Policy Review'' 98 (1999): 15+. Reports that \" many articles in the top journals have been fair, as have a number of influential books...from respected historians, presidential scholars, and political scientists -- people who were not Reagan supporters and are certainly not right-wingers.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.reaganlibrary.com/ Reagan Library]\n* [https://www.whitehouse.gov/1600/presidents/ronaldreagan Ronald Reagan biography on whitehouse.gov]\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/reagan-era/ Reagan Era] study guide, timeline, quotes, trivia, teacher resources\n\n{{Ronald Reagan}}\n{{US Presidential Administrations}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of Ronald Reagan| ]]\n[[Category:Presidencies of the United States|Reagan, Ronald]]\n[[Category:1980s in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1980\u201391)]]\n[[Category:Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1989 disestablishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 89-11 \u2192 89\u201311 (2), 1980's \u2192 1980s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidency_of_Ronald_Reagan"}
{"title_page": "Alan Wilder", "text_new": "{{for|the American actor|Alan Wilder (actor)}}\n{{short description|English musician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Alan Wilder\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = Alan Wilder.JPG\n|alt = Wilder standing behind a large electronic box\n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| landscape           = yes\n| caption             = Wilder in 2010\n| birth_name          = Alan Charles Wilder\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1959|06|01}}\n| birth_place         = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| death_date          =\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Synthpop]]|[[New wave music|new wave]]|[[electronic rock]]|[[electronica]]}} \n| occupation          = Musician, composer, arranger, record producer\n| instrument          = Synthesizer, sampler, keyboards, piano, drums, percussion, flute, oboe, guitar, bass guitar, vocals\n| years_active        = 1975\u2013present\n| label               = [[Mute Records]]<br>[[Reprise Records|Reprise]]/[[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[The Hitmen (British band)|The Hitmen]] (1981)<br>[[Depeche Mode]] (1982\u20131995)<br>[[Recoil (band)|Recoil]] (1986\u2013present)\n| website             = {{url|recoil.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Alan Charles Wilder''' (born 1 June 1959) is an [[English people|English]] musician, composer, arranger, record producer, and a former member of the [[electronica|electronic]] band [[Depeche Mode]] from 1982 to 1995. Since his departure from the band, the musical project called [[Recoil (band)|Recoil]] became his primary musical enterprise, which initially started as a side project to Depeche Mode in 1986. Wilder has also provided production and remixing services to the bands [[Nitzer Ebb]] and [[Curve (band)|Curve]].\nHe is a classically trained musician.<ref>Bell, Max: \"[http://www.tuug.org/~jaakko/dm/dmtekstit/privateaw.html ALAN WILDER: THE BAND BOY] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040505/http://www.tuug.org/~jaakko/dm/dmtekstit/privateaw.html |date=4 March 2016}}\", PRIVATE LIVES \u2013 THE DEPECHE MODE STORY, 1985</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAlan Charles Wilder was born into a [[middle class]] family and was raised in [[Acton, London|Acton]], [[West London (sub region)|West London]]. He began piano at the age of eight, through the encouragement of his parents. Later on, he learned the flute at [[St Clement Danes]] grammar school and became a leading musician in his school bands. After school, Alan worked as a studio assistant at DJM Studios. This led to him ending up working for bands such as The Dragons and Dafne & the Tenderspots (as Alan Normal). Others include Real to Real (featuring Adrian Chilvers on bass, Pete Fresh on guitar, Wolfgang Marlander on drums and Paul St. James on vocals), [[The Hitmen (British band)|The Hitmen]], and [[The Korgis]], appearing on the UK No.&nbsp;13 single \"If I Had You\" (1979).\n\n==1982\u20131995: Depeche Mode==\nFollowing the departure of [[Vince Clarke]], Depeche Mode placed an advertisement in the music magazine ''[[Melody Maker]]'': \"Keyboard player needed for established band \u2013 no timewasters.\" Even though the ad was looking for someone under 21 (Wilder was 22) he lied about his age to get the job, and got away with it. He joined Depeche Mode in January 1982, initially as a tour keyboardist, and soon thereafter as a full member of the recording band.\n\nWilder wrote a handful of songs for Depeche Mode, including \"Two Minute Warning\" and \"The Landscape Is Changing\" (and a B-side, \"Fools\") from the album ''[[Construction Time Again]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2223/depeche-mode.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20120917231957/http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2223/depeche-mode.html|url-status=dead|title=Depeche Mode &#124; Review &#124; Music @ The Digital Fix|archivedate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> and \"If You Want\" (and a B-side, \"In Your Memory\") from the album ''[[Some Great Reward]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2227/depeche-mode.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20120913005406/http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2227/depeche-mode.html|url-status=dead|title=Depeche Mode &#124; Review &#124; Music @ The Digital Fix|archivedate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> and finally co-wrote \"Black Day\" (and a B-side, \"Christmas Island\") from the album ''[[Black Celebration]]''.\nHowever, Wilder's more notable contributions to Depeche Mode were as a musician, arranger, and producer.\n\nIn addition to playing synthesizer throughout his time with Depeche Mode, Wilder also played piano on the band's signature ballad \"[[Blasphemous Rumours / Somebody|Somebody]],\" and oboe on the band's hit anthem, \"[[Everything Counts]].\" In the documentary film ''[[101 (album)|101]]'', Wilder demonstrates how different synthesizer parts of a song are split and arranged across a sampling keyboard for playing them live during the concert, just one small example of Wilder's ongoing contributions to Depeche Mode during his time as a member of the group. For the recording of the album ''[[Songs of Faith and Devotion]]'' and its corresponding [[Devotional Tour]], Wilder also played live drums.\n\nFor \"[[Enjoy the Silence]]\" from the album ''[[Violator (album)|Violator]]'', Wilder took Martin Gore's melancholy ballad-esque demo and re-envisioned the song as a percolating, melodic dance track.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.themusicfix.co.uk/content.php?contentid=2253 |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002243/http://www.themusicfix.co.uk/content.php?contentid=2253 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The resulting single went on to become one of the most commercially successful songs in Depeche Mode's history.\n\n===Departure===\nOn 26 June 1995, Wilder announced his departure from Depeche Mode:\n\n:\"Due to increasing dissatisfaction with the internal relations and working practices of the group, it is with some sadness that I have decided to part company from Depeche Mode. My decision to leave the group was not an easy one particularly as our last few albums were an indication of the full potential that Depeche Mode was realizing. Since joining in 1982, I have continually striven to give total energy, enthusiasm and commitment to the furthering of the group's success and in spite of a consistent imbalance in the distribution of the workload, willingly offered this. Unfortunately, within the group, this level of input never received the respect and acknowledgement that it warrants. Whilst I believe that the calibre of our musical output has improved, the quality of our association has deteriorated to the point where I no longer feel that the end justifies the means. I have no wish to cast aspersions on any individual; suffice to say that relations have become seriously strained, increasingly frustrating and, ultimately, in certain situations, intolerable. Given these circumstances, I have no option but to leave the group. It seems preferable therefore, to leave on a relative high, and as I still retain a great enthusiasm and passion for music, I am excited by the prospect of pursuing new projects. The remaining band members have my support and best wishes for anything they may pursue in the future, be it collectively or individually.\"\n\nAfter his split from Depeche Mode, Wilder was approached by [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] with an offer to join [[the Cure]]. Wilder respectfully declined.<ref>Miller, Jonathan: ''Stripped: Depeche Mode'', Omnibus Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-7119-9397-1}}.</ref>\nAccording to Wilder himself, the possibility was offered on behalf of the Cure by Daryl Bamonte (tour manager for both Depeche Mode and the Cure, and brother of the Cure member [[Perry Bamonte]]), and he declined as joining another band was the last thing on his mind.<ref>[http://www.recoil.co.uk/qa_vault/ge_other.html Shunt Q+A Vault: Other Artists \u2013 likes / dislikes / record collection] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100202181419/http://www.recoil.co.uk/qa_vault/ge_other.html |date=2 February 2010 }} Retrieved on 25 October 2009</ref>\n\nHe briefly reunited with Depeche Mode during the Teenage Cancer Trust concert at the Royal Albert Hall in London on 17 February 2010, and enjoyed a rapturous reception. During the encore, Wilder accompanied Martin Gore on piano for \"[[Blasphemous Rumours / Somebody|Somebody]]\". Gore returned the favour and played a DJ set on one of Recoil's Selected Events.\n\nIn 2011, Wilder provided two mixes for the Depeche Mode track \"In Chains\".\n\n==1986\u2013present: Recoil==\n===Side project===\nRecoil began in 1986 as a two-track experimental EP. Simply entitled ''[[1 + 2 (album)|1 + 2]]'', this collection of primitive demos caught the attention of [[Mute Records]] label boss [[Daniel Miller (music producer)|Daniel Miller]] and was inconspicuously released as a mini-album on 12\" vinyl. An album, ''[[Hydrology (album)|Hydrology]]'', soon followed in 1988 and both were eventually re-issued by Mute on CD as ''[[Hydrology (album)|Hydrology plus 1 + 2]]''. Wilder described the project at the time as \"an antidote to Depeche Mode; a way to alleviate the frustrations of always working within a pop format\".{{Cite quote|date=February 2009}}\n\nAlmost immediately, Wilder found himself back in the studio to record what would become the most successful Depeche Mode album to date, ''[[Violator (album)|Violator]]''. It wasn't until the band finally allowed themselves an extended break after the [[World Violation Tour]] that Alan could return to Recoil\u2014not, however, before agreeing to produce ''Ebbhead'', another album for label-mates [[Nitzer Ebb]].\n\nIt was during this time that he cemented a working relationship with lead singer Douglas McCarthy who would return the favour by singing on Recoil's next album, ''[[Bloodline (Recoil album)|Bloodline]]''. For the ''Bloodline'' LP, released in 1991, Wilder recruited guest vocalists for the first time, with further contributions from [[Toni Halliday]] and [[Moby]]. 'Bloodline' also marked the first Recoil single, a cover of [[Alex Harvey (musician)|Alex Harvey]]'s song 'Faith Healer' as well as 'Electro Blues For Bukka White', featuring the posthumously sampled voice of Blues-man White set into a post-modern context.\n\nBetween 1992\u201393 Wilder resumed his Depeche Mode duties as the band recorded the album ''[[Songs of Faith and Devotion]]''.  Depeche Mode embarked on their most adventurous tour to date, enduring a grueling fifteen months on the road. Although the group had reached the pinnacle of success, aspects of the lifestyle had taken their toll on everyone and things eventually came to a head. In June 1995, having spent fourteen years as an integral part of one of the most popular and influential bands the UK has ever produced, Alan Wilder made the decision to leave Depeche Mode.\n\n===Solo efforts===\nFree from his group commitments, Wilder could now focus solely on Recoil. In September 1996, he began work in his own studio, The Thin Line, gradually piecing together what would become Recoil's next album ''[[Unsound Methods]]''. Guest vocalists this time played a more up-front role than ever and featured [[Maggie Estep]], Siobhan Lynch, the reappearance of Douglas McCarthy, and Hildia Campbell.\n\nIn the spring of 2000, Recoil released ''[[Liquid (Recoil album)|Liquid]]'' which this time featured fellow Mute artist [[Diamanda Gal\u00e1s]], 1940s gospel crooners the [[Golden Gate Jubilee Quartet]], along with New York spoken-word performers [[Nicole Blackman]] and Samantha Coerbell.\n\nFollowing a five-year break from recording, Alan Wilder returned in 2007 with Recoil's fifth studio album, entitled ''[[SubHuman]]''.\n\n2010 saw the release of 'Selected', a selection of Recoil tracks chosen by Alan who explains: \"The collection is made up of my personal favourites, remastered and edited together into what I consider a cohesive and total listening experience.\u201d\n\nA tour entitled \u2018A Strange Hour\u2019 was presented during 2010 & 2011 in 52 cities across the world, as part of the \u2018Selected Events\u2019, which celebrated 25 years of the Recoil project. It signified the first time Recoil had ever taken to the road.  The events were not so much \u2018live\u2019 band but more art or video installation. Wilder gathered together filmmakers from as far as Russia, via the Czech Republic and Hungary, all the way to Argentina for this purpose, working very fast, and in the modern way, by creating a central server where everybody could upload their work for others to see, react to and feedback on.  Says Wilder: \u201cThis for me typifies the whole essence of what Recoil is all about \u2013 a collective but with a focused direction \u2013 and a very thrilling process it was too, watching and hearing \u2019A Strange Hour\u2019 come together from our base in the UK.\u201d\n\nRecoil returned in 2012 to release the concert film 'A Strange Hour In Budapest' on Blu-ray, with 5.1 surround sound, directed by Attila Herk\u00f3.\n\nAlso in 2012, we saw Alan Wilder turn up again as Executive Producer & contributor for a new tribute album to Mark Hollis & Talk Talk.  Recoil offered two cover versions for the album featuring the vocals of Linton Kwesi Johnson, Shara Worden and Paul Marshall.  Wilder also mixed a track for Richard Reed Parry from Arcade Fire. \u2018Spirit of Talk Talk\u2019 was released in September 2012 on Fierce Panda Records.\n\n==Discography==\n===Early work===\n* The Dragons \u2013 \"Misbehavin'\" (1977)\n* Dafne & The Tenderspots \u2013 \"Disco Hell\" (1979)\n* [[The Korgis]] \u2013 \"If I Had You\" (1979) UK No.&nbsp;13 (The track also appears on ''[[The Korgis (album)|The Korgis]]'', as well as all of the band's [[The Korgis#Compilations|compilation albums]].)\n* Real to Real \u2013 \"White Man Reggae\" (March 1980)\n* Real to Real \u2013 \"The Blue\" (1980)\n* Real to Real \u2013 ''Tightrope Walkers'' (November 1980)\n* Real to Real \u2013 \"Mr. and Mrs.\" (March 1981)\n* The Flatbackers  \u2013 \"Serenade of Love\" (1981)\n* The Hitmen  \u2013 \"Ouija\" (1981)\n\n===With Depeche Mode===\n{{Main|Depeche Mode discography}}\nWilder appeared on all of Depeche Mode's releases from \"[[Get the Balance Right!|Get the Balance Right]]\" (31 January 1983) up to \"[[In Your Room (Depeche Mode song)|In Your Room]]\" (10 January 1994), later taking part in reissues and compilations containing material from his time in the band.\n====Discography featuring Alan Wilder====\nStudio albums:\n* [[Construction Time Again]] (1983)\n* [[Some Great Reward]] (1984)\n* [[Black Celebration]] (1986)\n* [[Music for the Masses]] (1987)\n* [[Violator (album)|Violator]] (1990)\n* [[Songs of Faith and Devotion]] (1993)\n\nLive albums:\n* [[101 (album)|101]] (1989)\n* [[Songs of Faith and Devotion Live]] (1993)\n\nCompilations:\n* [[People Are People (album)|People Are People]] (1984) - all tracks, excepting: \"Now This Is Fun\" and \"[[Leave In Silence]]\".\n* [[The Singles 81\u219285]] (1985) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Dreaming of Me]]\", \"[[New Life (song)|New Life]]\", \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[See You (Depeche Mode song)|See You]]\", \"[[The Meaning of Love]]\" (only on the CD version) and \"[[Leave in Silence]]\"; also, he did not feature on both the bonus tracks on the 1998 reissue.\n* [[Catching Up with Depeche Mode]] (1985) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Dreaming of Me]]\", \"[[New Life (song)|New Life]]\", \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[See You (Depeche Mode song)|See You]]\" and \"[[The Meaning of Love]]\".\n* [[The Singles 86\u201398]] (1998) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\" and \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\".\n* [[Remixes 81\u201304]] (2004) - all tracks, excepting \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\" (Underworld Hard Mix) (one-disc edition), \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\" (The Kruder + Dorfmeister Session\u2122), \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\" (Air 'Around the Golf' Remix), \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\" (Schizo Mix) and \"[[Enjoy the Silence 04]]\"; all tracks, excepting: \"Shout!\" (Rio Remix), \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\" (Air 'Around the Golf' Remix), \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\" (Underworld Hard Mix), \"[[Freelove]]\" (DJ Muggs Remix), \"[[I Feel Loved]]\" (Chamber's Remix), \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\" (Schizo Mix) (two-disc edition), \"Painkiller\" (Kill the Pain DJ Shadow vs. Depeche Mode), \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\" (The Kruder + Dorfmeister Session\u2122), \"[[Dream On (Depeche Monde song)|Dream On]]\" (Dave Clarke Acoustic Version), \"[[It's No Good]]\" (Speedy J Mix) and \"Enjoy the Silence\" (Timo Maas Extended Mix); all tracks, excepting all the above and \"I Feel Loved\" (Danny Tenaglia's Labor of Love Dub (Edit)), \"It's No Good\" (Club 69 Future Mix), \"Photographic\" (Rex the Dog Dubb Mix).\n* [[The Best of Depeche Mode Volume 1]] (2006) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[See You (Depeche Mode song)|See You]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Suffer Well]]\", \"[[Dream On (Depeche Mode song)|Dream On]]\", \"[[Martyr (song)|Martyr]]\", \"[[Precious (Depeche Mode song)|Precious]]\" and \"[[New Life (song)|New Life]]\".\n* [[Remixes 2: 81\u201311]] (2011) - partial.\n\nSingles:\n* \"Get the Balance Right!\"\n* \"Everything Counts\"\n* \"Love, in Itself\"\n* \"People Are People\"\n* \"Master and Servant\"\n* \"Blasphemous Rumours\" / \"Somebody\"\n* \"Shake the Disease\"\n* \"It's Called a Heart\"\n* \"Stripped\"\n* \"A Question of Lust\"\n* \"A Question of Time\"\n* \"Strangelove\"\n* \"Never Let Me Down Again\"\n* \"Behind the Wheel\"\n* \"Little 15\"\n* \"Personal Jesus\"\n* \"Enjoy the Silence\"\n* \"Policy of Truth\"\n* \"World in My Eyes\"\n* \"I Feel You\"\n* \"Walking in My Shoes\"\n* \"Condemnation\"\n* \"In Your Room\"\n\nVideo albums:\n* [[The World We Live In and Live in Hamburg]] (1985)\n* [[Some Great Videos]] (1985) - all clips, except \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\"\n* [[Strange (video)|Strange]] (1988)\n* [[101 (album)|101]] (1989)\n* [[Strange Too]] (1990)\n* [[Devotional (video)|Devotional]] (1993)\n* [[The Videos 86\u201398]] (1998) - all clips, except: \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\", \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\", \"[[Only When I Lose Myself]]\" and \"[[Ultra (Depeche Mode album)|Ultra]] - Electronic Press Kit\".\n* [[The Best of Depeche Mode Volume 1]] (2006) - all clips, except: \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\", \"[[Only When I Lose Myself]]\", \"[[Dream On (Depeche Mode song)|Dream On]]\", \"[[I Feel Loved]]\", \"[[Enjoy the Silence 04]]\", \"[[Precious (Depeche Mode song)|Precious]]\" and \"[[Suffer Well]]\".\n* [[Video Singles Collection]] (2016) - all clips, except: \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\" and 33-55 clips\n\n===As Recoil===\n{{Main|Recoil (band)#Discography}}\n\n===Collected===\nWilder organized with Omega an auction selling a lot of DM collectable items on 3 September 2011 in Manchester. A DVD called \"Collected +\" was released as promotion for these events.\n\n===Covers and collaborations===\n*1991&nbsp;\u2013 Mixed the [[Nitzer Ebb]] song \"Come Alive\" from their [[As Is (Nitzer Ebb EP)|As Is]] EP.\n*1991&nbsp;\u2013 Along with [[Flood (producer)|Flood]], produced the [[Nitzer Ebb]] full album [[Ebbhead]].\n*2001&nbsp;\u2013 Provided strings and ambient sounds for the song \"Polaroid\" from the [[Curve (band)|Curve]] album \"[[Gift (Curve album)|Gift]]\".\n*2003&nbsp;\u2013 Provided strings and sounds for \"The Digital Intervention\" track called \"Coma Idyllique\" from their album \"Capture\".   ''PK'', a longtime [[Recoil (band)|Recoil]] collaborator is one of its members along with Olivia Louvel.\n*2012&nbsp;\u2013 Covered two tracks: \"Inheritance\" \u2013 Recoil (ft. Linton Kwesi Johnson & Paul Marshall) and \"Dum Dum Girl\" \u2013 Recoil (ft. Shara Worden) for a [[Talk Talk]] tribute album (double) cd/book set called''\"Spirit of Talk Talk''. He also became executive music producer for the album.\n*2016&nbsp;\u2013 Dede Featuring Alan Wilder \"Calling the Clock\" - Provided music and arrangements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recoil.co.uk/#!/dede-featuring-alan-wilder|title=SHUNT - The Official Recoil Website|website=Recoil.co.uk|accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Remixes===\n*1989 [[Toni Halliday]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"Time Turns Around\" (Euro-Tech Version)\n*1991 [[Nitzer Ebb]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"I Give to You\" (Wilder Mix Full Version)\n*2010 [[Nitzer Ebb]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"I Am Undone\" (Alan Wilder Remix)\n*2011 [[Depeche Mode]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"In Chains\" (Alan Wilder Remix)\n*2011 [[Sonoio]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"Minutes\" (Expansion Mix)\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.recoil.co.uk/ Shunt&nbsp;\u2013 The Official Recoil Website]\n* [http://store.recoil.co.uk/ Recoil Official Store]\n\n{{Depeche Mode}}\n{{Recoil}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilder, Alan}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:Depeche Mode members]]\n[[Category:English electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:English rock keyboardists]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Acton, London]]\n[[Category:People from Hammersmith]]\n[[Category:British synth-pop new wave musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American actor|Alan Wilder (actor)}}\n{{short description|English musician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Alan Wilder\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = Alan Wilder.JPG\n|alt = Wilder standing behind a large electronic box\n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| landscape           = yes\n| caption             = Wilder in 2010\n| birth_name          = Alan Charles Wilder\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1959|06|01}}\n| birth_place         = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| death_date          =\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Synthpop]]|[[New wave music|new wave]]|[[electronic rock]]|[[electronica]]}} \n| occupation          = Musician, composer, arranger, record producer\n| instrument          = Synthesizer, sampler, keyboards, piano, drums, percussion, flute, oboe, guitar, bass guitar, vocals\n| years_active        = 1975\u2013present\n| label               = [[Mute Records]]<br>[[Reprise Records|Reprise]]/[[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[The Hitmen (British band)|The Hitmen]] (1981)<br>[[Depeche Mode]] (1982\u20131995)<br>[[Recoil (band)|Recoil]] (1986\u2013present)\n| website             = {{url|recoil.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Alan Charles Wilder''' (born 1 June 1959) is an [[English people|English]] musician, composer, arranger, record producer, and a former member of the [[electronica|electronic]] band [[Depeche Mode]] from 1982 to 1995. Since his departure from the band, the musical project called [[Recoil (band)|Recoil]] became his primary musical enterprise, which initially started as a side project to Depeche Mode in 1986. Wilder has also provided production and remixing services to the bands [[Nitzer Ebb]] and [[Curve (band)|Curve]].\nHe is a classically trained musician.<ref>Bell, Max: \"[http://www.tuug.org/~jaakko/dm/dmtekstit/privateaw.html ALAN WILDER: THE BAND BOY] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040505/http://www.tuug.org/~jaakko/dm/dmtekstit/privateaw.html |date=4 March 2016}}\", PRIVATE LIVES \u2013 THE DEPECHE MODE STORY, 1985</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAlan Charles Wilder was born into a [[middle class]] family and was raised in [[Acton, London|Acton]], [[West London (sub region)|West London]]. He began piano at the age of eight, through the encouragement of his parents. Later on, he learned the flute at [[St Clement Danes]] grammar school and became a leading musician in his school bands. After school, Alan worked as a studio assistant at DJM Studios. This led to him ending up working for bands such as The Dragons and Dafne & the Tenderspots (as Alan Normal). Others include Real to Real (featuring Adrian Chilvers on bass, Pete Fresh on guitar, Wolfgang Marlander on drums and Paul St. James on vocals), [[The Hitmen (British band)|The Hitmen]], and [[The Korgis]], appearing on the UK No.&nbsp;13 single \"If I Had You\" (1979).\n\n==1982\u20131995: Depeche Mode==\nFollowing the departure of [[Vince Clarke]], Depeche Mode placed an advertisement in the music magazine ''[[Melody Maker]]'': \"Keyboard player needed for established band \u2013 no timewasters.\" Even though the ad was looking for someone under 21 (Wilder was 22) he lied about his age to get the job, and got away with it. He joined Depeche Mode in January 1982, initially as a tour keyboardist, and soon thereafter as a full member of the recording band.\n\nWilder wrote a handful of songs for Depeche Mode, including \"Two Minute Warning\" and \"The Landscape Is Changing\" (and a B-side, \"Fools\") from the album ''[[Construction Time Again]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2223/depeche-mode.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20120917231957/http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2223/depeche-mode.html|url-status=dead|title=Depeche Mode &#124; Review &#124; Music @ The Digital Fix|archivedate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> and \"If You Want\" (and a B-side, \"In Your Memory\") from the album ''[[Some Great Reward]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2227/depeche-mode.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20120913005406/http://music.thedigitalfix.com/content/review/2227/depeche-mode.html|url-status=dead|title=Depeche Mode &#124; Review &#124; Music @ The Digital Fix|archivedate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> and finally co-wrote \"Black Day\" (and a B-side, \"Christmas Island\") from the album ''[[Black Celebration]]''.\nHowever, Wilder's more notable contributions to Depeche Mode were as a musician, arranger, and producer.\n\nIn addition to playing synthesizer throughout his time with Depeche Mode, Wilder also played piano on the band's signature ballad \"[[Blasphemous Rumours / Somebody|Somebody]],\" and oboe on the band's hit anthem, \"[[Everything Counts]].\" In the documentary film ''[[101 (album)|101]]'', Wilder demonstrates how different synthesizer parts of a song are split and arranged across a sampling keyboard for playing them live during the concert, just one small example of Wilder's ongoing contributions to Depeche Mode during his time as a member of the group. For the recording of the album ''[[Songs of Faith and Devotion]]'' and its corresponding [[Devotional Tour]], Wilder also played live drums.\n\nFor \"[[Enjoy the Silence]]\" from the album ''[[Violator (album)|Violator]]'', Wilder took Martin Gore's melancholy ballad-esque demo and re-envisioned the song as a percolating, melodic dance track.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.themusicfix.co.uk/content.php?contentid=2253 |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002243/http://www.themusicfix.co.uk/content.php?contentid=2253 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The resulting single went on to become one of the most commercially successful songs in Depeche Mode's history.\n\n===Departure===\nOn 26 June 1995, Wilder announced his departure from Depeche Mode:\n\n:\"Due to increasing dissatisfaction with the internal relations and working practices of the group, it is with some sadness that I have decided to part company from Depeche Mode. My decision to leave the group was not an easy one particularly as our last few albums were an indication of the full potential that Depeche Mode was realizing. Since joining in 1982, I have continually striven to give total energy, enthusiasm and commitment to the furthering of the group's success and in spite of a consistent imbalance in the distribution of the workload, willingly offered this. Unfortunately, within the group, this level of input never received the respect and acknowledgement that it warrants. Whilst I believe that the calibre of our musical output has improved, the quality of our association has deteriorated to the point where I no longer feel that the end justifies the means. I have no wish to cast aspersions on any individual; suffice to say that relations have become seriously strained, increasingly frustrating and, ultimately, in certain situations, intolerable. Given these circumstances, I have no option but to leave the group. It seems preferable therefore, to leave on a relative high, and as I still retain a great enthusiasm and passion for music, I am excited by the prospect of pursuing new projects. The remaining band members have my support and best wishes for anything they may pursue in the future, be it collectively or individually.\"\n\nAfter his split from Depeche Mode, Wilder was approached by [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] with an offer to join [[the Cure]]. Wilder respectfully declined.<ref>Miller, Jonathan: ''Stripped: Depeche Mode'', Omnibus Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-7119-9397-1}}.</ref>\nAccording to Wilder himself, the possibility was offered on behalf of the Cure by Daryl Bamonte (tour manager for both Depeche Mode and the Cure, and brother of the Cure member [[Perry Bamonte]]), and he declined as joining another band was the last thing on his mind.<ref>[http://www.recoil.co.uk/qa_vault/ge_other.html Shunt Q+A Vault: Other Artists \u2013 likes / dislikes / record collection] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100202181419/http://www.recoil.co.uk/qa_vault/ge_other.html |date=2 February 2010 }} Retrieved on 25 October 2009</ref>\n\nHe briefly reunited with Depeche Mode during the Teenage Cancer Trust concert at the Royal Albert Hall in London on 17 February 2010, and enjoyed a rapturous reception. During the encore, Wilder accompanied Martin Gore on piano for \"[[Blasphemous Rumours / Somebody|Somebody]]\". Gore returned the favour and played a DJ set on one of Recoil's Selected Events.\n\nIn 2011, Wilder provided two mixes for the Depeche Mode track \"In Chains\".\n\n==1986\u2013present: Recoil==\n===Side project===\nRecoil began in 1986 as a two-track experimental EP. Simply entitled ''[[1 + 2 (album)|1 + 2]]'', this collection of primitive demos caught the attention of [[Mute Records]] label boss [[Daniel Miller (music producer)|Daniel Miller]] and was inconspicuously released as a mini-album on 12\" vinyl. An album, ''[[Hydrology (album)|Hydrology]]'', soon followed in 1988 and both were eventually re-issued by Mute on CD as ''[[Hydrology (album)|Hydrology plus 1 + 2]]''. Wilder described the project at the time as \"an antidote to Depeche Mode; a way to alleviate the frustrations of always working within a pop format\".{{Cite quote|date=February 2009}}\n\nAlmost immediately, Wilder found himself back in the studio to record what would become the most successful Depeche Mode album to date, ''[[Violator (album)|Violator]]''. It wasn't until the band finally allowed themselves an extended break after the [[World Violation Tour]] that Alan could return to Recoil\u2014not, however, before agreeing to produce ''Ebbhead'', another album for label-mates [[Nitzer Ebb]].\n\nIt was during this time that he cemented a working relationship with lead singer Douglas McCarthy who would return the favour by singing on Recoil's next album, ''[[Bloodline (Recoil album)|Bloodline]]''. For the ''Bloodline'' LP, released in 1991, Wilder recruited guest vocalists for the first time, with further contributions from [[Toni Halliday]] and [[Moby]]. 'Bloodline' also marked the first Recoil single, a cover of [[Alex Harvey (musician)|Alex Harvey]]'s song 'Faith Healer' as well as 'Electro Blues For Bukka White', featuring the posthumously sampled voice of Blues-man White set into a post-modern context.\n\nBetween 1992\u201393 Wilder resumed his Depeche Mode duties as the band recorded the album ''[[Songs of Faith and Devotion]]''.  Depeche Mode embarked on their most adventurous tour to date, enduring a grueling fifteen months on the road. Although the group had reached the pinnacle of success, aspects of the lifestyle had taken their toll on everyone and things eventually came to a head. In June 1995, having spent fourteen years as an integral part of one of the most popular and influential bands the UK has ever produced, Alan Wilder made the decision to leave Depeche Mode.\n\n===Solo efforts===\nFree from his group commitments, Wilder could now focus solely on Recoil. In September 1996, he began work in his own studio, The Thin Line, gradually piecing together what would become Recoil's next album ''[[Unsound Methods]]''. Guest vocalists this time played a more up-front role than ever and featured [[Maggie Estep]], Siobhan Lynch, the reappearance of Douglas McCarthy, and Hildia Campbell.\n\nIn the spring of 2000, Recoil released ''[[Liquid (Recoil album)|Liquid]]'' which this time featured fellow Mute artist [[Diamanda Gal\u00e1s]], 1940s gospel crooners the [[Golden Gate Jubilee Quartet]], along with New York spoken-word performers [[Nicole Blackman]] and Samantha Coerbell.\n\nFollowing a five-year break from recording, Alan Wilder returned in 2007 with Recoil's fifth studio album, entitled ''[[SubHuman]]''.\n\n2010 saw the release of 'Selected', a selection of Recoil tracks chosen by Alan who explains: \"The collection is made up of my personal favourites, remastered and edited together into what I consider a cohesive and total listening experience.\u201d\n\nA tour entitled \u2018A Strange Hour\u2019 was presented during 2010 & 2011 in 52 cities across the world, as part of the \u2018Selected Events\u2019, which celebrated 25 years of the Recoil project. It signified the first time Recoil had ever taken to the road.  The events were not so much \u2018live\u2019 band but more art or video installation. Wilder gathered together filmmakers from as far as Russia, via the Czech Republic and Hungary, all the way to Argentina for this purpose, working very fast, and in the modern way, by creating a central server where everybody could upload their work for others to see, react to and feedback on.  Says Wilder: \u201cThis for me typifies the whole essence of what Recoil is all about \u2013 a collective but with a focused direction \u2013 and a very thrilling process it was too, watching and hearing \u2019A Strange Hour\u2019 come together from our base in the UK.\u201d\n\nRecoil returned in 2012 to release the concert film 'A Strange Hour In Budapest' on Blu-ray, with 5.1 surround sound, directed by Attila Herk\u00f3.\n\nAlso in 2012, we saw Alan Wilder turn up again as Executive Producer & contributor for a new tribute album to Mark Hollis & Talk Talk.  Recoil offered two cover versions for the album featuring the vocals of Linton Kwesi Johnson, Shara Worden and Paul Marshall.  Wilder also mixed a track for Richard Reed Parry from Arcade Fire. \u2018Spirit of Talk Talk\u2019 was released in September 2012 on Fierce Panda Records.\n\n==Discography==\n===Early work===\n* The Dragons \u2013 \"Misbehavin'\" (1977)\n* Dafne & The Tenderspots \u2013 \"Disco Hell\" (1979)\n* [[The Korgis]] \u2013 \"If I Had You\" (1979) UK No.&nbsp;13 (The track also appears on ''[[The Korgis (album)|The Korgis]]'', as well as all of the band's [[The Korgis#Compilations|compilation albums]].)\n* Real to Real \u2013 \"White Man Reggae\" (March 1980)\n* Real to Real \u2013 \"The Blue\" (1980)\n* Real to Real \u2013 ''Tightrope Walkers'' (November 1980)\n* Real to Real \u2013 \"Mr. and Mrs.\" (March 1981)\n* The Flatbackers  \u2013 \"Serenade of Love\" (1981)\n* The Hitmen  \u2013 \"Ouija\" (1981)\n\n===With Depeche Mode===\n{{Main|Depeche Mode discography}}\nWilder appeared on all of Depeche Mode's releases from \"[[Get the Balance Right!|Get the Balance Right]]\" (31 January 1983) up to \"[[In Your Room (Depeche Mode song)|In Your Room]]\" (10 January 1994), later taking part in reissues and compilations containing material from his time in the band.\n==Discography featuring Alan Wilder==\nStudio albums:\n* [[Construction Time Again]] (1983)\n* [[Some Great Reward]] (1984)\n* [[Black Celebration]] (1986)\n* [[Music for the Masses]] (1987)\n* [[Violator (album)|Violator]] (1990)\n* [[Songs of Faith and Devotion]] (1993)\n\nLive albums:\n* [[101 (album)|101]] (1989)\n* [[Songs of Faith and Devotion Live]] (1993)\n\nCompilations:\n* [[People Are People (album)|People Are People]] (1984) - all tracks, excepting: \"Now This Is Fun\" and \"[[Leave In Silence]]\".\n* [[The Singles 81\u219285]] (1985) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Dreaming of Me]]\", \"[[New Life (song)|New Life]]\", \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[See You (Depeche Mode song)|See You]]\", \"[[The Meaning of Love]]\" (only on the CD version) and \"[[Leave in Silence]]\"; also, he did not feature on both the bonus tracks on the 1998 reissue.\n* [[Catching Up with Depeche Mode]] (1985) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Dreaming of Me]]\", \"[[New Life (song)|New Life]]\", \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[See You (Depeche Mode song)|See You]]\" and \"[[The Meaning of Love]]\".\n* [[The Singles 86\u201398]] (1998) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\" and \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\".\n* [[Remixes 81\u201304]] (2004) - all tracks, excepting \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\" (Underworld Hard Mix) (one-disc edition), \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\" (The Kruder + Dorfmeister Session\u2122), \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\" (Air 'Around the Golf' Remix), \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\" (Schizo Mix) and \"[[Enjoy the Silence 04]]\"; all tracks, excepting: \"Shout!\" (Rio Remix), \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\" (Air 'Around the Golf' Remix), \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\" (Underworld Hard Mix), \"[[Freelove]]\" (DJ Muggs Remix), \"[[I Feel Loved]]\" (Chamber's Remix), \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\" (Schizo Mix) (two-disc edition), \"Painkiller\" (Kill the Pain DJ Shadow vs. Depeche Mode), \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\" (The Kruder + Dorfmeister Session\u2122), \"[[Dream On (Depeche Monde song)|Dream On]]\" (Dave Clarke Acoustic Version), \"[[It's No Good]]\" (Speedy J Mix) and \"Enjoy the Silence\" (Timo Maas Extended Mix); all tracks, excepting all the above and \"I Feel Loved\" (Danny Tenaglia's Labor of Love Dub (Edit)), \"It's No Good\" (Club 69 Future Mix), \"Photographic\" (Rex the Dog Dubb Mix).\n* [[The Best of Depeche Mode Volume 1]] (2006) - all tracks, excepting: \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[See You (Depeche Mode song)|See You]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Suffer Well]]\", \"[[Dream On (Depeche Mode song)|Dream On]]\", \"[[Martyr (song)|Martyr]]\", \"[[Precious (Depeche Mode song)|Precious]]\" and \"[[New Life (song)|New Life]]\".\n* [[Remixes 2: 81\u201311]] (2011) - partial.\n\nSingles:\n* \"Get the Balance Right!\"\n* \"Everything Counts\"\n* \"Love, in Itself\"\n* \"People Are People\"\n* \"Master and Servant\"\n* \"Blasphemous Rumours\" / \"Somebody\"\n* \"Shake the Disease\"\n* \"It's Called a Heart\"\n* \"Stripped\"\n* \"A Question of Lust\"\n* \"A Question of Time\"\n* \"Strangelove\"\n* \"Never Let Me Down Again\"\n* \"Behind the Wheel\"\n* \"Little 15\"\n* \"Personal Jesus\"\n* \"Enjoy the Silence\"\n* \"Policy of Truth\"\n* \"World in My Eyes\"\n* \"I Feel You\"\n* \"Walking in My Shoes\"\n* \"Condemnation\"\n* \"In Your Room\"\n\nVideo albums:\n* [[The World We Live In and Live in Hamburg]] (1985)\n* [[Some Great Videos]] (1985) - all clips, except \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\"\n* [[Strange (video)|Strange]] (1988)\n* [[101 (album)|101]] (1989)\n* [[Strange Too]] (1990)\n* [[Devotional (video)|Devotional]] (1993)\n* [[The Videos 86\u201398]] (1998) - all clips, except: \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\", \"[[Useless (song)|Useless]]\", \"[[Only When I Lose Myself]]\" and \"[[Ultra (Depeche Mode album)|Ultra]] - Electronic Press Kit\".\n* [[The Best of Depeche Mode Volume 1]] (2006) - all clips, except: \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\", \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\", \"[[It's No Good]]\", \"[[Home (Depeche Mode song)|Home]]\", \"[[Only When I Lose Myself]]\", \"[[Dream On (Depeche Mode song)|Dream On]]\", \"[[I Feel Loved]]\", \"[[Enjoy the Silence 04]]\", \"[[Precious (Depeche Mode song)|Precious]]\" and \"[[Suffer Well]]\".\n* [[Video Singles Collection]] (2016) - all clips, except: \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (Depeche Mode song)|Just Can't Get Enough]]\" and 33-55 clips\n\n===As Recoil===\n{{Main|Recoil (band)#Discography}}\n\n===Collected===\nWilder organized with Omega an auction selling a lot of DM collectable items on 3 September 2011 in Manchester. A DVD called \"Collected +\" was released as promotion for these events.\n\n===Covers and collaborations===\n*1991&nbsp;\u2013 Mixed the [[Nitzer Ebb]] song \"Come Alive\" from their [[As Is (Nitzer Ebb EP)|As Is]] EP.\n*1991&nbsp;\u2013 Along with [[Flood (producer)|Flood]], produced the [[Nitzer Ebb]] full album [[Ebbhead]].\n*2001&nbsp;\u2013 Provided strings and ambient sounds for the song \"Polaroid\" from the [[Curve (band)|Curve]] album \"[[Gift (Curve album)|Gift]]\".\n*2003&nbsp;\u2013 Provided strings and sounds for \"The Digital Intervention\" track called \"Coma Idyllique\" from their album \"Capture\".   ''PK'', a longtime [[Recoil (band)|Recoil]] collaborator is one of its members along with Olivia Louvel.\n*2012&nbsp;\u2013 Covered two tracks: \"Inheritance\" \u2013 Recoil (ft. Linton Kwesi Johnson & Paul Marshall) and \"Dum Dum Girl\" \u2013 Recoil (ft. Shara Worden) for a [[Talk Talk]] tribute album (double) cd/book set called''\"Spirit of Talk Talk''. He also became executive music producer for the album.\n*2016&nbsp;\u2013 Dede Featuring Alan Wilder \"Calling the Clock\" - Provided music and arrangements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recoil.co.uk/#!/dede-featuring-alan-wilder|title=SHUNT - The Official Recoil Website|website=Recoil.co.uk|accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Remixes===\n*1989 [[Toni Halliday]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"Time Turns Around\" (Euro-Tech Version)\n*1991 [[Nitzer Ebb]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"I Give to You\" (Wilder Mix Full Version)\n*2010 [[Nitzer Ebb]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"I Am Undone\" (Alan Wilder Remix)\n*2011 [[Depeche Mode]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"In Chains\" (Alan Wilder Remix)\n*2011 [[Sonoio]]&nbsp;\u2013 \"Minutes\" (Expansion Mix)\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.recoil.co.uk/ Shunt&nbsp;\u2013 The Official Recoil Website]\n* [http://store.recoil.co.uk/ Recoil Official Store]\n\n{{Depeche Mode}}\n{{Recoil}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilder, Alan}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:Depeche Mode members]]\n[[Category:English electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:English rock keyboardists]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Acton, London]]\n[[Category:People from Hammersmith]]\n[[Category:British synth-pop new wave musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Wekahash", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiscography featuring Alan Wilder", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Wilder"}
{"title_page": "Cambridge Analytica", "text_new": "{{short description|2013\u20132018 British political consulting firm}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Cambridge Analytica Ltd\n| logo = Cambridge Analytica logo.svg\n| logo_size = 125px\n| type = Subsidiary\n| location = London, UK\n| foundation = 2013\n| defunct = 1 May 2018\n| successor = [[Emerdata]]\n| key_people = [[Alexander Nix]] (CEO)<ref name=Sky2016>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/behind-the-scenes-at-donald-trumps-uk-digital-war-room-10626155 |title=Behind the scenes at Donald Trump's UK digital war room |last1=Cheshire |first1=Tom |date=21 October 2016 |publisher=[[Sky News]]}}</ref><br/>[[Robert Mercer (businessman)|Robert Mercer]] (investor)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cadwalladr |first1=Carole |title='I made Steve Bannon's psychological warfare tool': meet the data war whistleblower |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/data-war-whistleblower-christopher-wylie-faceook-nix-bannon-trump |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=18 March 2018 |date=18 March 2018 }}</ref><br/>[[Rebekah Mercer]] (investor)<br/>[[Steve Bannon]] (vice president, former)<ref>{{cite web |last=Illing |first=Sean |title=Cambridge Analytica, the shady data firm that might be a key Trump-Russia link, explained |website=Vox |date=16 October 2017 |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/10/16/15657512/cambridge-analytica-christopher-wylie-facebook-trump-russia | access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n| parent = [[SCL Group]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica LLC: Private Company Information |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=434877108 |website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Cambridge Analytica Ltd''' ('''CA''') was a British [[political consulting]] firm that combined [[misappropriation]] of [[digital assets]], [[data mining]], [[data broker]]age and [[data analysis]] with [[strategic communication]] during the electoral processes.<ref>{{cite web |last=Editorial |first=Reuters |title=Factbox: Who is Cambridge Analytica and what did it do? |website=U.S. |date=20 March 2018 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-cambridge-analytica-factbox/factbox-who-is-cambridge-analytica-and-what-did-it-do-idUSKBN1GW07F | access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Exposed: Undercover secrets of Trump's data firm |website=Channel 4 News |date=20 March 2018 |url=https://www.channel4.com/news/exposed-undercover-secrets-of-donald-trump-data-firm-cambridge-analytica | access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref> It was started in 2013<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OHm5yAEACAAJ&dq=Cambridge+Analytica.+Il+potere+segreto,+la+gestione+del+consenso+e+la+fine+della+propaganda.|title=Cambridge Analytica. Il potere segreto, la gestione del consenso e la fine della propaganda.|last=Tirino|first=Nazzareno|publisher=Libellula Edizioni|year=2019|isbn=9788867355129|location=Lecce - Italy|pages=109|language=Italian|trans-title=Cambridge Analytica. The secret power to manage consensus to the end of propaganda.}}</ref> as an offshoot of the [[SCL Group]]. After closing operations with legal proceedings including bankruptcy, members of the SCL Group have been continuing operations under the legal entity [[Emerdata]] Limited.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90381366/the-mysterious-afterlife-of-cambridge-analytica-and-its-trove-of-data|title=The strange afterlife of Cambridge Analytica and the mysterious fate of its data|date=26 July 2018|work=Fast Company|access-date=16 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=issenberg/> The company closed operations in 2018 in the course of the [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal]], although related firms still exist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44807093|title=Cambridge Analytica staff set up new firm|date=12 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=24 December 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe company was partly owned by the family of [[Robert Mercer]], an American [[hedge-fund]] manager who supports many politically conservative causes.<ref name=\"issenberg\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/features/2015-11-12/is-the-republican-party-s-killer-data-app-for-real- |first=Sasha |last=Issenberg |authorlink=Sasha Issenberg |title=Cruz-Connected Data Miner Aims to Get Inside U.S. Voters' Heads |publisher=Bloomberg |date=12 November 2015 |accessdate=2 February 2016 }}</ref><ref name=politico/> The firm maintained offices in London, New York City, and Washington, DC.<ref name=ca/> CEO [[Alexander Nix]] has said CA was involved in 44 US political races in 2014.<ref name=wpost/> In 2015, CA performed data analysis services for [[Ted Cruz's presidential campaign]].<ref name=politico/> In 2016, CA worked for [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's presidential campaign]]<ref>{{cite journal |date=10 October 2016 |title=Silent Partners |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |page=44 |author=Alex Altman}}</ref> as well as for [[Leave.EU]] (one of the organisations campaigning in the United Kingdom's [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on European Union membership]]). CA's role in those campaigns has been controversial and is the subject of ongoing criminal investigations in both countries.<ref name=\"Confessore\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/us/politics/cambridge-analytica.html |title=Data Firm Says 'Secret Sauce' Aided Trump; Many Scoff |last=Confessore |first=Nicholas |date=6 March 2017 |work=The New York Times|access-date=7 March 2017 |last2=Hakim |first2=Danny |issn=0362-4331 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/donald-trump-und-die-daten-ingenieure-endlich-eine-erklaerung-mit-der-alles-sinn-ergibt-a-1124439.html |title=Ich ganz allein habe Trump ins Amt gebracht |last2=Schnack |first2=Thies |date=6 December 2016 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |last1=Reinbold |first1=Fabian }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/mar/04/cambridge-analytics-data-brexit-trump |title=Watchdog to launch inquiry into misuse of data in politics |last=Doward |first=Jamie |date=4 March 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=14 June 2017 |last2=Cadwalladr |first2=Carole |issn=0261-3077 |last3=Gibbs |first3=Alice }}</ref> Political scientists question CA's claims about the effectiveness of its methods of targeting voters.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2018/03/23/four-and-a-half-reasons-not-to-worry-that-cambridge-analytica-skewed-the-2016-election/ |title=Analysis {{!}} Four and a half reasons not to worry that Cambridge Analytica skewed the 2016 election|last=Trump|first=Kris-Stella|date=23 March 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=23 March 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, multiple media outlets broke news of Cambridge Analytica's business practices. ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Observer]]'' reported that the company had [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data breach|acquired and used personal data about Facebook users]] from an external researcher who had told [[Facebook]] he was collecting it for academic purposes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions|last=Rosenberg|first=Matthew|date=17 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=4 March 2019|last2=Confessore|first2=Nicholas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cadwalladr|first3=Carole}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' aired undercover investigative videos showing Nix boasting about using prostitutes, bribery [[sting operation]]s, and [[honey trapping|honey traps]] to discredit politicians on whom it conducted [[opposition research]], and saying that the company \"ran all of (Donald Trump's) digital campaign\". In response to the media reports, the [[Information Commissioner's Office]] (ICO) of the UK pursued a [[warrant (law)|warrant]] to search the company's servers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/92390/cambridge-analytica-ceo-admits-to-dirty-tricks |title=Cambridge Analytica CEO 'admits to dirty tricks' |work=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-20/cambridge-analytica-used-disappearing-emails-in-campaign-report |title=Cambridge Analytica Boasted of Disappearing Emails in Campaigns |date=20 March 2018 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref> Facebook banned Cambridge Analytica from advertising on its platform, saying that it had been deceived.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html |title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions |last=Rosenberg |first=Matthew |date=17 March 2018 |work=The New York Times|access-date=17 March 2018 |last2=Confessore |first2=Nicholas |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Cadwalladr |first3=Carole }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election |title=Revealed: 50 million Facebook profiles harvested for Cambridge Analytica in major data breach |date=17 March 2018 |accessdate=18 March 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |first1=Carole |last1=Cadwalladr |first2=Emma |last2=Graham-Harrison }}</ref> On 23 March 2018, the [[High Court of Justice|British High Court]] granted the ICO a warrant to search Cambridge Analytica's London offices.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/23/uk-high-court-grants-cambridge-analytica-search-warrant-to-ico.html |title=UK High Court grants Cambridge Analytica search warrant to ICO |last=CNBC |date=23 March 2018 |work=CNBC|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe personal data of up to 87 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/04/technology/mark-zuckerberg-testify-congress.html |title=\"Facebook Says Cambridge Analytica Harvested Data of Up to 87 Million Users\" in ''The New York Times'' |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref> Facebook users were acquired via the 270,000 Facebook users who used a Facebook app called \"This Is Your Digital Life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/apr/10/facebook-notify-users-data-harvested-cambridge-analytica|title=How to check whether Facebook shared your data with Cambridge Analytica|first=Alex|last=Hern|date=10 April 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> By giving this third-party app permission to acquire their data, back in 2015, this also gave the app access to information on the user's friends network; this resulted in the data of about 87&nbsp;million users, the majority of whom had not explicitly given Cambridge Analytica permission to access their data, being collected. The app developer breached Facebook's [[terms of service]] by giving the data to Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.recode.net/2018/3/17/17134072/facebook-cambridge-analytica-trump-explained-user-data |title=Here's how Facebook allowed Cambridge Analytica to get data for 50 million users |work=Recode|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2018, Cambridge Analytica and its parent company filed for [[insolvency|insolvency proceedings]] and closed operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/05/02/cambridge-analytica-is-shutting-down-following-facebook-scandal/ |title=Cambridge Analytica is shutting down following Facebook scandal |last=Lumb |first=David |date=2 May 2018 |work=[[Engadget]] |access-date=2 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica and Scl Elections Commence Insolvency Proceedings and Release Results of Independent Investigation into Recent Allegations |url=https://ca-commercial.com/news/cambridge-analytica-and-scl-elections-commence-insolvency-proceedings-and-release-results-3 |website=CA Commercial |publisher=Cambridge Analytica |accessdate=2 May 2018 |language=en |date=2 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502183542/https://ca-commercial.com/news/cambridge-analytica-and-scl-elections-commence-insolvency-proceedings-and-release-results-3 |archive-date=2 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Alexander Tayler, a former director for Cambridge Analytica, was appointed director of [[Emerdata]] on 28 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nichols|first1=Shaun|title=Cambridge Analytica dismantled for good? Nope: It just changed its name to Emerdata|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/05/02/cambridge_analytica_shutdown/|accessdate=2 May 2018|publisher=The Register|date=2 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Rebekah Mercer]], [[Jennifer Mercer]], [[Alexander Nix]] and {{ill|Johnson Chun Shun Ko|zh|\u9ad8\u632f\u9806}}, who has links to American businessman [[Erik Prince]], are in leadership positions at Emerdata.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/cambridge-analytica-executives-and-mercer-family-launch-emerdata-2018-3|title=The power players behind Cambridge Analytica have set up a mysterious new data company|last=Ghosh|first=Shona|date=2018-03-21|website=Business Insider Australia|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/05514098/officers|title=SCL GROUP LIMITED - Officers (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCambridge Analytica (SCL USA) was incorporated in January 2015 with its registered office in Westferry Circus, London and just one staff member, its director and CEO Alexander James Ashburner Nix (also appointed in January 2015).<ref>{{cite web |title=Filing record for Cambridge Analytica (UK) Limited \u2013 Company number 09375920 |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09375920 |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |publisher=Companies house, UK |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> Nix is also the director of nine similar companies sharing the same registered offices in London, including Firecrest technologies, [[Emerdata]] and six SCL Group companies including \"SCL elections limited\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexander James Ashburner NIX \u2013 Appoinments |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/YEplkqBMfc6Rp3dbPs57pN3aqO4/appointments |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |publisher=Companies house, UK Government |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> [[Nigel Oakes]] founded [[SCL Group]], which is the parent company of Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/old-etonian-smoothie-fails-to-buff-indonesian-leaders-image-711373.html |title=Old Etonian smoothie fails to buff Indonesian leader's image |author= |date=6 August 2000 |website=independent.co.uk |accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nPublicly, SCL Group called itself a \"global election management agency\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scl.cc/ |title=SCL Group \u2013 Home |website=scl.cc |access-date=9 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208184806/http://scl.cc/ |archive-date=8 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Politico'' reported it was known for involvement \"in [[military deception|military disinformation]] campaigns to social media branding and [[voter]] targeting\".<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/ted-cruz-donor-for-data-119813 |first=Kenneth P.|last=Vogel |authorlink=Kenneth P. Vogel |title=Cruz partners with donor's 'psychographic' firm |publisher=[[Politico]] |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=27 December 2015 }}</ref> SCL's involvement in the political world has been primarily in the developing world where it has been used by the military and politicians to study and manipulate public opinion and political will. ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' writer Sharon Weinberger compared one of SCL's hypothetical test scenarios to fomenting a coup.<ref name=politico/>\n\nCambridge Analytica was founded by conservative businessmen [[Steve Bannon]] and Robert Mercer. A minimum of 15 million dollars has been invested into the company by Mercer, according to ''The New York Times''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/us/cambridge-analytica-alexander-nix.html |first=Matthew |last=Rosenberg |title=Cambridge Analytica, Trump-Tied Political Firm, Offered to Entrap Politicians |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2018 }}</ref> Bannon's stake in the company was estimated at 1 to 5 million dollars, but he divested his holdings in April 2017 as required by his role as [[White House Chief Strategist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article200917134.html |first1=Ben |last1=Wieder |first2=Anita |last2=Kumar |title=Bannon sold Cambridge Analytica stake, fined for late ethics report |work=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]] |date=20 February 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> In March 2018, Jennifer Mercer and [[Rebekah Mercer]] became directors of Emerdata limited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Appoinment as directors |date=16 March 2018 |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/10911848/filing-history |publisher=Companies house |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\nIn March 2018 it became public by [[Whistleblower]] [[Christopher Wylie]], that Cambridge Analytica's first activities were founded on a data set, which its parent company SCL bought 2014 from a company named Global Science Research founded by [[Aleksandr Kogan]]<ref>Hannes Grassegger und Mikael Krogerus, in: [[Tages-Anzeiger]]: [https://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/ausland/europa/Ich-habe-nur-gezeigt-dass-es-die-Bombe-gibt/story/17474918 \u00abIch habe nur gezeigt, dass es die Bombe gibt\u00bb (I only showed, that there is a bomb)], 3. 20th 2018</ref> who worked as a psychologist at Cambridge.\n\nPer the Associated Press, [[Data Propria]], a data analysis firm launched May 2018, is run by former officials at Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/ap-trump-2020-working-with-ex-cambridge-analytica-staffers/2018/06/15/ebdde7e2-70c0-11e8-b4d8-eaf78d4c544c_story.html |title=AP: Trump 2020 working with ex-Cambridge Analytica staffers |author=Jeff Horwitz|date=15 June 2018 |work=Associated Press |via=WashingtonPost.com |access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmagazine.com/data-propria-heir-to-cambridge-analytica-working-for-rnc-possibly-trump-campaign/article/774206/ |title=Data Propria, heir to Cambridge Analytica, working for RNC, possibly Trump campaign |author=Teri Robinson|date=18 June 2018 |website=scmagazine.com |access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.accesswire.com/500425/CloudCommerce-Launches-Data-Propria-Inc-Its-New-Data-Analytics-Division |title=CloudCommerce Launches Data Propria, Inc., Its New Data Analytics Division |author=|date=29 May 2018 |website=accesswire.com |access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, several former Cambridge Analytica staff launched [[Auspex International]], a company intended to influence politics and society in Africa and the Middle East.<ref>https://www.wired.co.uk/article/wired-awake-130718</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44807093</ref><ref>https://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/3035777/cambridge-analyticas-latest-wants-your-google-search-history</ref><ref>https://boingboing.net/2018/07/11/zombie-analytica.html</ref><ref>https://www.ft.com/content/1c8a5e74-6901-11e8-8cf3-0c230fa67aec</ref><ref>https://www.ft.com/content/d92164fe-8514-11e8-96dd-fa565ec55929</ref>\n\n==Methods==\nCA's data analysis methods were to a large degree based on the academic work of Michal Kosinski. In 2008, Kosinski had joined the Psychometrics Centre of [[Cambridge University]] where he then developed with his colleagues a profiling system using general online data, [[Facebook]]-likes, and [[smartphone]] data.<ref name=\"Magazin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dasmagazin.ch/2016/12/03/ich-habe-nur-gezeigt-dass-es-die-bombe-gibt/ |author=Mikael Krogerus, Hannes Grassegger |title=Ich habe nur gezeigt, dass es die Bombe gibt |publisher=[[Das Magazin]] |language=German |date=3 December 2016 |accessdate=7 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.1218772110 |pmid=23479631 |title=Private traits and attributes are predictable from digital records of human behavior |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=110 |issue=15 |pages=5802\u20135805 |year=2013 |last1=Kosinski |first1=M |last2=Stillwell |first2=D |last3=Graepel |first3=T|pmc=3625324 |bibcode=2013PNAS..110.5802K }}</ref> He showed that with a limited number of \"likes\", people can be analysed better than friends or relatives can do and that individual psychological targeting is a powerful tool to influence people.<ref name=\"Magazin\"/>\n\nCA would collect data on voters using sources such as [[demographics]], [[consumer behaviour]], [[Computer and network surveillance|internet activity]], and other public and private sources. According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', CA used psychological data derived from millions of Facebook users, largely without users' permission or knowledge.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/11/senator-ted-cruz-president-campaign-facebook-user-data |author=Davies, H |title=Ted Cruz using firm that harvested data on millions of unwitting Facebook users |work=The Guardian |date=11 December 2015 |accessdate=7 February 2016 }}</ref> Another source of information was the \"Cruz Crew\" [[mobile app]] that tracked physical movements and contacts and according to the [[Associated Press]], invaded personal data more than previous presidential campaign apps.<ref name=\"ap0216\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/2db0fc93cf664a63909e26e708e91c67|title=Cruz app data collection helps campaign read minds of voters|last1=Biesecker|first1=Michael|date=11 February 2016|work=AP News|accessdate=13 February 2016|agency=[[Associated Press]]|last2=Bykowicz|first2=Julie}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=Today in the United States we have somewhere close to four or five thousand data points on every individual ... So we model the personality of every adult across the United States, some 230 million people.|author=Alexander Nix, chief executive of Cambridge Analytica |source=October 2016.<ref name=Sky2016/>}}[[File:Web Summit 2017 - Centre Stage Day 3 SAM 7454 (24415941378).jpg|thumb|left|Cambridge Analytica CEO [[Alexander Nix]] speaking in November 2017.]]\n\nThe company claimed to use \"data enhancement and [[audience segmentation]] techniques\" providing \"[[psychographic]] analysis\" for a \"deeper knowledge of the target audience\". The company uses the [[Big Five personality traits|Big Five model]] of personality <ref name=wpost/><ref name=ca/> Using what it calls \"[[behavioral targeting|behavioral]] [[microtargeting]]\" the company indicates that it can predict \"[[needs]]\" of subjects and how these needs may change over time. Services then can be individually targeted for the benefit of its clients from the political arena, governments, and companies providing \"a better and more actionable view of their key audiences.\" According to [[Sasha Issenberg]], CA indicates that it can tell things about an individual he might not even know about himself.<ref name=issenberg/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/passionateeye/episodes/the-persuasion-machine-of-silicon-valley |agency=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation and British Broadcasting Corporation |title=The Persuasion Machine of Silicon Valley |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=17 February 2018 |accessdate=17 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nCA derived much of its personality data on [[online survey]]s which it conducts on an ongoing basis. For each political client, the firm would narrow voter segments from 32 different [[personality style]]s it attributes to every adult in the United States. The personality data would inform the tone of the language used in ad messages or voter contact scripts, while additional data is used to determine voters' stances on particular issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/campaign-trail/cruz-s-data-company-works-night-3m-payout/302515 |title=Cruz's Data Company Works into the Night After Big $3 Million Payout |website=[[Advertising Age]]| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe data would get updated with monthly surveys, asking about political preferences and how people get the information they use to make decisions. It also covered consumer topics about different [[brand engagement|brands and preferred products]], building up an image of how someone shops as much as how they vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dcinno.streetwise.co/2016/02/08/political-ad-targeting-cambridge-analytica-adtech |title=Inside the Tech That Puts Political Ads on Your Screen |website=DC Inno| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===''Channel 4 News'' investigation===\n''[[Channel 4 News]]'', a news programme broadcast by the [[Public service broadcasting in the United Kingdom|British public service]] [[Channel 4]], conducted a four-month investigation into Cambridge Analytica starting in November 2017. An undercover reporter posed as a potential customer for Cambridge Analytica, hoping to help [[Sri Lanka]]n candidates get elected. Video footage from this operation was published on 19 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.channel4.com/news/cambridge-analytica-revealed-trumps-election-consultants-filmed-saying-they-use-bribes-and-sex-workers-to-entrap-politicians-investigation |title=Revealed: Trump's election consultants filmed saying they use bribes and sex workers to entrap politicians |work=Channel 4 News |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> From the footage, Cambridge Analytica executives say they worked on over 200 elections across the world.<ref name=\"dailynation\"/> Alexander Nix was recorded in this investigation, talking \"unguardedly about the company's practices\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Cadwalladr |first=Carole |authorlink1=Carole Cadwalladr |last2=Graham-Harrison |first2=Emma |title=The Cambridge Analytica Files : 'I made Steve Bannon's psychological warfare tool': meet the data war whistleblower |date=17 March 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/data-war-whistleblower-christopher-wylie-faceook-nix-bannon-trump |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=19 March 2018 }}</ref> Nix said that his company uses honey traps, bribery stings, and prostitutes, for opposition research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/92390/cambridge-analytica-ceo-admits-to-dirty-tricks |title=Cambridge Analytica CEO 'admits to dirty tricks' |work=The Week |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> For example, Nix offered to discredit political opponents in Sri Lanka with suggestive videos using \"beautiful Ukrainian girls\" and offers of bribes, even if the opponents did not accept the offers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/british-firm-sends-girls-to-entrap-politicians-wpthxqhwv |title=Cambridge Analytica sends 'girls' to entrap politicians |date=20 March 2018 |work=The Times}}</ref> He also said he uses \"Israeli companies\" to entrap political opponents with bribes and sex, the Wall Street Journal confirmed that it was referring to [[Psy-Group]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-intelligence-company-formed-venture-with-trump-campaign-firm-cambridge-analytica-1527030765|title=Israeli Intelligence Company Formed Venture With Trump Campaign Firm Cambridge Analytica|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=23 May 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=9 June 2019|last2=Ballhaus|first2=Rebecca|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"Nast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/05/the-dark-truth-about-cambridge-analyticas-ties-to-trumpworld|title=The Dark Truth About Cambridge Analytica's Ties to Trumpworld|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref>  [[Joel Zamel|Zamel]] signed a memorandum of understanding for Psy-Group with Cambridge Analytica on 14 December 2016.<ref name=\"Nast\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-intelligence-company-formed-venture-with-trump-campaign-firm-cambridge-analytica-1527030765|title=Israeli Intelligence Company Formed Venture With Trump Campaign Firm Cambridge Analytica|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=23 May 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=5 June 2019|last2=Ballhaus|first2=Rebecca|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-intelligence-company-formed-venture-with-trump-campaign-firm-cambridge-analytica-1527030765|title=Israeli Intelligence Company Formed Venture With Trump Campaign Firm Cambridge Analytica|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=23 May 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=9 June 2019|last2=Ballhaus|first2=Rebecca|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nCambridge Analytica said that the video footage was \"edited and scripted to grossly misrepresent\" the recorded conversations and company's business practices. Nix said that he had \"entertained a series of ludicrous hypothetical scenarios\", but insisted his company does not engage in entrapment or bribery.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pham |first1=Sherisse |last2=Riley |first2=Charles |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/03/20/technology/cambridge-analytica-channel-4-report/index.html |title=Cambridge Analytica responds after CEO filmed discussing bribery and entrapment |publisher=CNN |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the third part of the series, Nix also said that Cambridge Analytica \"ran all the digital campaign\" for Trump. Nix stated they used communications that would be self-destructive, leaving no incriminating evidence. After the news segment was broadcast, the board of Cambridge Analytica suspended Nix as chief executive officer. The company also released a statement that the allegations did not represent the ethics of the company, and an independent entity would investigate Nix's statements.<ref name=\"Lanxon\">{{cite news |last=Lanxon |first=Nate |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-20/cambridge-analytica-used-disappearing-emails-in-campaign-report |title=Cambridge Analytica Boasted of Disappearing Emails in Campaigns |work=Bloomberg |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe investigation also raised questions regarding campaign finance law. During the 2016 election, the company was employed both by Trump's campaign and Robert Mercer's [[Make America Number 1]] Super [[Political Action Committee|PAC]] which supported Trump. While PACs are not limited in the amount of funds they can spend on behalf of a candidate, they are not allowed to coordinate strategy with the campaigns they are supporting. Nix's statements in the recorded video describe how the Trump campaign itself could \"take the high road\" and \"stay clean\", while the negative attacks were handled by the firm and the Super PAC, in a way which makes it \"unattributable, untrackable\". These statements potentially suggested unlawful coordination between Trump's campaign and the PAC, although Cambridge Analytica has denied this.<ref name=\"Bump\">{{cite news |last=Bump |first=Philip |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/03/20/a-new-undercover-video-raises-significant-questions-about-cambridge-analyticas-elections-work/ |title=A new undercover video raises significant questions about Cambridge Analytica's elections work |work=The Washington Post |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Assessment of impact===\n[[File:Cambridge Analytica protest Parliament Square4.jpg|thumb|Canadian whistleblower [[Christopher Wylie]] who was the former director of research at Cambridge Analytica]]\nPolitical scientists have been highly skeptical of claims made by Cambridge Analytica about the effectiveness of its microtargeting of voters (microtargeting refers to the process of \"analyzing data to predict the behavior, interests, and opinions held by specific groups of people and then serving them the messages they're most likely to respond to\").<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/20/17138854/cambridge-analytica-facebook-data-trump-campaign-psychographic-microtargeting |title=Cambridge Analytica's Facebook data abuse shouldn't get credit for Trump |work=The Verge|access-date=20 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/03/27/the-reclusive-hedge-fund-tycoon-behind-the-trump-presidency |title=The Reclusive Hedge-Fund Tycoon Behind the Trump Presidency |last=Mayer |first=Jane |date=17 March 2017 |work=The New Yorker|access-date=20 March 2018 |issn=0028-792X }}</ref> Political scientists note that access to digital data is not going to provide significantly more information than from public voter databases, and the digital data has limited value over time as the preferences of voters change.<ref name=\":1\" /> Political scientists also note that it is hard to infer political values from personality traits, which means that it is easy to mistarget the messages that are sent to voters with specific personality traits.<ref name=\":1\" /> Research discussed by [[Brendan Nyhan]] of Dartmouth College showed that it is extremely hard to alter voters' preferences because many likely voters are already committed partisans; as a result, it is easier to simply mobilize partisan voters.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/13/upshot/fake-news-and-bots-may-be-worrisome-but-their-political-power-is-overblown.html |title=Fake News and Bots May Be Worrisome, but Their Political Power Is Overblown |last=Nyhan |first=Brendan |date=13 February 2018 |work=The New York Times|access-date=20 March 2018 |issn=0362-4331 }}</ref> Tufts University political scientist Eitan Hersh, who has published on microtargeting in campaigns, has expressed strong skepticism about Cambridge Analytica's methods and their purported effectiveness, saying \"Every claim about psychographics etc made by or about [Cambridge Analytica] is BS.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/03/19/cambridge-analytica |title=Cambridge Analytica Was Doing Marketing, Not Black Magic |date=19 March 2018 |work=Reason|access-date=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, CA claimed that it has psychological profiles of 220 million US citizens based on 5,000 separate data sets.<ref name=\"InkJun2017\">{{cite news |url=https://fountainink.in/reportage/aadhaar-in-the-hand-of-spies- |title=Aadhaar in the hand of spies Big Data, global surveillance state and the identity project |author=Govind Krishnan V. |date=3 June 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |publisher=Fountain Ink Magazine }}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that CA had exaggerated its capabilities: \"Cambridge executives now concede that the company never used psychographics in the Trump campaign.\"<ref name=\"Confessore\" /> Trump aides have also disputed CA's role in the campaign, describing it as \"modest\" and noting that none of the company's efforts involved psychographics.<ref name=\"Confessore\" />\n\nAccording to an aide and consultant for Ted Cruz's presidential campaign, their campaign stopped using CA after its psychographic models failed to identify likely Cruz supporters. The Cruz campaign ceased access to all of Cambridge's data after the [[2016 South Carolina Republican primary|South Carolina Republican primary]] on 20 February 2016 when Cruz came in third after Trump and Rubio.<ref name=Confessore/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/south-carolina-nevada-2016-election/ted-cruz-speaks-after-south-carolina-primary/ |title=Ted Cruz on South Carolina Primary |date=20 February 2016 |work=The New York Times|access-date=21 March 2018 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Privacy issues===\nThe use of [[personal data]] collected without knowledge or permission to establish sophisticated models of user's personalities raises ethical and [[Privacy concerns with social networking services|privacy issue]]s.<ref name=guardian/> CA operated out of the United States; its operations would be illegal in Europe with its stricter [[privacy law]]s.<ref name=ap0216/> While Cruz was outspoken about protecting personal information from the government, his database of CA has been described as \"political-voter [[surveillance]]\".<ref name=\"ap0216\" />\n\nRegarding CA's use of Facebook users, a speaker for CA indicated that these users gave permission when signing up with the provider, while Facebook declared that \"misleading people or misusing information\" is in violation of Facebook's policies.<ref name=guardian/> In 2015, Facebook indicated that it was investigating the matter.<ref name=guardian/> In March 2018, Facebook announced that it had suspended the accounts of Strategic Communication Laboratories for failing to delete data on Facebook users that had been improperly collected.<ref>{{cite news |first=Elizabeth |last=Dwoskin |date=16 March 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2018/03/16/facebook-bans-trump-campaigns-data-analytics-firm-for-taking-user-data/ |title=Facebook bans Trump campaign's data analytics firm for taking user data |work=[[The Washington Post]] |quote=Facebook said it was suspending the accounts of Strategic Communication Laboratories, the parent company of Cambridge Analytica, as well as the accounts of a University of Cambridge psychologist Aleksandr Kogan, and Christopher Wylie of Eunoia Technologies, Inc. Cambridge Analytica, a firm specializing in using online data to create voter personality profiles in order to target them with messages, ran data operations for Trump's presidential campaign. }}</ref>\n\nAlexander Nix suggested that data collection and microtargeting benefits the voters \u2013 because they receive messages about issues they care about. However, [[digital rights]] protection groups raised concerns that private information is collected, stored, and shared while individuals are \"left in the dark about [it]\" and have no control.<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/2016-election-day/trump-campaign-pays-millions-overseas-big-data-firm-n677321 |first=Kate |last=Brannelly |title=Trump Campaign Pays Millions to Overseas Big Data Firm |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=4 November 2016 |accessdate=5 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nSignificant backlash against Facebook came to light in March 2018, resulting in controversy as well as a $37&nbsp;billion drop in the [[market capitalization]] of Facebook, as of 20 March.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43462423 |title=Facebook's value falls $37bn amid backlash |date=19 March 2018 |publisher=BBC |access-date=20 March 2018 }}</ref> Due to the scandal of enabling monetization of Facebook personal data, one assessment was that only 41% of Facebook users trust the company.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Nelson Granados |title=Transparency: How Facebook Can Recover From The Cambridge Analytica Crisis |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nelsongranados/2018/03/26/transparency-how-facebook-can-recover-from-the-cambridge-analytica-crisis/ |work=Forbes |accessdate=26 March 2018 |date=26 March 2018}}</ref> On 26 March, the US [[Federal Trade Commission]] announced it is \"conducting an open investigation of Facebook Inc's privacy practices following the disclosure that 50 million users' data got into the hands of political consultancy Cambridge Analytica.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. FTC investigating Facebook's privacy practices |url=http://news.trust.org/item/20180326145505-6je9o/ |work=Reuters |date=26 March 2018 |quote=If the FTC finds Facebook violated terms of the consent decree, it has the power to fine the company thousands of dollars a day per violation, which could add up to billions of dollars. \"The FTC takes very seriously recent press reports raising substantial concerns about the privacy practices of Facebook. Today, the FTC is confirming that it has an open non-public investigation into these practices,\" Tom Pahl, acting director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection, said in a statement.}}</ref> In March 2019 Facebook acknowledged it had concerns about \u201cimproper data-gathering practices\u201d by CA, months before the previously reported onset-of-alert at December 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/mar/21/facebook-knew-of-cambridge-analytica-data-misuse-earlier-than-reported-court-filing|title=Facebook acknowledges concerns over Cambridge Analytica emerged earlier than reported|last=Wong|first=Julia Carrie|date=22 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=22 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Elections==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn Australia, Cambridge Analytica set up an office. Allan Lorraine, a friend of Alexander Tayler who was a former director for Cambridge Analytica and later appointed director of [[Emerdata]], set up SCL (the parent company of Cambridge Analytica) in Australia. Representatives of Cambridge Analytica had a private dinner with [[Dan Tehan]] when he was then the minister responsible for cyber security, and [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal party]] executives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-21/cambridge-analytica-in-australia/9570432|title=Cambridge Analytica's Australian office is a former used-car salesman's house|last=McGhee|first=political reporter Ashlynne|date=2018-03-21|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> The business name \"Cambridge Analytica\" was registered in Australia to the Lorraine Family Trust in June 2015. SCL Group, promoted Mr Lorraine online as its head of Australian operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/consumer-affairs/friend-of-a-friend-australian-link-to-cambridge-analytica-20180321-p4z5jb.html|title='Friend of a friend': Australian link to Cambridge Analytica|last=Begley|first=Patrick|date=2018-03-21|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Alexander Nix spoke at an Australian data-driven advertising conference run by the [[Association for Data-driven Marketing and Advertising]] and met with Liberal Party officials.<ref name=\"sbs.com.au\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/trump-s-data-consultant-to-meet-aust-govt|title=Trump's data consultant to meet Aust govt|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adma.com.au/people/alexander-nix|title=Alexander Nix|date=2017-01-10|website=ADMA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Cambridge Analytica was scoping both political as well as commercial work in Australia.<ref name=\"sbs.com.au\"/> Cambridge Analytica's managing director of political operations said in a video recorded by Channel 4 that \"We\u2019ve done it in Mexico, we\u2019ve done it in Malaysia, we\u2019re now moving into Brazil, Australia, China.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australian-parties-deny-using-data-firm-cambridge-analytica|title=Australian parties deny using data firm Cambridge Analytica|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\nMore than 310,000 Australian Facebook users were among the millions globally who may have had their information improperly shared with Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/facebook-says-310-000-australian-users-may-have-been-affected-by-cambridge-analytica-scandal-20180405-p4z7tm.html|title=Facebook says 310,000 Australian users may have been affected by Cambridge Analytica scandal|last=Clun|first=Rachel|date=2018-04-04|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/311127-australian-facebook-users-may-harvested-data-passed-cambridge-analytica-509188|title=Up to 311,127 Australian Facebook users may have had harvested data passed on to Cambridge Analytica|last=Burrowes|first=Tim|date=2018-04-04|website=Mumbrella|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n===India===\nIn India, Cambridge Analytica had been used by the [[Indian National Congress]] (INC) to carry out \"in-depth electorate analysis\" and influence voters, including in the [[2010 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2010 elections]] to the [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Punit |first1=Itika |title=Cambridge Analytica's parent firm proposed a massive political machine for India's 2014 elections |url=https://qz.com/1239561/cambridge-analyticas-parent-firm-proposed-a-massive-political-machine-for-indias-2014-elections/ |accessdate=6 June 2018 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Quartz |date=28 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"caofficialpol\">{{cite web |title=Our Political data driven campaigns|publisher=Cambridge Analytica official website }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Punit |first=Itika Sharma |title=Why Cambridge Analytica was eager to play in the world's largest democracy |url=https://qz.com/1233040/cambridge-analytica-was-eager-to-play-in-the-worlds-largest-democracy/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> 355 Indian Facebook users installed a Cambridge Analytica app, exposing the data of 562,455 users.<ref>{{cite web |last=Punit |first=Itika Sharma |title=Facebook admits Cambridge Analytica may have accessed the data of over 560,000 users in India \u2013 Quartz |url=https://qz.com/1245515/facebook-admits-cambridge-analytica-may-have-accessed-the-data-of-over-560000-users-in-india |website=Quartz |accessdate=5 April 2018 |date=5 April 2018}}</ref> In addition, [[Christopher Wylie]], the Cambridge Analytica [[whistleblower]], alleged that the company had offices and staff in India, and that the INC party was a major client.<ref>{{cite news |title='Believe' Congress was a client, says Cambridge Analytica whistleblower |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/believe-congress-was-a-client-says-cambridge-analytica-whistleblower/articleshow/63491061.cms |accessdate=23 April 2018 |publisher=[[The Economic Times]] |date=27 March 2018}}</ref> A [[BBC]] documentary clip showing a poster of the INC in Wylie's office went viral in India, sparking accusations that the company was manipulating both mainstream and social media in order to subvert Indian voters away from the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and towards the INC as part of a [[neocolonial]] effort to undermine Indian politics in favor of vested interests.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC documentary clip goes viral, shows Congress poster in office of Cambridge Analytica's ex-CEO Alexander Nix |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-bbc-documentary-clip-goes-viral-shows-congress-poster-in-office-of-cambridge-analytica-s-ex-ceo-alexander-nix-2598837 |website=[[DNA India]] |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> In early 2018 Cambridge Analytica made a 50-page proposal for the INC for both the upcoming [[2019 Indian general election|2019 general election in India]] and their upcoming electoral campaign for the Indian states of [[Karnataka]], Chhattisgarh and [[Madhya Pradesh]] state elections in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica made 2019 roadmap for Congress; party denies any deal |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/cambridge-analytica-made-2019-roadmap-for-congress-party-denies-any-deal/articleshow/63823483.cms |website=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> The Indian National Congress, however, lost the elections by a sizable margin, winning not even enough seats to be the official opposition party in India.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Kenya===\nCA ran campaigns in secret during Kenya's [[2013 Kenyan general election|2013]] and [[2017 Kenyan general election|2017 elections]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dahir |first1=Abdi Latif |title=\"We'd stage the whole thing\": Cambridge Analytica filmed boasting of its role in Kenya's polls |url=https://qz.com/1233084/channel-4-news-films-cambridge-analytica-execs-saying-they-staged-kenya-uhuru-kenyatta-elections/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> In 2018, a CA employee said that his predecessor at the company had been found dead in his hotel room in Kenya while working on [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]'s 2013 campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lang'at |first1=Patrick |title=Exposed: Analytica staff died in Kenya |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Cambridge-Analytica-staff-Dan-Mure-an-died-in-Kenya/1064-4351058-11gicwcz/index.html |accessdate=21 March 2018 |work=Daily Nation |date=21 March 2018 |language=en-UK}}</ref> The company claimed on its website to have conducted a survey of 47,000 Kenyans during the 2013 elections in order to understand \"key national and local political issues, levels of trust in key politicians, voting behaviours/intentions, and preferred information channels\". According to verified sources, CA worked with 360 Media, a company formed by [[Simon Gicharu]] (founder of [[Mount Kenya University]]) and Tom Mshindi (Editor-in-Chief of [[Nation Media Group]]). 360 Media developed online campaigns in the 2017 Kenyan elections portraying \"Raila Odinga as a blood-thirsty individual who is also sympathetic to Al-Shabaab and having no development agenda,\" whilst portraying the incumbent President Kenyatta as \"tough on terrorism, and being good for the economy.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Matende |first1=David |title=Media, like false preachers |url=http://nairobilawmonthly.com/index.php/2018/06/05/media-like-false-preachers |accessdate=6 August 2018 |work=Nairobi Law Monthly |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the revelations in March 2018, where CA staff boasted of their power in Kenya, opposition figures called for an investigation. Norman Magaya, an official of the [[National Super Alliance]], accused CA and the ruling [[Jubilee Party]] of committing a crime and called for an investigation.<ref name=\"BBC_News_3/20/2018\">{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica's Kenyan role queried |website=BBC News |date=20 March 2018 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43471707 | access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref> The Jubilee Party downplayed CA's role, saying it had hired the firm's parent company, to assist with branding.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cambridge Analytica's Kenyan role queried |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43471707 |accessdate=21 March 2018 |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Malta===\n\nIn its Disinformation and 'fake news' inquiry, published on 29 July 2018, the UK Parliament's [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]] noted that it is believed that CA, or its associated companies, worked with the [[Labour Party (Malta)|Labour Party]] in [[Malta]], on the [[2013 Maltese general election]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee |title=Disinformation and 'fake news': Interim Report |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201719/cmselect/cmcumeds/363/36309.htm#_idTextAnchor053}}</ref> Several sources claim that CA had close relationships with [[Henley & Partners]] who would immediately after the election introduce and run a lucrative Citizenship by Investment Program in Malta.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.imidaily.com/editors-picks/hpsclcambridge2/ |title= Henley & Partners Speaks Out on SCL, Cambridge Analytica, House of Commons Report\n |date=7 August 2018 |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Caribbean News Now! |title=UK parliamentary report calls for criminal investigation of Henley and SCL |url=https://www.dominicavibes.dm/international/print-248315/  |access-date=13 March 2020}}<!-- original url (no good archive copies found): https://wp.caribbeannewsnow.com/2018/07/30/uk-parliamentary-report-calls-for-criminal-investigation-of-henley-and-scl/ --></ref> The Maltese Government issued a press release denying the claims and calling the report and its sources \"[[fake news]]\".<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Government of Malta Department of Information  |title=PR181687: Statement by the Government of Malta: Government of Malta makes official representations regarding UK DCMS Committee report |url=https://www.gov.mt/en/Government/DOI/Press%20Releases/Pages/2018/July/30/pr181687.aspx}}</ref> Henley & Partners denied any wrongdoing. According to Henley & Partners, there was never a formal working relationship with CA.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/world/85644/passportsellers_henley_and_cambridge_analyticas_nix_exchanged_ideas_on_caribbean_election#.W-QmuieNzUI |title= Passport-sellers Henley and Cambridge Analytica's Nix 'exchanged ideas' on Caribbean election |date=28 March 2018 |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Final Report by the [[UK Parliament]]'s Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee, published on 18 February 2019, took note of the [[Maltese Government]]'s submissions (including through PR agency [[Chelgate]]'s services) but determined that compelling evidence shown to the Committee confirmed that:\n\n\"''SCL certainly had meetings in Malta, that [[Christian K\u00e4lin|Christian Kalin]] of Henley & Partners was introduced by SCL to [[Joseph Muscat]] in 2011, and that Christian Kalin met with both political parties before 2013''\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee |title=Disinformation and 'fake news': Final Report |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201719/cmselect/cmcumeds/1791/179110.htm#_idTextAnchor071}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maltese Government 2017\u20132022|Maltese Government]] later issued a further denial decrying the use of \"''unnamed sources''\" and \"''confidential documents''\".<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Government of Malta Department of Information |title=PR190309: Statement by the Government of Malta: Malta denies allegations in report by the Select Committee on Digital, Culture, Media and Sport |url=https://www.gov.mt/en/Government/DOI/Press%20Releases/Pages/2019/February/18/pr190309.aspx}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nAfter the [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal]], ''[[Forbes]]'' published that the British news program ''Channel 4 News'' had mentioned the existence of proof revealing ties between the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]] (PRI) and Cambridge Analytica, suggesting a ''[[modus operandi]]'' similar to the one in the United States. According to Channel 4 News' Guillermo Galdos, CA worked for the PRI at least until January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com.mx/cambridge-analytica-mexico-pri-enero-2018-channel-4-news/|title=Cambridge Analytica trabaj\u00f3 con el PRI: Channel 4 News|website=Forbes M\u00e9xico|date=30 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/opinion/javier-murillo/cambridge-analytica-sigan-la-ruta-del-dinero|title=Cambridge Analytica, sigan la ruta del dinero|first=Javier|last=Murillo|website=El Financiero}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/03/22/inenglish/1521710735_571195.html|title=The distorted online networks of Mexico's election campaign|first1=Fernando|last1=Peinado|first2=Elvira|last2=Palomo|first3=Javier|last3=Gal\u00e1n|date=22 March 2018|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds}}</ref> An investigation was requested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.proceso.com.mx/528182/exigen-al-inai-investigar-a-cambridge-analytica-facebook-y-desarrolladoras-de-apps-en-mexico|title=Exigen al INAI investigar a Cambridge Analytica, Facebook y desarrolladoras de Apps en M\u00e9xico|website=Proceso|date=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the company had reached out to the PRI, Mexico's ruling political party, in order to bolster the party's presidential campaign during the largest-ever political [[2018 Mexican general election|elections of 2018]]. The party decided that it was sufficiently equipped to mess with the election on its own, but still paid Cambridge Analytica to prevent it from working with rival parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/24/world/americas/mexico-election-cambridge-analytica.html|title=Mexico's Hardball Politics Get Even Harder as PRI Fights to Hold On to Power|access-date=1 July 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{further|Russian interference in the 2016 Brexit referendum|Unlawful campaigning in the 2016 EU referendum}}\n[[File:Cambridge Analytica protest Parliament Square1.jpg|thumb|A protest following the Cambridge Analytica scandal, 29 March 2018]]\nMany donors to the UK [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] reportedly have connections to the parent company of Cambridge Analytica.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/21/tory-donors-among-investors-in-cambridge-analytica-parent-firm-scl-group Tory donors among investors in Cambridge Analytica parent firm] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nCA became involved in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]] (Brexit) supporting \"persuadable\" voters to vote for leaving the [[European Union]] (EU).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/world/trump-calls-in-brexit-experts-to-target-voters-pf0hwcts9 |first=Rhys |last=Blakely |title=Data scientists target 20 million new voters for Trump |work=[[The Times]] |date=22 September 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 }}</ref> Articles by [[Carole Cadwalladr]] in ''[[The Observer]]'' and ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' newspapers, respectively published in February and May 2017, speculated in detail that CA had influenced both the [[Brexit]]/[[Vote Leave]] option in the UK's 2016 EU membership referendum and [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Trump's 2016 US presidential campaign]] with [[Robert Mercer]]'s backing of [[Donald Trump]] being key. They also discuss the legality of using the social data farmed.<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite news |last=Barnett |first=Anthony |url=http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2017/12/14/democracy-and-the-machinations-of-mind-control/ |title=Democracy and the Machinations of Mind Control |work=New York Review of Books |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=16 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/feb/26/robert-mercer-breitbart-war-on-media-steve-bannon-donald-trump-nigel-farage |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |title=Robert Mercer: the big data billionaire waging war on mainstream media |work=[[The Observer]] |date=26 February 2017 |accessdate=27 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/07/the-great-british-brexit-robbery-hijacked-democracy |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |title=The Great British Brexit robbery how our democracy was hijacked |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=7 May 2017 |accessdate=7 May 2017 }}</ref> CA is pursuing legal action over the claims made in Cadwalladr's articles.<ref name=\"Barnett\"/>\n\nNo campaign contributions, in cash or in kind, by Cambridge Analytica were reported to the UK electoral authorities. Both CA and [[Leave.EU]] refused to comment on any donation of services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/feb/26/us-billionaire-mercer-helped-back-brexit |title=Revealed: how US billionaire helped to back Brexit |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |date=26 February 2017 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> On 23 March 2018, it was reported that a former employee, [[Brittany Kaiser]], who was the company's former director of business development, revealed that the company misled the public and MPs over its links with Leave.EU and the analysis of data which had been provided by the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP). She said she felt she had lied by supporting Cambridge Analytica's company line that it had done \"no paid or unpaid work\" for Leave.EU. \"In my opinion, I was lying. In my opinion I felt like we should say, 'this is exactly what we did'\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/23/cambridge-analytica-misled-mps-over-work-for-leave-eu-says-ex-director-brittany-kaiser |title=Cambridge Analytica misled MPs over work for Leave.EU, says ex-director |work=[[The Guardian]] |author=Paul Lewis and Paul Hilder |date=23 March 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> The following day, it was reported that the company claimed that it would be able to affect the outcome of the Referendum and that it had produced a 10-page document headed \"Big Data Solutions for the EU Referendum\", claiming it could single out 'Brexiteers' among voters, donors, politicians and journalists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/cambridge-analytica-bragged-we-have-vast-data-for-brexit-vote-a3797441.html |title=Cambridge Analytica bragged: We have vast data for Brexit vote |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |author=Joe Murphy, Political Editor |date=24 March 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nDW reported in March 2018 that \"Whistleblower Christopher Wylie told UK lawmakers during a committee hearing on Tuesday that a firm linked to Cambridge Analytica helped the official Vote Leave campaign [the official pro-Brexit group headed by [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Michael Gove]]] circumvent campaign financing laws during the Brexit referendum.\"<ref>\"[http://www.dw.com/en/what-role-did-cambridge-analytica-play-in-the-brexit-vote/a-43151460 What role did Cambridge Analytica play in the Brexit vote?]\". ''Deutsche Welle.'' 27 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===United States===\nLaurence Levy, a lawyer with the law firm [[Bracewell & Giuliani]], advises [[Rebekah Mercer]], [[Steve Bannon]], and [[Alexander Nix]] on the legality of their company, Cambridge Analytica, being involved in [[Elections in the United States]]. He advises that Nix and any foreign nationals without a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]] working for the company must not be involved in any decision making regarding any work the company performs for any clients related to [[U.S. elections]].  He further advises Nix to recuse himself from any involvement with the company's U.S. election work because he is not a [[U.S. citizen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Participation in US Elections |url=http://msnbcmedia.msn.com/i/TODAY/z_Creative/LEVY_MEMO_DM_4636592_v1_Memo_re__Participation_in_US_Elections.pdf |date=22 July 2014 |access-date=23 March 2018 |last=Levy |first=Laurence |via=[[MSNBC]] |publisher=[[Bracewell & Giuliani|Bracewell & Giuliani LLP]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402031730/http://msnbcmedia.msn.com/i/TODAY/z_Creative/LEVY_MEMO_DM_4636592_v1_Memo_re__Participation_in_US_Elections.pdf |archive-date=2 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/wylie-foreigners-worked-cambridge-analytica-nc-senate-campaign-n859526 |title=Wylie: Foreigners worked for Cambridge Analytica on NC Senate campaign |work=NBC News|access-date=23 March 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====2014 midterm elections====\nCA had entered the US market in 2012<ref name= wp/> (or 2013),<ref name=issenberg/> and was involved in 44 [[United States Congress|US congressional]], [[United States Senate|US Senate]] and state-level elections in the [[2014 United States elections|2014 US elections]].<ref name=\"wp\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cruz-campaign-paid-750000-to-psychographic-profiling-company/2015/10/19/6c83e508-743f-11e5-9cbb-790369643cf9_story.html |title=Cruz campaign paid $750,000 to 'psychographic profiling' company |last=Sellers |first=Frances Stead |authorlink=Frances Stead Sellers |date=19 October 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |issn=0190-8286| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe company worked with the [[John R. Bolton#John Bolton Super PAC|John Bolton Super PAC]] (political action committee) on a major digital and TV campaign focused on senate races in [[2014 United States Senate election in Arkansas|Arkansas]], [[2014 United States Senate election in North Carolina|North Carolina]] and [[2014 United States Senate election in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] and helped turn out voters for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] candidates in those states. Two of the Republican candidates backed by the Bolton Super PAC, [[Thom Tillis]] in North Carolina and [[Tom Cotton]] in Arkansas, won their Senate bids, while [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] lost in New Hampshire. The PAC ran 15 different TV advertisements each in North Carolina and Arkansas and 17 in New Hampshire, mostly online with some targeted directly to households using [[Dish Network]] and [[DirecTV]]. All were intended to push Bolton's national security agenda.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/campaign-trail/hyped-data-firm-s-promise-tested-iowa/302412 |title=Much-Hyped Data Firm's Promise Could Be Tested in Iowa |work=Advertising Age| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nCA also supported [[Thom Tillis]]'s successful campaign to oust [[Kay Hagan]] as a senator for North Carolina. The firm was credited for its role in identifying a sizeable cluster of North Carolinians who prioritised foreign affairs, which encouraged Tillis to shift the conversation from state-level debates over education policy to charges that incumbent Kay Hagan had failed to take [[ISIS]]'s rise seriously.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/features/2015-11-12/is-the-republican-party-s-killer-data-app-for-real |title=Cruz-Connected Data Miner Aims to Get Inside U.S. Voters' Heads |website=Bloomberg.com | access-date = 26 February 2016}}</ref> Tillis's campaign and the [[North Carolina Republican Party]] paid Cambridge Analytica $345,000 for these services.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Brian |last2=Bonner |first2=Lynn |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/politics-columns-blogs/under-the-dome/article205946479.html |title=Tillis and NC Republicans paid $345,000 to the data firm that's now banned from Facebook |work=The News & Observer |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nCA sent dozens of non-U.S. citizens to provide campaign strategy and messaging advice to Republican candidates in 2014, opening the firm and individuals to prosecution under the [[Foreign Agents Registration Act]], for being foreign agents having not registered through the [[United States Department of Justice]] as such.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/former-cambridge-analytica-workers-say-firm-sent-foreigners-to-advise-us-campaigns/2018/03/25/6a0d7d90-2fa2-11e8-911f-ca7f68bff0fc_story.html |title=Former Cambridge Analytica workers say firm sent foreigners to advise U.S. campaigns |last=Timberg |first=Craig |date=25 March 2018 |work=Washington Post|access-date=26 March 2018 |last2=Hamburger |first2=Tom |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n====2016 presidential election====\n{{further|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)}}\nCA's involvement in the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries]] became known in July 2015.<ref name=politico/> As of December 2015, CA claimed to have collected up to 5,000 data points on over 220 million Americans.<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web |url=https://cambridgeanalytica.org/about |title=About Us |publisher=Cambridge Analytica |accessdate=27 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216023554/https://cambridgeanalytica.org/about |archivedate=16 February 2016 }}</ref> At that time [[Robert Mercer (businessman)|Robert Mercer]] was a major supporter of [[Ted Cruz]].<ref name=issenberg/><ref name=\"nyt0415\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/11/us/politics/hedge-fund-magnaterobert-mercer-emerges-as-a-generous-backer-of-ted-cruz.html |last1=Lichtblau |first1=E |last2=Stevenson |first2=A |title=Hedge-Fund Magnate Robert Mercer Emerges as a Generous Backer of Cruz |work=The New York Times |date=10 April 2015 |accessdate=6 February 2016 }}</ref> The Mercer family funded CA directly and indirectly through several [[super-PACs]] as well as through payments via Cruz's campaign.<ref name= guardian/>\n\nCruz became an early major client of CA in the 2016 presidential campaign. Just prior to the [[2016 Iowa Republican caucuses|Iowa Republican caucuses]], the Cruz campaign had spent $3&nbsp;million for CA's services,<ref name=\"guardian2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/01/ted-cruz-trump-iowa-caucus-voter-targeting |author=Harry Davies |title=Ted Cruz erased Trump's Iowa lead by spending millions on voter targeting |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=7 February 2016 }}</ref> with additional money coming from allied Super-PACs.<ref name=guardian2/> After Cruz's win at the Iowa caucus CA was credited with having been able to identify and motivate potential voters.<ref name=\"bloomberg2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2016-02-02/how-ted-cruz-engineered-his-iowa-triumph |author=Sasha Issenberg |title=How Ted Cruz Engineered His Iowa Triumph |work=Bloomberg.com |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cambridge-analytica-congratulates-senator-ted-cruz-on-iowa-caucus-win-300213608.html |title=Cambridge Analytica Congratulates Senator Ted Cruz on Iowa Caucus Win |agency=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 }}</ref> Ultimately the Cruz campaign spent $5.8&nbsp;million on work by CA.<ref name=adage/>\n\n[[Ben Carson]] was a second client of CA; [[Ben Carson 2016 presidential campaign|his campaign]] had paid $220,000 for \"data management\" and \"web service\" as reported in October 2015.<ref name=\"wpost\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cruz-campaign-paid-750000-to-psychographic-profiling-company/2015/10/19/6c83e508-743f-11e5-9cbb-790369643cf9_story.html |first=Frances Stead |last=Sellers |title=Cruz campaign paid $750,000 to 'psychographic profiling' company |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=7 February 2016 }}</ref> [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign|Marco Rubio's campaign]] was supported by [[Optimus Consulting]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.campaignsandelections.com/campaign-insider/2646/organization-and-analytics-help-take-down-trump-in-iowa |first1=Sean J. |last=Miller |title=Organization and Analytics Help Take Down Trump in Iowa |work=CampaignsandElections.com |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=23 February 2016 }}</ref> Meanwhile, the third competitor, Governor [[John Kasich]], was supported by rivalling firm [[Applecart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-11-24/a-new-data-mining-technique-to-uncover-new-hampshire-influencers |title=Data-Mining Firm Searches for Voters by Combing High School Yearbooks |work=Bloomberg.com }}</ref>\n\nAfter Cruz dropped out of the race for the Republican presidential nomination in May 2016, Robert Mercer and his daughter Rebekah Mercer started to support Trump.<ref name=\"nr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/438739/trump-campaigns-data-firm-partner-cambridge-analytica-worked-cruz |first=Eliana |last=Johnson |title=The GOP nominee makes a late attempt at data-driven targeted messaging |work=[[National Review]] |date=5 August 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 }}</ref> In August, it became known that CA followed their allegiance and worked for Trump's presidential campaign.<ref name= adage/><ref name=nr/> Trump's campaign also worked with digital firm [[Giles-Parscale|Giles Parscale]].<ref name=\"adage\">{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/campaign-trail/trump-spending-cambridge-peanuts/305597/ |author=Kate Kaye |title=Trump Spending With Cambridge Analytica Looks Like Peanuts Compared to Cruz |work=Advertising Age |date=24 August 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 }}</ref> In September, the Trump campaign spent $5&nbsp;million to purchase television advertising.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/us/politics/cambridge-analytica.html |first1=Nicholas |last1=Confessore |first2=Danny |last2=Hakim |title=Data Firm Says 'Secret Sauce' Aided Trump; Many Scof |work=The New York Times |date=6 March 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2017 }}</ref> The Trump campaign spent less than $1&nbsp;million in data work.<ref name=\"opensecrets\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/pres16/expenditures?id=n00023864 |author=OpenSecrets \u2013 FEC |title=Top Vendors/Recipients |publisher=[[OpenSecrets]]/[[Federal Election Commission|FEC]] }}</ref>{{failed verification|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2016, the company said that it had not used psychographics in the Trump presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/us/politics/cambridge-analytica.html |title=Data Firm Says 'Secret Sauce' Aided Trump; Many Scoff |work=The New York Times |date=6 March 2017 }}</ref> Cambridge Analytica targeted potential voters with bespoke messages. Cambridge Analytica's data head, Alexander Tayler said, \"When you think about the fact that Donald Trump lost the popular vote by 3m votes but won the electoral college vote, [t]hat's down to the data and the research.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/22/us-politics-data-cambridge-analytica-russia-trump The poison in politics runs deeper than dodgy data] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nThe head of Cambridge Analytica said he asked [[WikiLeaks]] founder, [[Julian Assange]], for help finding [[Hillary Clinton]]'s 33,000 [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|deleted emails]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/367141-congressional-investigators-find-irregularities-in-fbis-handling-of |title=Congressional investigators find irregularities in FBI's handling of Clinton email case |first=Brandon |last=Conradis |date=2 January 2018 |publisher=The Hill }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-data-guru-i-tried-to-team-up-with-julian-assange |title=Trump Data Guru: I Tried to Team Up With Julian Assange |last=Woodruff |first=Betsy |date=25 October 2017 |work=The Daily Beast|access-date=25 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/25/politics/cambridge-analytica-julian-assange-wikileaks-clinton-emails/index.html |title=Trump campaign analytics company contacted WikiLeaks about Clinton emails |author1=Kara Scannell |author2=Dana Bash |author3=Marshall Cohen |publisher=CNN|access-date=25 October 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2017, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported that the [[US Congress]] was investigating CA in connection with [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]. The report alleges that CA may have coordinated the spread of Russian propaganda using its microtargetting capabilities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/4783932/inside-russia-social-media-war-america/ |title=Inside Russia's Social Media War on America |website=Time }}</ref> According to the Trump campaign's digital operations chief, CA worked \"side-by-side\" with representatives from Facebook, [[Alphabet Inc.]] and [[Twitter]] on Trump's digital campaign activities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/14/brad-parscale-trump-digital-house-intel-committee-240557 |title=Trump campaign's digital director agrees to meet with House Intel Committee |publisher=Politico }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2017, [[Michael Flynn]], who is under investigation by US counterintelligence for his contacts with Russian officials, amended a public financial filing to reflect that he had served in an advisory role in an agreement with CA during the 2016 Trump campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-eyes-michael-flynns-links-to-russia-1485134942 |title=U.S. Eyes Michael Flynn's Links to Russia |first1=Carol E. |last1=Lee |first2=Devlin |last2=Barrett |first3=Shane |last3=Harris |date=23 January 2017 |via=The Wall Street Journal }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2017, [[Brad Parscale]], who was the digital media director for Trump's 2016 presidential campaign, stated in an interview with [[Lesley Stahl]] from [[CBS News]] on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' that Parscale was able to utilize Facebook advertising to directly target individual voters in [[swing states]].<ref name=\"CBSNews\">{{Cite news|last=Stahl|first=Lesley|title=Parscale: TV news \"thought I was a joke\"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/parscale-tv-news-thought-i-was-a-joke/|work=CBS News|date=8 October 2017|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Parscale cited the example in which he was able to target specific universes (audiences) who care about infrastructure and promote Trump and his message to build back up the crumbling American infrastructure.<ref name=\"SecretWeapon\">{{Cite news|title=Secret Weapon|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/secret-weapon/|work=CBS News|date=8 October 2017|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Although he hired Cambridge Analytica to assist with [[microtargeting]], and Cambridge Analytica stated that it was the key to Trump's victory, Parscale denied that he gained assistance from the firm, stating that he thought Cambridge Analytica's use of psychographics doesn't work.<ref name=\"Stahl\">{{cite news |last=Stahl|first=Lesley|title= Facebook \"embeds,\" Russia and the Trump campaign's secret weapon|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-embeds-russia-and-the-trump-campaigns-secret-weapon/|work=CBS News|date=8 October 2017|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> He also denied any assistance with links to Russia.<ref name=Stahl/> According to Parscale, the [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|Clinton campaign]] turned down assistance from these platforms.<ref name=Stahl/>\n\nOn 25 October 2017, Assange said on Twitter that he had been approached by Cambridge Analytica, but that he had rejected its proposal.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=JulianAssange |number=923226553428987904 |title=I can confirm an approach by Cambridge Analytica and can confirm that it was rejected by WikiLeaks. |name=Julian Assange&nbsp; |date=25 October 2017}}</ref> Assange's tweet followed a story in ''[[The Daily Beast]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-data-guru-i-tried-to-team-up-with-julian-assange |title=Trump Data Guru: I Tried to Team Up With Julian Assange |first=Betsy |last=Woodruff |date=25 October 2017 |via=thedailybeast.com }}</ref> alleging that Cambridge Analytica chief executive Alexander Nix had proposed a collaboration with Wikileaks to find the 33,000 emails that had been deleted from Clinton's private server. [[CNN]] said it had been told by several unnamed sources<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/27/politics/trump-campaign-wikileaks-cambridge-analytica/index.html |title=Trump. Cambridge Analytica. WikiLeaks. The connections, explained. |first=Marshall |last=Cohen |publisher=CNN }}</ref> that Nix intended to turn the Clinton email archive released to the public by the [[United States Department of State|State Department]] into a searchable database for the campaign or a pro-Trump [[political action committee]].\n\nOn 14 December 2017, it was revealed that [[Robert Mueller]] had requested during the fall of 2017 that Cambridge Analytica turn over the emails of any of its employees who worked on the Trump campaign, as part of his [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mueller-sought-emails-of-trump-campaign-data-firm-1513296899 |title=Mueller Sought Emails of Trump Campaign Data Firm |last=Ballhaus |first=Rebecca |date=15 December 2017 |work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=15 December 2017 |issn=0099-9660 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, following disclosures that the company had improperly used the personal information of over 50 million Facebook users while working on Trump's presidential campaign, ''[[The Times of Israel]]'' reported that the company had used what Nix had called \"intelligence gathering\" from [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[State of Israel|Israeli]] companies as part of their efforts to influence the election results in Trump's favor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump campaign mined Facebook user data using Israeli 'intelligence gathering' |accessdate=21 March 2018 |work=The Times of Israel |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/trump-campaign-mined-facebook-user-data-using-israeli-intelligence-gathering/}}</ref>\n\n===Other countries===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2018}}\nCambridge Analytica's executives said in 2018 that the company had worked in more than 200 elections around the world, including in [[Trinidad and Tobago]], [[Nigeria]], the [[Czech Republic]], and [[Argentina]].<ref name=\"dailynation\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/How-Cambridge-Analytica-influenced-Kenyan-poll/1064-4349034-le7xbuz/index.html |title=Revealed: Cambridge Analytica says it worked for Uhuru |work=[[Daily Nation]] |date=20 March 2018 |location=Kenya | access-date=}}</ref> During the investigation it was admitted that the company has been contacted from a famous italian party to manage the electoral campaign in [[Italy]] but the name of the party was not revealed. \n\nIn the [[Philippines]], Cambridge Analytica was also involved in the 2016 presidential election with reports citing it helped [[Rodrigo Duterte]] win the race.<ref>{{cite web | last=Robles | first=Raissa | title=How Cambridge Analytica's parent company helped 'man of action' Rodrigo Duterte win the 2016 Philippines election | website=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=12 April 2018 | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/2140303/how-cambridge-analyticas-parent-company-helped-man-action | access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> Duterte's camp denied this association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/10/18/palace-denies-cambridge-analytica-involved-in-duterte-campaign|title=Palace denies Cambridge Analytica involved in Duterte campaign|last=Placido|first=Dharel|date=10 April 2018|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> The [[SCL Group]], Cambridge Analytica's parent company, claimed that it rebranded the politician's image to target voters who they found are swayed by qualities such as toughness and decisiveness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/cambridge-analytica-duterte-tough-guy-image-for-presidential-election-2018-4|title=Cambridge Analytica's parent company claimed it invented the tough guy image that got Rodrigo Duterte elected|last=Perper|first=Rosie|date=6 April 2018|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> During the election cycle, Facebook confirmed that its data of more 1 million Filipino users were improperly shared with the communications company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/199599-facebook-data-scandal-cambridge-analytica-help-duterte-win-philippine-elections|title=Did Cambridge Analytica use Filipinos' Facebook data to help Duterte win?|last=Gutierrez|first=Natashya|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2020, a release of more than 100,000 documents showed how Cambridge Analytica worked in 68 countries. A global infrastructure with operations to manipulate voters on \"an industrial scale\". The release of documents began on New Year\u2019s Day from an anonymous Twitter account called @HindsightFiles, that published material on elections in Malaysia, Kenya and Brazil (and next days so more countries). This documents came from Brittany Kaiser, an ex-Cambridge Analytica employee turned whistleblower, and were retrieved from her email accounts and hard drives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cadwalladr |first1=Carole |title=Fresh Cambridge Analytica leak 'shows global manipulation is out of control' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/04/cambridge-analytica-data-leak-global-election-manipulation |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Observer |publisher=The Guardian |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order and add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Data Propria]]\n* [[Catalist]]\n* [[Data dredging]]\n* [[The Groundwork]]\n* [[Herd behaviour]]\n* [[ORCA (computer system)]]\n* [[Project Alamo]]\n* [[Project Houdini]]\n* [[Project Narwhal]]\n* [[Predictive analytics]]\n* [[Right-wing politics]]\n* [[Sam Patten (political consultant)]]\n* [[Social media analytics]]\n* [[Tech companies in the New York metropolitan area]]\n* ''[[The Great Hack]]''\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Companies|United Kingdom|United States|Politics}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170710031857/https://cambridgeanalytica.org/ Archived website]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/news/series/cambridge-analytica-files The Cambridge Analytica Files], ongoing investigative reporting from ''[[The Observer]]''/''[[The Guardian]]'', beginning 17 March 2018, part of [https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/cambridge-analytica News: Cambridge Analytica] beginning a year earlier\n* [https://www.channel4.com/news/data-democracy-and-dirty-tricks-cambridge-analytica-uncovered-investigation-expose Data, Democracy and Dirty Tricks], [[Channel 4]]\n\n[[Category:Cambridge Analytica]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2018 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct technology companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Technology companies disestablished in 2018]]\n[[Category:Big data companies]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Data management]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Facebook]]\n[[Category:Political campaign techniques]]\n[[Category:Political campaign technology]]\n[[Category:Prediction]]\n[[Category:Transaction processing]]\n[[Category:2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]]\n[[Category:Consulting firms established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Consulting firms disestablished in 2018]]\n[[Category:Brexit]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013\u20132018 British political consulting firm}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Cambridge Analytica Ltd\n| logo = Cambridge Analytica logo.svg\n| logo_size = 125px\n| type = Subsidiary\n| location = London, UK\n| foundation = 2013\n| defunct = 1 May 2018\n| successor = [[Emerdata]]\n| key_people = [[Alexander Nix]] (CEO)<ref name=Sky2016>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/behind-the-scenes-at-donald-trumps-uk-digital-war-room-10626155 |title=Behind the scenes at Donald Trump's UK digital war room |last1=Cheshire |first1=Tom |date=21 October 2016 |publisher=[[Sky News]]}}</ref><br/>[[Robert Mercer (businessman)|Robert Mercer]] (investor)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cadwalladr |first1=Carole |title='I made Steve Bannon's psychological warfare tool': meet the data war whistleblower |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/data-war-whistleblower-christopher-wylie-faceook-nix-bannon-trump |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=18 March 2018 |date=18 March 2018 }}</ref><br/>[[Rebekah Mercer]] (investor)<br/>[[Steve Bannon]] (vice president, former)<ref>{{cite web |last=Illing |first=Sean |title=Cambridge Analytica, the shady data firm that might be a key Trump-Russia link, explained |website=Vox |date=16 October 2017 |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/10/16/15657512/cambridge-analytica-christopher-wylie-facebook-trump-russia | access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n| parent = [[SCL Group]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica LLC: Private Company Information |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=434877108 |website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Cambridge Analytica Ltd''' ('''CA''') was a British [[political consulting]] firm that combined [[misappropriation]] of [[digital assets]], [[data mining]], [[data broker]]age and [[data analysis]] with [[strategic communication]] during the electoral processes.<ref>{{cite web |last=Editorial |first=Reuters |title=Factbox: Who is Cambridge Analytica and what did it do? |website=U.S. |date=20 March 2018 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-cambridge-analytica-factbox/factbox-who-is-cambridge-analytica-and-what-did-it-do-idUSKBN1GW07F | access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Exposed: Undercover secrets of Trump's data firm |website=Channel 4 News |date=20 March 2018 |url=https://www.channel4.com/news/exposed-undercover-secrets-of-donald-trump-data-firm-cambridge-analytica | access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref> It was started in 2013<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OHm5yAEACAAJ&dq=Cambridge+Analytica.+Il+potere+segreto,+la+gestione+del+consenso+e+la+fine+della+propaganda.|title=Cambridge Analytica. Il potere segreto, la gestione del consenso e la fine della propaganda.|last=Tirino|first=Nazzareno|publisher=Libellula Edizioni|year=2019|isbn=9788867355129|location=Lecce - Italy|pages=109|language=Italian|trans-title=Cambridge Analytica. The secret power to manage consensus to the end of propaganda.}}</ref> as an offshoot of the [[SCL Group]]. After closing operations with legal proceedings including bankruptcy, members of the SCL Group have been continuing operations under the legal entity [[Emerdata]] Limited.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90381366/the-mysterious-afterlife-of-cambridge-analytica-and-its-trove-of-data|title=The strange afterlife of Cambridge Analytica and the mysterious fate of its data|date=26 July 2018|work=Fast Company|access-date=16 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=issenberg/> The company closed operations in 2018 in the course of the [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal]], although related firms still exist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44807093|title=Cambridge Analytica staff set up new firm|date=12 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=24 December 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe company was partly owned by the family of [[Robert Mercer (businessman)|Robert Mercer]], an American [[hedge-fund]] manager who supports many politically conservative causes.<ref name=\"issenberg\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/features/2015-11-12/is-the-republican-party-s-killer-data-app-for-real- |first=Sasha |last=Issenberg |authorlink=Sasha Issenberg |title=Cruz-Connected Data Miner Aims to Get Inside U.S. Voters' Heads |publisher=Bloomberg |date=12 November 2015 |accessdate=2 February 2016 }}</ref><ref name=politico/> The firm maintained offices in London, New York City, and Washington, DC.<ref name=ca/> CEO [[Alexander Nix]] has said CA was involved in 44 US political races in 2014.<ref name=wpost/> In 2015, CA performed data analysis services for [[Ted Cruz's presidential campaign]].<ref name=politico/> In 2016, CA worked for [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's presidential campaign]]<ref>{{cite journal |date=10 October 2016 |title=Silent Partners |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |page=44 |author=Alex Altman}}</ref> as well as for [[Leave.EU]] (one of the organisations campaigning in the United Kingdom's [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on European Union membership]]). CA's role in those campaigns has been controversial and is the subject of ongoing criminal investigations in both countries.<ref name=\"Confessore\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/us/politics/cambridge-analytica.html |title=Data Firm Says 'Secret Sauce' Aided Trump; Many Scoff |last=Confessore |first=Nicholas |date=6 March 2017 |work=The New York Times|access-date=7 March 2017 |last2=Hakim |first2=Danny |issn=0362-4331 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/donald-trump-und-die-daten-ingenieure-endlich-eine-erklaerung-mit-der-alles-sinn-ergibt-a-1124439.html |title=Ich ganz allein habe Trump ins Amt gebracht |last2=Schnack |first2=Thies |date=6 December 2016 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |last1=Reinbold |first1=Fabian }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/mar/04/cambridge-analytics-data-brexit-trump |title=Watchdog to launch inquiry into misuse of data in politics |last=Doward |first=Jamie |date=4 March 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=14 June 2017 |last2=Cadwalladr |first2=Carole |issn=0261-3077 |last3=Gibbs |first3=Alice }}</ref> Political scientists question CA's claims about the effectiveness of its methods of targeting voters.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2018/03/23/four-and-a-half-reasons-not-to-worry-that-cambridge-analytica-skewed-the-2016-election/ |title=Analysis {{!}} Four and a half reasons not to worry that Cambridge Analytica skewed the 2016 election|last=Trump|first=Kris-Stella|date=23 March 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=23 March 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, multiple media outlets broke news of Cambridge Analytica's business practices. ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Observer]]'' reported that the company had [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data breach|acquired and used personal data about Facebook users]] from an external researcher who had told [[Facebook]] he was collecting it for academic purposes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions|last=Rosenberg|first=Matthew|date=17 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=4 March 2019|last2=Confessore|first2=Nicholas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cadwalladr|first3=Carole}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' aired undercover investigative videos showing Nix boasting about using prostitutes, bribery [[sting operation]]s, and [[honey trapping|honey traps]] to discredit politicians on whom it conducted [[opposition research]], and saying that the company \"ran all of (Donald Trump's) digital campaign\". In response to the media reports, the [[Information Commissioner's Office]] (ICO) of the UK pursued a [[warrant (law)|warrant]] to search the company's servers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/92390/cambridge-analytica-ceo-admits-to-dirty-tricks |title=Cambridge Analytica CEO 'admits to dirty tricks' |work=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-20/cambridge-analytica-used-disappearing-emails-in-campaign-report |title=Cambridge Analytica Boasted of Disappearing Emails in Campaigns |date=20 March 2018 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref> Facebook banned Cambridge Analytica from advertising on its platform, saying that it had been deceived.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html |title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions |last=Rosenberg |first=Matthew |date=17 March 2018 |work=The New York Times|access-date=17 March 2018 |last2=Confessore |first2=Nicholas |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Cadwalladr |first3=Carole }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election |title=Revealed: 50 million Facebook profiles harvested for Cambridge Analytica in major data breach |date=17 March 2018 |accessdate=18 March 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |first1=Carole |last1=Cadwalladr |first2=Emma |last2=Graham-Harrison }}</ref> On 23 March 2018, the [[High Court of Justice|British High Court]] granted the ICO a warrant to search Cambridge Analytica's London offices.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/23/uk-high-court-grants-cambridge-analytica-search-warrant-to-ico.html |title=UK High Court grants Cambridge Analytica search warrant to ICO |last=CNBC |date=23 March 2018 |work=CNBC|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe personal data of up to 87 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/04/technology/mark-zuckerberg-testify-congress.html |title=\"Facebook Says Cambridge Analytica Harvested Data of Up to 87 Million Users\" in ''The New York Times'' |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref> Facebook users were acquired via the 270,000 Facebook users who used a Facebook app called \"This Is Your Digital Life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/apr/10/facebook-notify-users-data-harvested-cambridge-analytica|title=How to check whether Facebook shared your data with Cambridge Analytica|first=Alex|last=Hern|date=10 April 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> By giving this third-party app permission to acquire their data, back in 2015, this also gave the app access to information on the user's friends network; this resulted in the data of about 87&nbsp;million users, the majority of whom had not explicitly given Cambridge Analytica permission to access their data, being collected. The app developer breached Facebook's [[terms of service]] by giving the data to Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.recode.net/2018/3/17/17134072/facebook-cambridge-analytica-trump-explained-user-data |title=Here's how Facebook allowed Cambridge Analytica to get data for 50 million users |work=Recode|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2018, Cambridge Analytica and its parent company filed for [[insolvency|insolvency proceedings]] and closed operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/05/02/cambridge-analytica-is-shutting-down-following-facebook-scandal/ |title=Cambridge Analytica is shutting down following Facebook scandal |last=Lumb |first=David |date=2 May 2018 |work=[[Engadget]] |access-date=2 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica and Scl Elections Commence Insolvency Proceedings and Release Results of Independent Investigation into Recent Allegations |url=https://ca-commercial.com/news/cambridge-analytica-and-scl-elections-commence-insolvency-proceedings-and-release-results-3 |website=CA Commercial |publisher=Cambridge Analytica |accessdate=2 May 2018 |language=en |date=2 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502183542/https://ca-commercial.com/news/cambridge-analytica-and-scl-elections-commence-insolvency-proceedings-and-release-results-3 |archive-date=2 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Alexander Tayler, a former director for Cambridge Analytica, was appointed director of [[Emerdata]] on 28 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nichols|first1=Shaun|title=Cambridge Analytica dismantled for good? Nope: It just changed its name to Emerdata|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/05/02/cambridge_analytica_shutdown/|accessdate=2 May 2018|publisher=The Register|date=2 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Rebekah Mercer]], [[Jennifer Mercer]], [[Alexander Nix]] and {{ill|Johnson Chun Shun Ko|zh|\u9ad8\u632f\u9806}}, who has links to American businessman [[Erik Prince]], are in leadership positions at Emerdata.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/cambridge-analytica-executives-and-mercer-family-launch-emerdata-2018-3|title=The power players behind Cambridge Analytica have set up a mysterious new data company|last=Ghosh|first=Shona|date=2018-03-21|website=Business Insider Australia|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/05514098/officers|title=SCL GROUP LIMITED - Officers (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCambridge Analytica (SCL USA) was incorporated in January 2015 with its registered office in Westferry Circus, London and just one staff member, its director and CEO Alexander James Ashburner Nix (also appointed in January 2015).<ref>{{cite web |title=Filing record for Cambridge Analytica (UK) Limited \u2013 Company number 09375920 |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09375920 |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |publisher=Companies house, UK |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> Nix is also the director of nine similar companies sharing the same registered offices in London, including Firecrest technologies, [[Emerdata]] and six SCL Group companies including \"SCL elections limited\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexander James Ashburner NIX \u2013 Appoinments |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/YEplkqBMfc6Rp3dbPs57pN3aqO4/appointments |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |publisher=Companies house, UK Government |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> [[Nigel Oakes]] founded [[SCL Group]], which is the parent company of Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/old-etonian-smoothie-fails-to-buff-indonesian-leaders-image-711373.html |title=Old Etonian smoothie fails to buff Indonesian leader's image |author= |date=6 August 2000 |website=independent.co.uk |accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nPublicly, SCL Group called itself a \"global election management agency\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scl.cc/ |title=SCL Group \u2013 Home |website=scl.cc |access-date=9 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208184806/http://scl.cc/ |archive-date=8 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Politico'' reported it was known for involvement \"in [[military deception|military disinformation]] campaigns to social media branding and [[voter]] targeting\".<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/ted-cruz-donor-for-data-119813 |first=Kenneth P.|last=Vogel |authorlink=Kenneth P. Vogel |title=Cruz partners with donor's 'psychographic' firm |publisher=[[Politico]] |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=27 December 2015 }}</ref> SCL's involvement in the political world has been primarily in the developing world where it has been used by the military and politicians to study and manipulate public opinion and political will. ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' writer Sharon Weinberger compared one of SCL's hypothetical test scenarios to fomenting a coup.<ref name=politico/>\n\nCambridge Analytica was founded by conservative businessmen [[Steve Bannon]] and Robert Mercer. A minimum of 15 million dollars has been invested into the company by Mercer, according to ''The New York Times''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/us/cambridge-analytica-alexander-nix.html |first=Matthew |last=Rosenberg |title=Cambridge Analytica, Trump-Tied Political Firm, Offered to Entrap Politicians |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2018 }}</ref> Bannon's stake in the company was estimated at 1 to 5 million dollars, but he divested his holdings in April 2017 as required by his role as [[White House Chief Strategist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article200917134.html |first1=Ben |last1=Wieder |first2=Anita |last2=Kumar |title=Bannon sold Cambridge Analytica stake, fined for late ethics report |work=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]] |date=20 February 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> In March 2018, Jennifer Mercer and [[Rebekah Mercer]] became directors of Emerdata limited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Appoinment as directors |date=16 March 2018 |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/10911848/filing-history |publisher=Companies house |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\nIn March 2018 it became public by [[Whistleblower]] [[Christopher Wylie]], that Cambridge Analytica's first activities were founded on a data set, which its parent company SCL bought 2014 from a company named Global Science Research founded by [[Aleksandr Kogan]]<ref>Hannes Grassegger und Mikael Krogerus, in: [[Tages-Anzeiger]]: [https://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/ausland/europa/Ich-habe-nur-gezeigt-dass-es-die-Bombe-gibt/story/17474918 \u00abIch habe nur gezeigt, dass es die Bombe gibt\u00bb (I only showed, that there is a bomb)], 3. 20th 2018</ref> who worked as a psychologist at Cambridge.\n\nPer the Associated Press, [[Data Propria]], a data analysis firm launched May 2018, is run by former officials at Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/ap-trump-2020-working-with-ex-cambridge-analytica-staffers/2018/06/15/ebdde7e2-70c0-11e8-b4d8-eaf78d4c544c_story.html |title=AP: Trump 2020 working with ex-Cambridge Analytica staffers |author=Jeff Horwitz|date=15 June 2018 |work=Associated Press |via=WashingtonPost.com |access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmagazine.com/data-propria-heir-to-cambridge-analytica-working-for-rnc-possibly-trump-campaign/article/774206/ |title=Data Propria, heir to Cambridge Analytica, working for RNC, possibly Trump campaign |author=Teri Robinson|date=18 June 2018 |website=scmagazine.com |access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.accesswire.com/500425/CloudCommerce-Launches-Data-Propria-Inc-Its-New-Data-Analytics-Division |title=CloudCommerce Launches Data Propria, Inc., Its New Data Analytics Division |author=|date=29 May 2018 |website=accesswire.com |access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, several former Cambridge Analytica staff launched [[Auspex International]], a company intended to influence politics and society in Africa and the Middle East.<ref>https://www.wired.co.uk/article/wired-awake-130718</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44807093</ref><ref>https://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/3035777/cambridge-analyticas-latest-wants-your-google-search-history</ref><ref>https://boingboing.net/2018/07/11/zombie-analytica.html</ref><ref>https://www.ft.com/content/1c8a5e74-6901-11e8-8cf3-0c230fa67aec</ref><ref>https://www.ft.com/content/d92164fe-8514-11e8-96dd-fa565ec55929</ref>\n\n==Methods==\nCA's data analysis methods were to a large degree based on the academic work of Michal Kosinski. In 2008, Kosinski had joined the Psychometrics Centre of [[Cambridge University]] where he then developed with his colleagues a profiling system using general online data, [[Facebook]]-likes, and [[smartphone]] data.<ref name=\"Magazin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dasmagazin.ch/2016/12/03/ich-habe-nur-gezeigt-dass-es-die-bombe-gibt/ |author=Mikael Krogerus, Hannes Grassegger |title=Ich habe nur gezeigt, dass es die Bombe gibt |publisher=[[Das Magazin]] |language=German |date=3 December 2016 |accessdate=7 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.1218772110 |pmid=23479631 |title=Private traits and attributes are predictable from digital records of human behavior |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=110 |issue=15 |pages=5802\u20135805 |year=2013 |last1=Kosinski |first1=M |last2=Stillwell |first2=D |last3=Graepel |first3=T|pmc=3625324 |bibcode=2013PNAS..110.5802K }}</ref> He showed that with a limited number of \"likes\", people can be analysed better than friends or relatives can do and that individual psychological targeting is a powerful tool to influence people.<ref name=\"Magazin\"/>\n\nCA would collect data on voters using sources such as [[demographics]], [[consumer behaviour]], [[Computer and network surveillance|internet activity]], and other public and private sources. According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', CA used psychological data derived from millions of Facebook users, largely without users' permission or knowledge.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/11/senator-ted-cruz-president-campaign-facebook-user-data |author=Davies, H |title=Ted Cruz using firm that harvested data on millions of unwitting Facebook users |work=The Guardian |date=11 December 2015 |accessdate=7 February 2016 }}</ref> Another source of information was the \"Cruz Crew\" [[mobile app]] that tracked physical movements and contacts and according to the [[Associated Press]], invaded personal data more than previous presidential campaign apps.<ref name=\"ap0216\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/2db0fc93cf664a63909e26e708e91c67|title=Cruz app data collection helps campaign read minds of voters|last1=Biesecker|first1=Michael|date=11 February 2016|work=AP News|accessdate=13 February 2016|agency=[[Associated Press]]|last2=Bykowicz|first2=Julie}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=Today in the United States we have somewhere close to four or five thousand data points on every individual ... So we model the personality of every adult across the United States, some 230 million people.|author=Alexander Nix, chief executive of Cambridge Analytica |source=October 2016.<ref name=Sky2016/>}}[[File:Web Summit 2017 - Centre Stage Day 3 SAM 7454 (24415941378).jpg|thumb|left|Cambridge Analytica CEO [[Alexander Nix]] speaking in November 2017.]]\n\nThe company claimed to use \"data enhancement and [[audience segmentation]] techniques\" providing \"[[psychographic]] analysis\" for a \"deeper knowledge of the target audience\". The company uses the [[Big Five personality traits|Big Five model]] of personality <ref name=wpost/><ref name=ca/> Using what it calls \"[[behavioral targeting|behavioral]] [[microtargeting]]\" the company indicates that it can predict \"[[needs]]\" of subjects and how these needs may change over time. Services then can be individually targeted for the benefit of its clients from the political arena, governments, and companies providing \"a better and more actionable view of their key audiences.\" According to [[Sasha Issenberg]], CA indicates that it can tell things about an individual he might not even know about himself.<ref name=issenberg/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/passionateeye/episodes/the-persuasion-machine-of-silicon-valley |agency=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation and British Broadcasting Corporation |title=The Persuasion Machine of Silicon Valley |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=17 February 2018 |accessdate=17 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nCA derived much of its personality data on [[online survey]]s which it conducts on an ongoing basis. For each political client, the firm would narrow voter segments from 32 different [[personality style]]s it attributes to every adult in the United States. The personality data would inform the tone of the language used in ad messages or voter contact scripts, while additional data is used to determine voters' stances on particular issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/campaign-trail/cruz-s-data-company-works-night-3m-payout/302515 |title=Cruz's Data Company Works into the Night After Big $3 Million Payout |website=[[Advertising Age]]| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe data would get updated with monthly surveys, asking about political preferences and how people get the information they use to make decisions. It also covered consumer topics about different [[brand engagement|brands and preferred products]], building up an image of how someone shops as much as how they vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dcinno.streetwise.co/2016/02/08/political-ad-targeting-cambridge-analytica-adtech |title=Inside the Tech That Puts Political Ads on Your Screen |website=DC Inno| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===''Channel 4 News'' investigation===\n''[[Channel 4 News]]'', a news programme broadcast by the [[Public service broadcasting in the United Kingdom|British public service]] [[Channel 4]], conducted a four-month investigation into Cambridge Analytica starting in November 2017. An undercover reporter posed as a potential customer for Cambridge Analytica, hoping to help [[Sri Lanka]]n candidates get elected. Video footage from this operation was published on 19 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.channel4.com/news/cambridge-analytica-revealed-trumps-election-consultants-filmed-saying-they-use-bribes-and-sex-workers-to-entrap-politicians-investigation |title=Revealed: Trump's election consultants filmed saying they use bribes and sex workers to entrap politicians |work=Channel 4 News |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> From the footage, Cambridge Analytica executives say they worked on over 200 elections across the world.<ref name=\"dailynation\"/> Alexander Nix was recorded in this investigation, talking \"unguardedly about the company's practices\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Cadwalladr |first=Carole |authorlink1=Carole Cadwalladr |last2=Graham-Harrison |first2=Emma |title=The Cambridge Analytica Files : 'I made Steve Bannon's psychological warfare tool': meet the data war whistleblower |date=17 March 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/data-war-whistleblower-christopher-wylie-faceook-nix-bannon-trump |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=19 March 2018 }}</ref> Nix said that his company uses honey traps, bribery stings, and prostitutes, for opposition research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/92390/cambridge-analytica-ceo-admits-to-dirty-tricks |title=Cambridge Analytica CEO 'admits to dirty tricks' |work=The Week |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> For example, Nix offered to discredit political opponents in Sri Lanka with suggestive videos using \"beautiful Ukrainian girls\" and offers of bribes, even if the opponents did not accept the offers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/british-firm-sends-girls-to-entrap-politicians-wpthxqhwv |title=Cambridge Analytica sends 'girls' to entrap politicians |date=20 March 2018 |work=The Times}}</ref> He also said he uses \"Israeli companies\" to entrap political opponents with bribes and sex, the Wall Street Journal confirmed that it was referring to [[Psy-Group]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-intelligence-company-formed-venture-with-trump-campaign-firm-cambridge-analytica-1527030765|title=Israeli Intelligence Company Formed Venture With Trump Campaign Firm Cambridge Analytica|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=23 May 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=9 June 2019|last2=Ballhaus|first2=Rebecca|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"Nast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/05/the-dark-truth-about-cambridge-analyticas-ties-to-trumpworld|title=The Dark Truth About Cambridge Analytica's Ties to Trumpworld|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref>  [[Joel Zamel|Zamel]] signed a memorandum of understanding for Psy-Group with Cambridge Analytica on 14 December 2016.<ref name=\"Nast\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-intelligence-company-formed-venture-with-trump-campaign-firm-cambridge-analytica-1527030765|title=Israeli Intelligence Company Formed Venture With Trump Campaign Firm Cambridge Analytica|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=23 May 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=5 June 2019|last2=Ballhaus|first2=Rebecca|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-intelligence-company-formed-venture-with-trump-campaign-firm-cambridge-analytica-1527030765|title=Israeli Intelligence Company Formed Venture With Trump Campaign Firm Cambridge Analytica|last=Tau|first=Byron|date=23 May 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=9 June 2019|last2=Ballhaus|first2=Rebecca|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nCambridge Analytica said that the video footage was \"edited and scripted to grossly misrepresent\" the recorded conversations and company's business practices. Nix said that he had \"entertained a series of ludicrous hypothetical scenarios\", but insisted his company does not engage in entrapment or bribery.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pham |first1=Sherisse |last2=Riley |first2=Charles |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/03/20/technology/cambridge-analytica-channel-4-report/index.html |title=Cambridge Analytica responds after CEO filmed discussing bribery and entrapment |publisher=CNN |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the third part of the series, Nix also said that Cambridge Analytica \"ran all the digital campaign\" for Trump. Nix stated they used communications that would be self-destructive, leaving no incriminating evidence. After the news segment was broadcast, the board of Cambridge Analytica suspended Nix as chief executive officer. The company also released a statement that the allegations did not represent the ethics of the company, and an independent entity would investigate Nix's statements.<ref name=\"Lanxon\">{{cite news |last=Lanxon |first=Nate |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-20/cambridge-analytica-used-disappearing-emails-in-campaign-report |title=Cambridge Analytica Boasted of Disappearing Emails in Campaigns |work=Bloomberg |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe investigation also raised questions regarding campaign finance law. During the 2016 election, the company was employed both by Trump's campaign and Robert Mercer's [[Make America Number 1]] Super [[Political Action Committee|PAC]] which supported Trump. While PACs are not limited in the amount of funds they can spend on behalf of a candidate, they are not allowed to coordinate strategy with the campaigns they are supporting. Nix's statements in the recorded video describe how the Trump campaign itself could \"take the high road\" and \"stay clean\", while the negative attacks were handled by the firm and the Super PAC, in a way which makes it \"unattributable, untrackable\". These statements potentially suggested unlawful coordination between Trump's campaign and the PAC, although Cambridge Analytica has denied this.<ref name=\"Bump\">{{cite news |last=Bump |first=Philip |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/03/20/a-new-undercover-video-raises-significant-questions-about-cambridge-analyticas-elections-work/ |title=A new undercover video raises significant questions about Cambridge Analytica's elections work |work=The Washington Post |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Assessment of impact===\n[[File:Cambridge Analytica protest Parliament Square4.jpg|thumb|Canadian whistleblower [[Christopher Wylie]] who was the former director of research at Cambridge Analytica]]\nPolitical scientists have been highly skeptical of claims made by Cambridge Analytica about the effectiveness of its microtargeting of voters (microtargeting refers to the process of \"analyzing data to predict the behavior, interests, and opinions held by specific groups of people and then serving them the messages they're most likely to respond to\").<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/20/17138854/cambridge-analytica-facebook-data-trump-campaign-psychographic-microtargeting |title=Cambridge Analytica's Facebook data abuse shouldn't get credit for Trump |work=The Verge|access-date=20 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/03/27/the-reclusive-hedge-fund-tycoon-behind-the-trump-presidency |title=The Reclusive Hedge-Fund Tycoon Behind the Trump Presidency |last=Mayer |first=Jane |date=17 March 2017 |work=The New Yorker|access-date=20 March 2018 |issn=0028-792X }}</ref> Political scientists note that access to digital data is not going to provide significantly more information than from public voter databases, and the digital data has limited value over time as the preferences of voters change.<ref name=\":1\" /> Political scientists also note that it is hard to infer political values from personality traits, which means that it is easy to mistarget the messages that are sent to voters with specific personality traits.<ref name=\":1\" /> Research discussed by [[Brendan Nyhan]] of Dartmouth College showed that it is extremely hard to alter voters' preferences because many likely voters are already committed partisans; as a result, it is easier to simply mobilize partisan voters.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/13/upshot/fake-news-and-bots-may-be-worrisome-but-their-political-power-is-overblown.html |title=Fake News and Bots May Be Worrisome, but Their Political Power Is Overblown |last=Nyhan |first=Brendan |date=13 February 2018 |work=The New York Times|access-date=20 March 2018 |issn=0362-4331 }}</ref> Tufts University political scientist Eitan Hersh, who has published on microtargeting in campaigns, has expressed strong skepticism about Cambridge Analytica's methods and their purported effectiveness, saying \"Every claim about psychographics etc made by or about [Cambridge Analytica] is BS.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/03/19/cambridge-analytica |title=Cambridge Analytica Was Doing Marketing, Not Black Magic |date=19 March 2018 |work=Reason|access-date=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, CA claimed that it has psychological profiles of 220 million US citizens based on 5,000 separate data sets.<ref name=\"InkJun2017\">{{cite news |url=https://fountainink.in/reportage/aadhaar-in-the-hand-of-spies- |title=Aadhaar in the hand of spies Big Data, global surveillance state and the identity project |author=Govind Krishnan V. |date=3 June 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |publisher=Fountain Ink Magazine }}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that CA had exaggerated its capabilities: \"Cambridge executives now concede that the company never used psychographics in the Trump campaign.\"<ref name=\"Confessore\" /> Trump aides have also disputed CA's role in the campaign, describing it as \"modest\" and noting that none of the company's efforts involved psychographics.<ref name=\"Confessore\" />\n\nAccording to an aide and consultant for Ted Cruz's presidential campaign, their campaign stopped using CA after its psychographic models failed to identify likely Cruz supporters. The Cruz campaign ceased access to all of Cambridge's data after the [[2016 South Carolina Republican primary|South Carolina Republican primary]] on 20 February 2016 when Cruz came in third after Trump and Rubio.<ref name=Confessore/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/south-carolina-nevada-2016-election/ted-cruz-speaks-after-south-carolina-primary/ |title=Ted Cruz on South Carolina Primary |date=20 February 2016 |work=The New York Times|access-date=21 March 2018 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Privacy issues===\nThe use of [[personal data]] collected without knowledge or permission to establish sophisticated models of user's personalities raises ethical and [[Privacy concerns with social networking services|privacy issue]]s.<ref name=guardian/> CA operated out of the United States; its operations would be illegal in Europe with its stricter [[privacy law]]s.<ref name=ap0216/> While Cruz was outspoken about protecting personal information from the government, his database of CA has been described as \"political-voter [[surveillance]]\".<ref name=\"ap0216\" />\n\nRegarding CA's use of Facebook users, a speaker for CA indicated that these users gave permission when signing up with the provider, while Facebook declared that \"misleading people or misusing information\" is in violation of Facebook's policies.<ref name=guardian/> In 2015, Facebook indicated that it was investigating the matter.<ref name=guardian/> In March 2018, Facebook announced that it had suspended the accounts of Strategic Communication Laboratories for failing to delete data on Facebook users that had been improperly collected.<ref>{{cite news |first=Elizabeth |last=Dwoskin |date=16 March 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2018/03/16/facebook-bans-trump-campaigns-data-analytics-firm-for-taking-user-data/ |title=Facebook bans Trump campaign's data analytics firm for taking user data |work=[[The Washington Post]] |quote=Facebook said it was suspending the accounts of Strategic Communication Laboratories, the parent company of Cambridge Analytica, as well as the accounts of a University of Cambridge psychologist Aleksandr Kogan, and Christopher Wylie of Eunoia Technologies, Inc. Cambridge Analytica, a firm specializing in using online data to create voter personality profiles in order to target them with messages, ran data operations for Trump's presidential campaign. }}</ref>\n\nAlexander Nix suggested that data collection and microtargeting benefits the voters \u2013 because they receive messages about issues they care about. However, [[digital rights]] protection groups raised concerns that private information is collected, stored, and shared while individuals are \"left in the dark about [it]\" and have no control.<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/2016-election-day/trump-campaign-pays-millions-overseas-big-data-firm-n677321 |first=Kate |last=Brannelly |title=Trump Campaign Pays Millions to Overseas Big Data Firm |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=4 November 2016 |accessdate=5 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nSignificant backlash against Facebook came to light in March 2018, resulting in controversy as well as a $37&nbsp;billion drop in the [[market capitalization]] of Facebook, as of 20 March.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43462423 |title=Facebook's value falls $37bn amid backlash |date=19 March 2018 |publisher=BBC |access-date=20 March 2018 }}</ref> Due to the scandal of enabling monetization of Facebook personal data, one assessment was that only 41% of Facebook users trust the company.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Nelson Granados |title=Transparency: How Facebook Can Recover From The Cambridge Analytica Crisis |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nelsongranados/2018/03/26/transparency-how-facebook-can-recover-from-the-cambridge-analytica-crisis/ |work=Forbes |accessdate=26 March 2018 |date=26 March 2018}}</ref> On 26 March, the US [[Federal Trade Commission]] announced it is \"conducting an open investigation of Facebook Inc's privacy practices following the disclosure that 50 million users' data got into the hands of political consultancy Cambridge Analytica.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. FTC investigating Facebook's privacy practices |url=http://news.trust.org/item/20180326145505-6je9o/ |work=Reuters |date=26 March 2018 |quote=If the FTC finds Facebook violated terms of the consent decree, it has the power to fine the company thousands of dollars a day per violation, which could add up to billions of dollars. \"The FTC takes very seriously recent press reports raising substantial concerns about the privacy practices of Facebook. Today, the FTC is confirming that it has an open non-public investigation into these practices,\" Tom Pahl, acting director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection, said in a statement.}}</ref> In March 2019 Facebook acknowledged it had concerns about \u201cimproper data-gathering practices\u201d by CA, months before the previously reported onset-of-alert at December 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/mar/21/facebook-knew-of-cambridge-analytica-data-misuse-earlier-than-reported-court-filing|title=Facebook acknowledges concerns over Cambridge Analytica emerged earlier than reported|last=Wong|first=Julia Carrie|date=22 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=22 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Elections==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn Australia, Cambridge Analytica set up an office. Allan Lorraine, a friend of Alexander Tayler who was a former director for Cambridge Analytica and later appointed director of [[Emerdata]], set up SCL (the parent company of Cambridge Analytica) in Australia. Representatives of Cambridge Analytica had a private dinner with [[Dan Tehan]] when he was then the minister responsible for cyber security, and [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal party]] executives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-21/cambridge-analytica-in-australia/9570432|title=Cambridge Analytica's Australian office is a former used-car salesman's house|last=McGhee|first=political reporter Ashlynne|date=2018-03-21|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> The business name \"Cambridge Analytica\" was registered in Australia to the Lorraine Family Trust in June 2015. SCL Group, promoted Mr Lorraine online as its head of Australian operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/consumer-affairs/friend-of-a-friend-australian-link-to-cambridge-analytica-20180321-p4z5jb.html|title='Friend of a friend': Australian link to Cambridge Analytica|last=Begley|first=Patrick|date=2018-03-21|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Alexander Nix spoke at an Australian data-driven advertising conference run by the [[Association for Data-driven Marketing and Advertising]] and met with Liberal Party officials.<ref name=\"sbs.com.au\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/trump-s-data-consultant-to-meet-aust-govt|title=Trump's data consultant to meet Aust govt|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adma.com.au/people/alexander-nix|title=Alexander Nix|date=2017-01-10|website=ADMA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Cambridge Analytica was scoping both political as well as commercial work in Australia.<ref name=\"sbs.com.au\"/> Cambridge Analytica's managing director of political operations said in a video recorded by Channel 4 that \"We\u2019ve done it in Mexico, we\u2019ve done it in Malaysia, we\u2019re now moving into Brazil, Australia, China.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australian-parties-deny-using-data-firm-cambridge-analytica|title=Australian parties deny using data firm Cambridge Analytica|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\nMore than 310,000 Australian Facebook users were among the millions globally who may have had their information improperly shared with Cambridge Analytica.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/facebook-says-310-000-australian-users-may-have-been-affected-by-cambridge-analytica-scandal-20180405-p4z7tm.html|title=Facebook says 310,000 Australian users may have been affected by Cambridge Analytica scandal|last=Clun|first=Rachel|date=2018-04-04|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/311127-australian-facebook-users-may-harvested-data-passed-cambridge-analytica-509188|title=Up to 311,127 Australian Facebook users may have had harvested data passed on to Cambridge Analytica|last=Burrowes|first=Tim|date=2018-04-04|website=Mumbrella|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n===India===\nIn India, Cambridge Analytica had been used by the [[Indian National Congress]] (INC) to carry out \"in-depth electorate analysis\" and influence voters, including in the [[2010 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2010 elections]] to the [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Punit |first1=Itika |title=Cambridge Analytica's parent firm proposed a massive political machine for India's 2014 elections |url=https://qz.com/1239561/cambridge-analyticas-parent-firm-proposed-a-massive-political-machine-for-indias-2014-elections/ |accessdate=6 June 2018 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Quartz |date=28 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"caofficialpol\">{{cite web |title=Our Political data driven campaigns|publisher=Cambridge Analytica official website }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Punit |first=Itika Sharma |title=Why Cambridge Analytica was eager to play in the world's largest democracy |url=https://qz.com/1233040/cambridge-analytica-was-eager-to-play-in-the-worlds-largest-democracy/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> 355 Indian Facebook users installed a Cambridge Analytica app, exposing the data of 562,455 users.<ref>{{cite web |last=Punit |first=Itika Sharma |title=Facebook admits Cambridge Analytica may have accessed the data of over 560,000 users in India \u2013 Quartz |url=https://qz.com/1245515/facebook-admits-cambridge-analytica-may-have-accessed-the-data-of-over-560000-users-in-india |website=Quartz |accessdate=5 April 2018 |date=5 April 2018}}</ref> In addition, [[Christopher Wylie]], the Cambridge Analytica [[whistleblower]], alleged that the company had offices and staff in India, and that the INC party was a major client.<ref>{{cite news |title='Believe' Congress was a client, says Cambridge Analytica whistleblower |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/believe-congress-was-a-client-says-cambridge-analytica-whistleblower/articleshow/63491061.cms |accessdate=23 April 2018 |publisher=[[The Economic Times]] |date=27 March 2018}}</ref> A [[BBC]] documentary clip showing a poster of the INC in Wylie's office went viral in India, sparking accusations that the company was manipulating both mainstream and social media in order to subvert Indian voters away from the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and towards the INC as part of a [[neocolonial]] effort to undermine Indian politics in favor of vested interests.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC documentary clip goes viral, shows Congress poster in office of Cambridge Analytica's ex-CEO Alexander Nix |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-bbc-documentary-clip-goes-viral-shows-congress-poster-in-office-of-cambridge-analytica-s-ex-ceo-alexander-nix-2598837 |website=[[DNA India]] |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> In early 2018 Cambridge Analytica made a 50-page proposal for the INC for both the upcoming [[2019 Indian general election|2019 general election in India]] and their upcoming electoral campaign for the Indian states of [[Karnataka]], Chhattisgarh and [[Madhya Pradesh]] state elections in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica made 2019 roadmap for Congress; party denies any deal |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/cambridge-analytica-made-2019-roadmap-for-congress-party-denies-any-deal/articleshow/63823483.cms |website=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> The Indian National Congress, however, lost the elections by a sizable margin, winning not even enough seats to be the official opposition party in India.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Kenya===\nCA ran campaigns in secret during Kenya's [[2013 Kenyan general election|2013]] and [[2017 Kenyan general election|2017 elections]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dahir |first1=Abdi Latif |title=\"We'd stage the whole thing\": Cambridge Analytica filmed boasting of its role in Kenya's polls |url=https://qz.com/1233084/channel-4-news-films-cambridge-analytica-execs-saying-they-staged-kenya-uhuru-kenyatta-elections/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> In 2018, a CA employee said that his predecessor at the company had been found dead in his hotel room in Kenya while working on [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]'s 2013 campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lang'at |first1=Patrick |title=Exposed: Analytica staff died in Kenya |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Cambridge-Analytica-staff-Dan-Mure-an-died-in-Kenya/1064-4351058-11gicwcz/index.html |accessdate=21 March 2018 |work=Daily Nation |date=21 March 2018 |language=en-UK}}</ref> The company claimed on its website to have conducted a survey of 47,000 Kenyans during the 2013 elections in order to understand \"key national and local political issues, levels of trust in key politicians, voting behaviours/intentions, and preferred information channels\". According to verified sources, CA worked with 360 Media, a company formed by [[Simon Gicharu]] (founder of [[Mount Kenya University]]) and Tom Mshindi (Editor-in-Chief of [[Nation Media Group]]). 360 Media developed online campaigns in the 2017 Kenyan elections portraying \"Raila Odinga as a blood-thirsty individual who is also sympathetic to Al-Shabaab and having no development agenda,\" whilst portraying the incumbent President Kenyatta as \"tough on terrorism, and being good for the economy.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Matende |first1=David |title=Media, like false preachers |url=http://nairobilawmonthly.com/index.php/2018/06/05/media-like-false-preachers |accessdate=6 August 2018 |work=Nairobi Law Monthly |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the revelations in March 2018, where CA staff boasted of their power in Kenya, opposition figures called for an investigation. Norman Magaya, an official of the [[National Super Alliance]], accused CA and the ruling [[Jubilee Party]] of committing a crime and called for an investigation.<ref name=\"BBC_News_3/20/2018\">{{cite web |title=Cambridge Analytica's Kenyan role queried |website=BBC News |date=20 March 2018 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43471707 | access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref> The Jubilee Party downplayed CA's role, saying it had hired the firm's parent company, to assist with branding.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cambridge Analytica's Kenyan role queried |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43471707 |accessdate=21 March 2018 |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Malta===\n\nIn its Disinformation and 'fake news' inquiry, published on 29 July 2018, the UK Parliament's [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]] noted that it is believed that CA, or its associated companies, worked with the [[Labour Party (Malta)|Labour Party]] in [[Malta]], on the [[2013 Maltese general election]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee |title=Disinformation and 'fake news': Interim Report |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201719/cmselect/cmcumeds/363/36309.htm#_idTextAnchor053}}</ref> Several sources claim that CA had close relationships with [[Henley & Partners]] who would immediately after the election introduce and run a lucrative Citizenship by Investment Program in Malta.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.imidaily.com/editors-picks/hpsclcambridge2/ |title= Henley & Partners Speaks Out on SCL, Cambridge Analytica, House of Commons Report\n |date=7 August 2018 |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Caribbean News Now! |title=UK parliamentary report calls for criminal investigation of Henley and SCL |url=https://www.dominicavibes.dm/international/print-248315/  |access-date=13 March 2020}}<!-- original url (no good archive copies found): https://wp.caribbeannewsnow.com/2018/07/30/uk-parliamentary-report-calls-for-criminal-investigation-of-henley-and-scl/ --></ref> The Maltese Government issued a press release denying the claims and calling the report and its sources \"[[fake news]]\".<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Government of Malta Department of Information  |title=PR181687: Statement by the Government of Malta: Government of Malta makes official representations regarding UK DCMS Committee report |url=https://www.gov.mt/en/Government/DOI/Press%20Releases/Pages/2018/July/30/pr181687.aspx}}</ref> Henley & Partners denied any wrongdoing. According to Henley & Partners, there was never a formal working relationship with CA.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/world/85644/passportsellers_henley_and_cambridge_analyticas_nix_exchanged_ideas_on_caribbean_election#.W-QmuieNzUI |title= Passport-sellers Henley and Cambridge Analytica's Nix 'exchanged ideas' on Caribbean election |date=28 March 2018 |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Final Report by the [[UK Parliament]]'s Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee, published on 18 February 2019, took note of the [[Maltese Government]]'s submissions (including through PR agency [[Chelgate]]'s services) but determined that compelling evidence shown to the Committee confirmed that:\n\n\"''SCL certainly had meetings in Malta, that [[Christian K\u00e4lin|Christian Kalin]] of Henley & Partners was introduced by SCL to [[Joseph Muscat]] in 2011, and that Christian Kalin met with both political parties before 2013''\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee |title=Disinformation and 'fake news': Final Report |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201719/cmselect/cmcumeds/1791/179110.htm#_idTextAnchor071}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maltese Government 2017\u20132022|Maltese Government]] later issued a further denial decrying the use of \"''unnamed sources''\" and \"''confidential documents''\".<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Government of Malta Department of Information |title=PR190309: Statement by the Government of Malta: Malta denies allegations in report by the Select Committee on Digital, Culture, Media and Sport |url=https://www.gov.mt/en/Government/DOI/Press%20Releases/Pages/2019/February/18/pr190309.aspx}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nAfter the [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal]], ''[[Forbes]]'' published that the British news program ''Channel 4 News'' had mentioned the existence of proof revealing ties between the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]] (PRI) and Cambridge Analytica, suggesting a ''[[modus operandi]]'' similar to the one in the United States. According to Channel 4 News' Guillermo Galdos, CA worked for the PRI at least until January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com.mx/cambridge-analytica-mexico-pri-enero-2018-channel-4-news/|title=Cambridge Analytica trabaj\u00f3 con el PRI: Channel 4 News|website=Forbes M\u00e9xico|date=30 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/opinion/javier-murillo/cambridge-analytica-sigan-la-ruta-del-dinero|title=Cambridge Analytica, sigan la ruta del dinero|first=Javier|last=Murillo|website=El Financiero}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/03/22/inenglish/1521710735_571195.html|title=The distorted online networks of Mexico's election campaign|first1=Fernando|last1=Peinado|first2=Elvira|last2=Palomo|first3=Javier|last3=Gal\u00e1n|date=22 March 2018|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds}}</ref> An investigation was requested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.proceso.com.mx/528182/exigen-al-inai-investigar-a-cambridge-analytica-facebook-y-desarrolladoras-de-apps-en-mexico|title=Exigen al INAI investigar a Cambridge Analytica, Facebook y desarrolladoras de Apps en M\u00e9xico|website=Proceso|date=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the company had reached out to the PRI, Mexico's ruling political party, in order to bolster the party's presidential campaign during the largest-ever political [[2018 Mexican general election|elections of 2018]]. The party decided that it was sufficiently equipped to mess with the election on its own, but still paid Cambridge Analytica to prevent it from working with rival parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/24/world/americas/mexico-election-cambridge-analytica.html|title=Mexico's Hardball Politics Get Even Harder as PRI Fights to Hold On to Power|access-date=1 July 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{further|Russian interference in the 2016 Brexit referendum|Unlawful campaigning in the 2016 EU referendum}}\n[[File:Cambridge Analytica protest Parliament Square1.jpg|thumb|A protest following the Cambridge Analytica scandal, 29 March 2018]]\nMany donors to the UK [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] reportedly have connections to the parent company of Cambridge Analytica.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/21/tory-donors-among-investors-in-cambridge-analytica-parent-firm-scl-group Tory donors among investors in Cambridge Analytica parent firm] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nCA became involved in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]] (Brexit) supporting \"persuadable\" voters to vote for leaving the [[European Union]] (EU).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/world/trump-calls-in-brexit-experts-to-target-voters-pf0hwcts9 |first=Rhys |last=Blakely |title=Data scientists target 20 million new voters for Trump |work=[[The Times]] |date=22 September 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 }}</ref> Articles by [[Carole Cadwalladr]] in ''[[The Observer]]'' and ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' newspapers, respectively published in February and May 2017, speculated in detail that CA had influenced both the [[Brexit]]/[[Vote Leave]] option in the UK's 2016 EU membership referendum and [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Trump's 2016 US presidential campaign]] with [[Robert Mercer]]'s backing of [[Donald Trump]] being key. They also discuss the legality of using the social data farmed.<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite news |last=Barnett |first=Anthony |url=http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2017/12/14/democracy-and-the-machinations-of-mind-control/ |title=Democracy and the Machinations of Mind Control |work=New York Review of Books |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=16 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/feb/26/robert-mercer-breitbart-war-on-media-steve-bannon-donald-trump-nigel-farage |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |title=Robert Mercer: the big data billionaire waging war on mainstream media |work=[[The Observer]] |date=26 February 2017 |accessdate=27 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/07/the-great-british-brexit-robbery-hijacked-democracy |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |title=The Great British Brexit robbery how our democracy was hijacked |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=7 May 2017 |accessdate=7 May 2017 }}</ref> CA is pursuing legal action over the claims made in Cadwalladr's articles.<ref name=\"Barnett\"/>\n\nNo campaign contributions, in cash or in kind, by Cambridge Analytica were reported to the UK electoral authorities. Both CA and [[Leave.EU]] refused to comment on any donation of services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/feb/26/us-billionaire-mercer-helped-back-brexit |title=Revealed: how US billionaire helped to back Brexit |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |date=26 February 2017 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> On 23 March 2018, it was reported that a former employee, [[Brittany Kaiser]], who was the company's former director of business development, revealed that the company misled the public and MPs over its links with Leave.EU and the analysis of data which had been provided by the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP). She said she felt she had lied by supporting Cambridge Analytica's company line that it had done \"no paid or unpaid work\" for Leave.EU. \"In my opinion, I was lying. In my opinion I felt like we should say, 'this is exactly what we did'\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/23/cambridge-analytica-misled-mps-over-work-for-leave-eu-says-ex-director-brittany-kaiser |title=Cambridge Analytica misled MPs over work for Leave.EU, says ex-director |work=[[The Guardian]] |author=Paul Lewis and Paul Hilder |date=23 March 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> The following day, it was reported that the company claimed that it would be able to affect the outcome of the Referendum and that it had produced a 10-page document headed \"Big Data Solutions for the EU Referendum\", claiming it could single out 'Brexiteers' among voters, donors, politicians and journalists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/cambridge-analytica-bragged-we-have-vast-data-for-brexit-vote-a3797441.html |title=Cambridge Analytica bragged: We have vast data for Brexit vote |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |author=Joe Murphy, Political Editor |date=24 March 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nDW reported in March 2018 that \"Whistleblower Christopher Wylie told UK lawmakers during a committee hearing on Tuesday that a firm linked to Cambridge Analytica helped the official Vote Leave campaign [the official pro-Brexit group headed by [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Michael Gove]]] circumvent campaign financing laws during the Brexit referendum.\"<ref>\"[http://www.dw.com/en/what-role-did-cambridge-analytica-play-in-the-brexit-vote/a-43151460 What role did Cambridge Analytica play in the Brexit vote?]\". ''Deutsche Welle.'' 27 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===United States===\nLaurence Levy, a lawyer with the law firm [[Bracewell & Giuliani]], advises [[Rebekah Mercer]], [[Steve Bannon]], and [[Alexander Nix]] on the legality of their company, Cambridge Analytica, being involved in [[Elections in the United States]]. He advises that Nix and any foreign nationals without a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]] working for the company must not be involved in any decision making regarding any work the company performs for any clients related to [[U.S. elections]].  He further advises Nix to recuse himself from any involvement with the company's U.S. election work because he is not a [[U.S. citizen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Participation in US Elections |url=http://msnbcmedia.msn.com/i/TODAY/z_Creative/LEVY_MEMO_DM_4636592_v1_Memo_re__Participation_in_US_Elections.pdf |date=22 July 2014 |access-date=23 March 2018 |last=Levy |first=Laurence |via=[[MSNBC]] |publisher=[[Bracewell & Giuliani|Bracewell & Giuliani LLP]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402031730/http://msnbcmedia.msn.com/i/TODAY/z_Creative/LEVY_MEMO_DM_4636592_v1_Memo_re__Participation_in_US_Elections.pdf |archive-date=2 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/wylie-foreigners-worked-cambridge-analytica-nc-senate-campaign-n859526 |title=Wylie: Foreigners worked for Cambridge Analytica on NC Senate campaign |work=NBC News|access-date=23 March 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====2014 midterm elections====\nCA had entered the US market in 2012<ref name= wp/> (or 2013),<ref name=issenberg/> and was involved in 44 [[United States Congress|US congressional]], [[United States Senate|US Senate]] and state-level elections in the [[2014 United States elections|2014 US elections]].<ref name=\"wp\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cruz-campaign-paid-750000-to-psychographic-profiling-company/2015/10/19/6c83e508-743f-11e5-9cbb-790369643cf9_story.html |title=Cruz campaign paid $750,000 to 'psychographic profiling' company |last=Sellers |first=Frances Stead |authorlink=Frances Stead Sellers |date=19 October 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |issn=0190-8286| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe company worked with the [[John R. Bolton#John Bolton Super PAC|John Bolton Super PAC]] (political action committee) on a major digital and TV campaign focused on senate races in [[2014 United States Senate election in Arkansas|Arkansas]], [[2014 United States Senate election in North Carolina|North Carolina]] and [[2014 United States Senate election in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] and helped turn out voters for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] candidates in those states. Two of the Republican candidates backed by the Bolton Super PAC, [[Thom Tillis]] in North Carolina and [[Tom Cotton]] in Arkansas, won their Senate bids, while [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] lost in New Hampshire. The PAC ran 15 different TV advertisements each in North Carolina and Arkansas and 17 in New Hampshire, mostly online with some targeted directly to households using [[Dish Network]] and [[DirecTV]]. All were intended to push Bolton's national security agenda.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/campaign-trail/hyped-data-firm-s-promise-tested-iowa/302412 |title=Much-Hyped Data Firm's Promise Could Be Tested in Iowa |work=Advertising Age| access-date = 26 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nCA also supported [[Thom Tillis]]'s successful campaign to oust [[Kay Hagan]] as a senator for North Carolina. The firm was credited for its role in identifying a sizeable cluster of North Carolinians who prioritised foreign affairs, which encouraged Tillis to shift the conversation from state-level debates over education policy to charges that incumbent Kay Hagan had failed to take [[ISIS]]'s rise seriously.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/features/2015-11-12/is-the-republican-party-s-killer-data-app-for-real |title=Cruz-Connected Data Miner Aims to Get Inside U.S. Voters' Heads |website=Bloomberg.com | access-date = 26 February 2016}}</ref> Tillis's campaign and the [[North Carolina Republican Party]] paid Cambridge Analytica $345,000 for these services.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Brian |last2=Bonner |first2=Lynn |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/politics-columns-blogs/under-the-dome/article205946479.html |title=Tillis and NC Republicans paid $345,000 to the data firm that's now banned from Facebook |work=The News & Observer |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nCA sent dozens of non-U.S. citizens to provide campaign strategy and messaging advice to Republican candidates in 2014, opening the firm and individuals to prosecution under the [[Foreign Agents Registration Act]], for being foreign agents having not registered through the [[United States Department of Justice]] as such.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/former-cambridge-analytica-workers-say-firm-sent-foreigners-to-advise-us-campaigns/2018/03/25/6a0d7d90-2fa2-11e8-911f-ca7f68bff0fc_story.html |title=Former Cambridge Analytica workers say firm sent foreigners to advise U.S. campaigns |last=Timberg |first=Craig |date=25 March 2018 |work=Washington Post|access-date=26 March 2018 |last2=Hamburger |first2=Tom |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n====2016 presidential election====\n{{further|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)}}\nCA's involvement in the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries]] became known in July 2015.<ref name=politico/> As of December 2015, CA claimed to have collected up to 5,000 data points on over 220 million Americans.<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web |url=https://cambridgeanalytica.org/about |title=About Us |publisher=Cambridge Analytica |accessdate=27 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216023554/https://cambridgeanalytica.org/about |archivedate=16 February 2016 }}</ref> At that time [[Robert Mercer (businessman)|Robert Mercer]] was a major supporter of [[Ted Cruz]].<ref name=issenberg/><ref name=\"nyt0415\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/11/us/politics/hedge-fund-magnaterobert-mercer-emerges-as-a-generous-backer-of-ted-cruz.html |last1=Lichtblau |first1=E |last2=Stevenson |first2=A |title=Hedge-Fund Magnate Robert Mercer Emerges as a Generous Backer of Cruz |work=The New York Times |date=10 April 2015 |accessdate=6 February 2016 }}</ref> The Mercer family funded CA directly and indirectly through several [[super-PACs]] as well as through payments via Cruz's campaign.<ref name= guardian/>\n\nCruz became an early major client of CA in the 2016 presidential campaign. Just prior to the [[2016 Iowa Republican caucuses|Iowa Republican caucuses]], the Cruz campaign had spent $3&nbsp;million for CA's services,<ref name=\"guardian2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/01/ted-cruz-trump-iowa-caucus-voter-targeting |author=Harry Davies |title=Ted Cruz erased Trump's Iowa lead by spending millions on voter targeting |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=7 February 2016 }}</ref> with additional money coming from allied Super-PACs.<ref name=guardian2/> After Cruz's win at the Iowa caucus CA was credited with having been able to identify and motivate potential voters.<ref name=\"bloomberg2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2016-02-02/how-ted-cruz-engineered-his-iowa-triumph |author=Sasha Issenberg |title=How Ted Cruz Engineered His Iowa Triumph |work=Bloomberg.com |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cambridge-analytica-congratulates-senator-ted-cruz-on-iowa-caucus-win-300213608.html |title=Cambridge Analytica Congratulates Senator Ted Cruz on Iowa Caucus Win |agency=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 }}</ref> Ultimately the Cruz campaign spent $5.8&nbsp;million on work by CA.<ref name=adage/>\n\n[[Ben Carson]] was a second client of CA; [[Ben Carson 2016 presidential campaign|his campaign]] had paid $220,000 for \"data management\" and \"web service\" as reported in October 2015.<ref name=\"wpost\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cruz-campaign-paid-750000-to-psychographic-profiling-company/2015/10/19/6c83e508-743f-11e5-9cbb-790369643cf9_story.html |first=Frances Stead |last=Sellers |title=Cruz campaign paid $750,000 to 'psychographic profiling' company |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=7 February 2016 }}</ref> [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign|Marco Rubio's campaign]] was supported by [[Optimus Consulting]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.campaignsandelections.com/campaign-insider/2646/organization-and-analytics-help-take-down-trump-in-iowa |first1=Sean J. |last=Miller |title=Organization and Analytics Help Take Down Trump in Iowa |work=CampaignsandElections.com |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=23 February 2016 }}</ref> Meanwhile, the third competitor, Governor [[John Kasich]], was supported by rivalling firm [[Applecart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-11-24/a-new-data-mining-technique-to-uncover-new-hampshire-influencers |title=Data-Mining Firm Searches for Voters by Combing High School Yearbooks |work=Bloomberg.com }}</ref>\n\nAfter Cruz dropped out of the race for the Republican presidential nomination in May 2016, Robert Mercer and his daughter Rebekah Mercer started to support Trump.<ref name=\"nr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/438739/trump-campaigns-data-firm-partner-cambridge-analytica-worked-cruz |first=Eliana |last=Johnson |title=The GOP nominee makes a late attempt at data-driven targeted messaging |work=[[National Review]] |date=5 August 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 }}</ref> In August, it became known that CA followed their allegiance and worked for Trump's presidential campaign.<ref name= adage/><ref name=nr/> Trump's campaign also worked with digital firm [[Giles-Parscale|Giles Parscale]].<ref name=\"adage\">{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/campaign-trail/trump-spending-cambridge-peanuts/305597/ |author=Kate Kaye |title=Trump Spending With Cambridge Analytica Looks Like Peanuts Compared to Cruz |work=Advertising Age |date=24 August 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 }}</ref> In September, the Trump campaign spent $5&nbsp;million to purchase television advertising.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/us/politics/cambridge-analytica.html |first1=Nicholas |last1=Confessore |first2=Danny |last2=Hakim |title=Data Firm Says 'Secret Sauce' Aided Trump; Many Scof |work=The New York Times |date=6 March 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2017 }}</ref> The Trump campaign spent less than $1&nbsp;million in data work.<ref name=\"opensecrets\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/pres16/expenditures?id=n00023864 |author=OpenSecrets \u2013 FEC |title=Top Vendors/Recipients |publisher=[[OpenSecrets]]/[[Federal Election Commission|FEC]] }}</ref>{{failed verification|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2016, the company said that it had not used psychographics in the Trump presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/us/politics/cambridge-analytica.html |title=Data Firm Says 'Secret Sauce' Aided Trump; Many Scoff |work=The New York Times |date=6 March 2017 }}</ref> Cambridge Analytica targeted potential voters with bespoke messages. Cambridge Analytica's data head, Alexander Tayler said, \"When you think about the fact that Donald Trump lost the popular vote by 3m votes but won the electoral college vote, [t]hat's down to the data and the research.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/22/us-politics-data-cambridge-analytica-russia-trump The poison in politics runs deeper than dodgy data] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nThe head of Cambridge Analytica said he asked [[WikiLeaks]] founder, [[Julian Assange]], for help finding [[Hillary Clinton]]'s 33,000 [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|deleted emails]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/367141-congressional-investigators-find-irregularities-in-fbis-handling-of |title=Congressional investigators find irregularities in FBI's handling of Clinton email case |first=Brandon |last=Conradis |date=2 January 2018 |publisher=The Hill }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-data-guru-i-tried-to-team-up-with-julian-assange |title=Trump Data Guru: I Tried to Team Up With Julian Assange |last=Woodruff |first=Betsy |date=25 October 2017 |work=The Daily Beast|access-date=25 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/25/politics/cambridge-analytica-julian-assange-wikileaks-clinton-emails/index.html |title=Trump campaign analytics company contacted WikiLeaks about Clinton emails |author1=Kara Scannell |author2=Dana Bash |author3=Marshall Cohen |publisher=CNN|access-date=25 October 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2017, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported that the [[US Congress]] was investigating CA in connection with [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]. The report alleges that CA may have coordinated the spread of Russian propaganda using its microtargetting capabilities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/4783932/inside-russia-social-media-war-america/ |title=Inside Russia's Social Media War on America |website=Time }}</ref> According to the Trump campaign's digital operations chief, CA worked \"side-by-side\" with representatives from Facebook, [[Alphabet Inc.]] and [[Twitter]] on Trump's digital campaign activities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/14/brad-parscale-trump-digital-house-intel-committee-240557 |title=Trump campaign's digital director agrees to meet with House Intel Committee |publisher=Politico }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2017, [[Michael Flynn]], who is under investigation by US counterintelligence for his contacts with Russian officials, amended a public financial filing to reflect that he had served in an advisory role in an agreement with CA during the 2016 Trump campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-eyes-michael-flynns-links-to-russia-1485134942 |title=U.S. Eyes Michael Flynn's Links to Russia |first1=Carol E. |last1=Lee |first2=Devlin |last2=Barrett |first3=Shane |last3=Harris |date=23 January 2017 |via=The Wall Street Journal }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2017, [[Brad Parscale]], who was the digital media director for Trump's 2016 presidential campaign, stated in an interview with [[Lesley Stahl]] from [[CBS News]] on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' that Parscale was able to utilize Facebook advertising to directly target individual voters in [[swing states]].<ref name=\"CBSNews\">{{Cite news|last=Stahl|first=Lesley|title=Parscale: TV news \"thought I was a joke\"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/parscale-tv-news-thought-i-was-a-joke/|work=CBS News|date=8 October 2017|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Parscale cited the example in which he was able to target specific universes (audiences) who care about infrastructure and promote Trump and his message to build back up the crumbling American infrastructure.<ref name=\"SecretWeapon\">{{Cite news|title=Secret Weapon|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/secret-weapon/|work=CBS News|date=8 October 2017|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Although he hired Cambridge Analytica to assist with [[microtargeting]], and Cambridge Analytica stated that it was the key to Trump's victory, Parscale denied that he gained assistance from the firm, stating that he thought Cambridge Analytica's use of psychographics doesn't work.<ref name=\"Stahl\">{{cite news |last=Stahl|first=Lesley|title= Facebook \"embeds,\" Russia and the Trump campaign's secret weapon|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-embeds-russia-and-the-trump-campaigns-secret-weapon/|work=CBS News|date=8 October 2017|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> He also denied any assistance with links to Russia.<ref name=Stahl/> According to Parscale, the [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|Clinton campaign]] turned down assistance from these platforms.<ref name=Stahl/>\n\nOn 25 October 2017, Assange said on Twitter that he had been approached by Cambridge Analytica, but that he had rejected its proposal.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=JulianAssange |number=923226553428987904 |title=I can confirm an approach by Cambridge Analytica and can confirm that it was rejected by WikiLeaks. |name=Julian Assange&nbsp; |date=25 October 2017}}</ref> Assange's tweet followed a story in ''[[The Daily Beast]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-data-guru-i-tried-to-team-up-with-julian-assange |title=Trump Data Guru: I Tried to Team Up With Julian Assange |first=Betsy |last=Woodruff |date=25 October 2017 |via=thedailybeast.com }}</ref> alleging that Cambridge Analytica chief executive Alexander Nix had proposed a collaboration with Wikileaks to find the 33,000 emails that had been deleted from Clinton's private server. [[CNN]] said it had been told by several unnamed sources<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/27/politics/trump-campaign-wikileaks-cambridge-analytica/index.html |title=Trump. Cambridge Analytica. WikiLeaks. The connections, explained. |first=Marshall |last=Cohen |publisher=CNN }}</ref> that Nix intended to turn the Clinton email archive released to the public by the [[United States Department of State|State Department]] into a searchable database for the campaign or a pro-Trump [[political action committee]].\n\nOn 14 December 2017, it was revealed that [[Robert Mueller]] had requested during the fall of 2017 that Cambridge Analytica turn over the emails of any of its employees who worked on the Trump campaign, as part of his [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mueller-sought-emails-of-trump-campaign-data-firm-1513296899 |title=Mueller Sought Emails of Trump Campaign Data Firm |last=Ballhaus |first=Rebecca |date=15 December 2017 |work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=15 December 2017 |issn=0099-9660 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, following disclosures that the company had improperly used the personal information of over 50 million Facebook users while working on Trump's presidential campaign, ''[[The Times of Israel]]'' reported that the company had used what Nix had called \"intelligence gathering\" from [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[State of Israel|Israeli]] companies as part of their efforts to influence the election results in Trump's favor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump campaign mined Facebook user data using Israeli 'intelligence gathering' |accessdate=21 March 2018 |work=The Times of Israel |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/trump-campaign-mined-facebook-user-data-using-israeli-intelligence-gathering/}}</ref>\n\n===Other countries===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2018}}\nCambridge Analytica's executives said in 2018 that the company had worked in more than 200 elections around the world, including in [[Trinidad and Tobago]], [[Nigeria]], the [[Czech Republic]], and [[Argentina]].<ref name=\"dailynation\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/How-Cambridge-Analytica-influenced-Kenyan-poll/1064-4349034-le7xbuz/index.html |title=Revealed: Cambridge Analytica says it worked for Uhuru |work=[[Daily Nation]] |date=20 March 2018 |location=Kenya | access-date=}}</ref> During the investigation it was admitted that the company has been contacted from a famous italian party to manage the electoral campaign in [[Italy]] but the name of the party was not revealed. \n\nIn the [[Philippines]], Cambridge Analytica was also involved in the 2016 presidential election with reports citing it helped [[Rodrigo Duterte]] win the race.<ref>{{cite web | last=Robles | first=Raissa | title=How Cambridge Analytica's parent company helped 'man of action' Rodrigo Duterte win the 2016 Philippines election | website=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=12 April 2018 | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/2140303/how-cambridge-analyticas-parent-company-helped-man-action | access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> Duterte's camp denied this association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/10/18/palace-denies-cambridge-analytica-involved-in-duterte-campaign|title=Palace denies Cambridge Analytica involved in Duterte campaign|last=Placido|first=Dharel|date=10 April 2018|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> The [[SCL Group]], Cambridge Analytica's parent company, claimed that it rebranded the politician's image to target voters who they found are swayed by qualities such as toughness and decisiveness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/cambridge-analytica-duterte-tough-guy-image-for-presidential-election-2018-4|title=Cambridge Analytica's parent company claimed it invented the tough guy image that got Rodrigo Duterte elected|last=Perper|first=Rosie|date=6 April 2018|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> During the election cycle, Facebook confirmed that its data of more 1 million Filipino users were improperly shared with the communications company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/199599-facebook-data-scandal-cambridge-analytica-help-duterte-win-philippine-elections|title=Did Cambridge Analytica use Filipinos' Facebook data to help Duterte win?|last=Gutierrez|first=Natashya|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2020, a release of more than 100,000 documents showed how Cambridge Analytica worked in 68 countries. A global infrastructure with operations to manipulate voters on \"an industrial scale\". The release of documents began on New Year\u2019s Day from an anonymous Twitter account called @HindsightFiles, that published material on elections in Malaysia, Kenya and Brazil (and next days so more countries). This documents came from Brittany Kaiser, an ex-Cambridge Analytica employee turned whistleblower, and were retrieved from her email accounts and hard drives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cadwalladr |first1=Carole |title=Fresh Cambridge Analytica leak 'shows global manipulation is out of control' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/04/cambridge-analytica-data-leak-global-election-manipulation |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Observer |publisher=The Guardian |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order and add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Data Propria]]\n* [[Catalist]]\n* [[Data dredging]]\n* [[The Groundwork]]\n* [[Herd behaviour]]\n* [[ORCA (computer system)]]\n* [[Project Alamo]]\n* [[Project Houdini]]\n* [[Project Narwhal]]\n* [[Predictive analytics]]\n* [[Right-wing politics]]\n* [[Sam Patten (political consultant)]]\n* [[Social media analytics]]\n* [[Tech companies in the New York metropolitan area]]\n* ''[[The Great Hack]]''\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Companies|United Kingdom|United States|Politics}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170710031857/https://cambridgeanalytica.org/ Archived website]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/news/series/cambridge-analytica-files The Cambridge Analytica Files], ongoing investigative reporting from ''[[The Observer]]''/''[[The Guardian]]'', beginning 17 March 2018, part of [https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/cambridge-analytica News: Cambridge Analytica] beginning a year earlier\n* [https://www.channel4.com/news/data-democracy-and-dirty-tricks-cambridge-analytica-uncovered-investigation-expose Data, Democracy and Dirty Tricks], [[Channel 4]]\n\n[[Category:Cambridge Analytica]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2018 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct technology companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Technology companies disestablished in 2018]]\n[[Category:Big data companies]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Data management]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Facebook]]\n[[Category:Political campaign techniques]]\n[[Category:Political campaign technology]]\n[[Category:Prediction]]\n[[Category:Transaction processing]]\n[[Category:2016 United Kingdom European Union member